{"title_page": "Montijo (parish)", "text_new": "{{Infobox Portuguese subdivision \n|type = parish \n| name                    = Montijo\n| image_skyline           = Montijo (60097524).jpg\n| image_caption           = The main square of Montijo by twilight\n| image_flag              = \n| image_shield            = \n|region             = [[Lisboa Region|Lisbon]]\n|metro              = [[Lisbon metropolitan area|Lisbon]]\n|district           = [[Set\u00fabal District|Set\u00fabal]]\n|municipality       = [[Montijo, Portugal|Montijo]]\n| coordinates             = {{coord|38|42|N|8|58|W|display=inline,title}}\n| area_total_km2          = 27.25\n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| population_total        = 29908\n| postal_code             = 2870-114\n| area_code               = 212\n| dissolved               = 2013\n}}\n'''Montijo''' is a former [[Freguesia (Portugal)|civil parish]] in the municipality of [[Montijo, Portugal|Montijo]], central [[Portugal]]. In 2013, the parish merged into the new parish [[Montijo e Afonsoeiro]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Law nr. 11-A/2013, page 552 78|url=http://dre.pt/pdf1sdip/2013/01/01901/0000200147.pdf |accessdate=28 July 2014|author=''[[Di\u00e1rio da Rep\u00fablica]]''|language=Portuguese|format=pdf}}</ref> The population in 2011 was 29,908,<ref>[http://www.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xlang=en&xpid=INE&xpgid=ine_indicadores&indOcorrCod=0005889&contexto=pi&selTab=tab0 Instituto Nacional de Estat\u00edstica]</ref> in an area of {{convert|27.25|km2|mi2}}&nbsp;km\u00b2.<ref>[http://epp.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/portal/page/portal/nuts_nomenclature/documents/PT-LAU.xls Eurostat]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Parishes of Montijo, Portugal]]\n[[Category:Former parishes of Portugal]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Portuguese subdivision \n|type = parish \n| name                    = Montijo\n| image_skyline           = Montijo (60097524).jpg\n| image_caption           = The main square of Montijo by twilight\n| image_flag              = \n| image_shield            = \n|region             = [[Lisboa Region|Lisbon]]\n|metro              = [[Lisbon metropolitan area|Lisbon]]\n|district           = [[Set\u00fabal District|Set\u00fabal]]\n|municipality       = [[Montijo, Portugal|Montijo]]\n| coordinates             = {{coord|38|42|N|8|58|W|display=inline,title}}\n| area_total_km2          = 27.25\n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| population_total        = 29908\n| postal_code             = 2870-114\n| area_code               = 212\n| dissolved               = 2013\n}}\n'''Montijo''' is a former [[Freguesia (Portugal)|civil parish]] in the municipality of [[Montijo, Portugal|Montijo]], central [[Portugal]]. In 2013, the parish merged into the new parish [[Montijo e Afonsoeiro]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Law nr. 11-A/2013, page 552 78|url=http://dre.pt/pdf1sdip/2013/01/01901/0000200147.pdf |accessdate=28 July 2014|author=''[[Di\u00e1rio da Rep\u00fablica]]''|language=Portuguese|format=pdf}}</ref> The population in 2011 was 29,908,<ref>[http://www.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xlang=en&xpid=INE&xpgid=ine_indicadores&indOcorrCod=0005889&contexto=pi&selTab=tab0 Instituto Nacional de Estat\u00edstica]</ref> in an area of {{convert|27.25|km2|mi2}}&nbsp;km\u00b2.<ref>[http://epp.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/portal/page/portal/nuts_nomenclature/documents/PT-LAU.xls Eurostat]</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Parishes of Montijo, Portugal]]\n[[Category:Former parishes of Portugal]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Montijo_(parish)"}
{"title_page": "Wiener Au\u00dfenring Autobahn", "text_new": "{{Infobox road \n|country=AUT\n|type=A\n|route=21\n|alternate_name=Wiener Au\u00dfenring Autobahn\n|map=Karte A21 AT.svg\n|e-road={{jct|country=AUT|E|60}}\n|length_km=38.2\n|terminus_a={{jct|country=AUT|A|1}} in [[Altlengbach]]\n|junction=\n|terminus_b={{jct|country=AUT|A|2}}, {{jct|country=AUT|S|1}} in [[V\u00f6sendorf]]\n|states= [[Lower Austria]], [[Vienna]]\n|previous_type=A\n|previous_route=14\n|next_type=A\n|next_route=22\n}}\nThe '''Wiener Au\u00dfenring Autobahn''' A 21 (also ''[[Alland|Allander]] Autobahn'') is a motorway in Austria and part of the [[European route E60]]. It connects the [[West Autobahn]] (A 1) at the Steinh\u00e4usl interchange with the [[S\u00fcd Autobahn]] (A 2) at the [[V\u00f6sendorf]] interchange, where it continues as the [[Wiener Au\u00dfenring Schnellstra\u00dfe]] (S 1).\n\nIn the future, the Wiener Au\u00dfenring Autobahn, in conjunction with other expressways and motorways, will form part of the so-called regional ring around Vienna.\n\n== Description ==\nThe A 21 has six lanes between the V\u00f6sendorf interchange and [[Brunn am Gebirge]]. The further route to the Steinh\u00e4usl interchange is basically four lanes, but in gradient areas there is an additional slow lane.\n\nThe two sections of the A 21 at Steinh\u00e4usl and [[Gie\u00dfh\u00fcbl]], with a maximum grade of 5.2%, are among the steepest sections of the Austrian motorway network. Several times a year, when snow falls in eastern Austria, [[snow chains]] have to be made compulsory for [[Truck|trucks]], or the highway has to be completely closed to trucks.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Weibachautobahn.jpg|left|thumb|Warehouse at the motorway construction site in Weissenbach bei M\u00f6dling]]\n[[File:Steinh\u00e4usl.jpg|left|thumb|Knoten Steinh\u00e4usl]]\nThe Wiener Au\u00dfenring Autobahn was already planned in the 1930s. The construction of the valley crossings had already begun in 1940. Thus, for example, in Weissenbach or Sittendorf barracks were set up, initially housing regular construction workers, but later serving as accommodation for prisoners of war. Thus, in the Sittendorfer camp, originally relatively well-paid workers from Vienna and the Burgenland, but also from Germany, were housed. In September 1941 Ukrainians came to this camp and were trained as soldiers. Later, prisoners from France and later Serbia came to the camp. The camp housed up to 250 inmates. In 1942, [[typhoid fever]] broke out and claimed numerous victims. After the barracks briefly served as a warehouse for aircraft parts from the Seegrotte, their usage was stopped in the war turmoil like all other construction sites.<ref>[[Nieder\u00f6sterreichische Nachrichten]] on the occasion of the construction of the \"Barackendenkmal\" 2007</ref> Another camp was located on the ''Fischerwiese'' in [[Klausen-Leopoldsdorf]], where [[Romani people|Roma]] were also imprisoned, who had to work as forced laborers on the highway.<ref>Heribert Artinger: ''Chronik der Freistadt Rust, 1850-1950: Tagebuch der kleinsten Stadt \u00d6sterreichs mit eigenem Statut''. </ref> In 1938, a barrack camp was built in Sittendorf, which originally served for the workers and later French prisoners of war, as well as for Serbian forced laborers. Today, a plaque commemorates the place of remembrance in the barracks camp and at the Sittendorf cemetery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://iehi.eu/index.php/component/content/article/128-erinnerungsort-barackenlager-sittendorf|title=Erinnerungsort Barackenlager Sittendorf|last=|first=|date=|website=iehi.eu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}} </ref>\n\nAfter the war, land already exchanged or replaced fell into Soviet hands as German property and only returned to the Republic of Austria after the [[Austrian State Treaty|State Treaty]] in 1955.\n\nOther route variants were also considered before the further construction. One variant, for example, was to make the A 21 run more southwards from Alland. However, since the [[Helenental]], a narrow valley, would have been too badly affected, this variant was dropped again. It was only in the area of [[Heiligenkreuz, Lower Austria|Heiligenkreuz]] that the route was moved further away from the village, so as not to affect the [[Heiligenkreuz Abbey]]. In addition, a large part of the land necessary for the construction had already been sold; thus, the further construction was not started until 1964.\n\nOn the first section opened in 1962 between the [[V\u00f6sendorf]] interchange and [[Brunn am Gebirge]], only one directional roadway was available. It was only passable in both directions from 1968 onwards. The last sections between [[Mayerling]] and [[Hinterbr\u00fchl]] were completed in 1982. Furthermore, the highway was planned to continue to Schwechat, where it would become the [[Ost Autobahn|A 4]]. This section was realized in the form of the [[Wiener Au\u00dfenring Schnellstra\u00dfe|S 1]] expressway, which opened in 2006.\n\nSoon after the opening of the continuous motorway, a rest area was to be built at the location of today's Hinterbr\u00fchl rest stop. After partial resistance from the local population, who feared that their habitat would be adversely affected, the plan was dropped and the rest area was built in Alland instead.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! style=\"background:#276FB7\" |<span style=\"color:white\"> Opening </span>\n! style=\"background:#276FB7\" |<span style=\"color:white\">Section</span>\n! style=\"background:#276FB7\" |<span style=\"color:white\"> Length</span>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |19.12.1962\n| align=\"center\" |ASt Brunn/Gebirge - Knoten V\u00f6sendorf (right carriageway)\n| align=\"center\" |2.116 km\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |11.04.1968\n| align=\"center\" |ASt Brunn/Gebirge - Knoten V\u00f6sendorf (left carriageway)\n| align=\"center\" |2.116 km\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |24.09.1971\n| align=\"center\" |Knoten Steinh\u00e4usl - Klausen-Leopoldsdorf\n| align=\"center\" |13.200 km\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |07.10.1977\n| align=\"center\" |Klausen-Leopoldsdorf - ASt Mayerling\n| align=\"center\" |4.017 km\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |24.10.1980\n| align=\"center\" |ASt Hinterbr\u00fchl - ASt Brunn/Gebirge\n| align=\"center\" |10.442 km\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |29.09.1982\n| align=\"center\" |ASt Heiligenkreuz - ASt Hinterbr\u00fchl\n| align=\"center\" |3.031 km\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |29.09.1982\n| align=\"center\" |ASt Mayerling - ASt Heiligenkreuz (left carriageway)\n| align=\"center\" |5.437 km\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |29.10.1982\n| align=\"center\" |ASt Mayerling - ASt Heiligenkreuz (right carriageway)\n| align=\"center\" |5.437 km\n|-\n|}\n\n== Accidents ==\nOn the night of 22 February 2010, a German coach bus traveling towards Steinh\u00e4usl collided with a truck in front of it. Six people were killed, ten seriously injured, and twenty slightly injured.  Temperatures around the freezing point made it difficult to use emergency services on the closed motorway.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://diepresse.com/home/panorama/oesterreich/541435/NOe_Busunfall-auf-A21-fordert-sechs-Todesopfer|title=N\u00d6: Busunfall auf A21 fordert sechs Todesopfer|last=|first=|date=|website=Die Presse|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615214757/http://diepresse.com/home/panorama/oesterreich/541435/NOe_Busunfall-auf-A21-fordert-sechs-Todesopfer|archive-date=15 June 2018|access-date=15 April 2020}} </ref><ref>[http://noe122.noet.at/filearchive/517b8607b76d14c5f957bba91a7e2790.pdf Die Trag\u00f6die auf der A{{NNBSP}}21] in Brandaus von 3/2010 (PDF)</ref>\n\n== Problems ==\nOn 2 December 2010, after heavy snowfall, 80 trucks were stuck on the A 21 and the entire highway was closed for five hours. After heavy snowfalls, the A 21 had to be closed on 1 December 2016 at the Steinh\u00e4usl interchange, because trucks got stuck there despite having winter equipment. One reason was the gradient of more than 5% there.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heute.at/s/-23244842|title=Wintereinbruch sorgte f\u00fcr Chaos auf A21 - Nieder\u00f6sterreich|website=Heute.at|language=de|access-date=2019-11-02}}</ref> On 19 April 2017, after heavy snowfall, the A 21 was closed again because several trucks and many cars that were already on summer tires got stuck on the A 21 for hours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fireworld.at/2017/04/21/noe-schnee-chaos-auf-der-a21-teil-2-feuerwehren-die-nacht-hindurch-im-einsatz/|title=N\u00f6: Schnee-Chaos auf der A21 Teil 2 \u2192 Feuerwehren die Nacht hindurch im Einsatz|last=Zukrigl|first=Gerald|date=2017-04-21|website=Fireworld.at|language=de-DE|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The [[ASFiNAG|ASFINAG]] responded to the criticism that they had responded too late to the snowfall by stating that they had sent the snowploughs on the road hours before the onset of the strongest snowfall. Crossed trucks and the failure to form the emergency lane (''Rettungsgasse'') by drivers would have made it impossible to get through with the snow plows.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://noe.orf.at/v2/news/stories/2762936/|title=A21 nach Schneechaos stundenlang gesperrt|date=2016-03-15|website=noe.orf.at|language=de|access-date=2019-11-02}}</ref> In a statement issued on 20 April 2017, Infrastructure Minister Leichtfried announced that the winter tires requirement for trucks would be extended until 15 May.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kurier.at/chronik/niederoesterreich/lenker-ueben-kritik-an-der-asfinag-nach-schneechaos-auf-a21/259.507.337|title=Lenker \u00fcben Kritik an der Asfinag nach Schneechaos auf A21|website=kurier.at|language=de|access-date=2019-11-02}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* Bernd Kreuzer: ''Der Bau der Autobahnen und Schnellstra\u00dfe in \u00d6sterreich.'' \u2013 In: ASFINAG (Hrsg.): ''[https://www.asfinag.at/media/1510/de_buch-30-jahre-asfinag.pdf Das Autobahnnetz in \u00d6sterreich. 30 Jahre Asfinag].'' \u2013 Vienna, 2012, S. 99\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://motorways-exitlists.com/europe/a/a21.htm Wiener Au\u00dfenring Autobahn in motorways-exitlists.com]\n* [https://www.asfinag.at/documents/10180/13369/de_Buch+30+Jahre+ASFINAG.pdf/8af1a7eb-9bda-4f3c-86a9-81181d4bacb9 30 Jahre \u201eAllander\u201c Autobahn \u2013 die A 21 feiert Geburtstag- Asfinag]\n\n{{Autobahn system in Austria}}\n[[Category:Roads in Europe]]\n[[Category:Sankt P\u00f6lten-Land District]]\n[[Category:M\u00f6dling District]]\n[[Category:Baden District, Austria]]\n[[Category:Autobahns in Austria]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox road \n|country=AUT\n|type=A\n|route=21\n|alternate_name=Wiener Au\u00dfenring Autobahn\n|map=Karte A21 AT.svg\n|e-road={{jct|country=AUT|E|60}}\n|length_km=38.2\n|terminus_a={{jct|country=AUT|A|1}} in [[Altlengbach]]\n|junction=\n|terminus_b={{jct|country=AUT|A|2}}, {{jct|country=AUT|S|1}} in [[V\u00f6sendorf]]\n|states= [[Lower Austria]], [[Vienna]]\n|previous_type=A\n|previous_route=14\n|next_type=A\n|next_route=23\n}}\nThe '''Wiener Au\u00dfenring Autobahn''' A 21 (also ''[[Alland|Allander]] Autobahn'') is a motorway in Austria and part of the [[European route E60]]. It connects the [[West Autobahn]] (A 1) at the Steinh\u00e4usl interchange with the [[S\u00fcd Autobahn]] (A 2) at the [[V\u00f6sendorf]] interchange, where it continues as the [[Wiener Au\u00dfenring Schnellstra\u00dfe]] (S 1).\n\nIn the future, the Wiener Au\u00dfenring Autobahn, in conjunction with other expressways and motorways, will form part of the so-called regional ring around Vienna.\n\n== Description ==\nThe A 21 has six lanes between the V\u00f6sendorf interchange and [[Brunn am Gebirge]]. The further route to the Steinh\u00e4usl interchange is basically four lanes, but in gradient areas there is an additional slow lane.\n\nThe two sections of the A 21 at Steinh\u00e4usl and [[Gie\u00dfh\u00fcbl]], with a maximum grade of 5.2%, are among the steepest sections of the Austrian motorway network. Several times a year, when snow falls in eastern Austria, [[snow chains]] have to be made compulsory for [[Truck|trucks]], or the highway has to be completely closed to trucks.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Weibachautobahn.jpg|left|thumb|Warehouse at the motorway construction site in Weissenbach bei M\u00f6dling]]\n[[File:Steinh\u00e4usl.jpg|left|thumb|Knoten Steinh\u00e4usl]]\nThe Wiener Au\u00dfenring Autobahn was already planned in the 1930s. The construction of the valley crossings had already begun in 1940. Thus, for example, in Weissenbach or Sittendorf barracks were set up, initially housing regular construction workers, but later serving as accommodation for prisoners of war. Thus, in the Sittendorfer camp, originally relatively well-paid workers from Vienna and the Burgenland, but also from Germany, were housed. In September 1941 Ukrainians came to this camp and were trained as soldiers. Later, prisoners from France and later Serbia came to the camp. The camp housed up to 250 inmates. In 1942, [[typhoid fever]] broke out and claimed numerous victims. After the barracks briefly served as a warehouse for aircraft parts from the Seegrotte, their usage was stopped in the war turmoil like all other construction sites.<ref>[[Nieder\u00f6sterreichische Nachrichten]] on the occasion of the construction of the \"Barackendenkmal\" 2007</ref> Another camp was located on the ''Fischerwiese'' in [[Klausen-Leopoldsdorf]], where [[Romani people|Roma]] were also imprisoned, who had to work as forced laborers on the highway.<ref>Heribert Artinger: ''Chronik der Freistadt Rust, 1850-1950: Tagebuch der kleinsten Stadt \u00d6sterreichs mit eigenem Statut''. </ref> In 1938, a barrack camp was built in Sittendorf, which originally served for the workers and later French prisoners of war, as well as for Serbian forced laborers. Today, a plaque commemorates the place of remembrance in the barracks camp and at the Sittendorf cemetery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://iehi.eu/index.php/component/content/article/128-erinnerungsort-barackenlager-sittendorf|title=Erinnerungsort Barackenlager Sittendorf|last=|first=|date=|website=iehi.eu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}} </ref>\n\nAfter the war, land already exchanged or replaced fell into Soviet hands as German property and only returned to the Republic of Austria after the [[Austrian State Treaty|State Treaty]] in 1955.\n\nOther route variants were also considered before the further construction. One variant, for example, was to make the A 21 run more southwards from Alland. However, since the [[Helenental]], a narrow valley, would have been too badly affected, this variant was dropped again. It was only in the area of [[Heiligenkreuz, Lower Austria|Heiligenkreuz]] that the route was moved further away from the village, so as not to affect the [[Heiligenkreuz Abbey]]. In addition, a large part of the land necessary for the construction had already been sold; thus, the further construction was not started until 1964.\n\nOn the first section opened in 1962 between the [[V\u00f6sendorf]] interchange and [[Brunn am Gebirge]], only one directional roadway was available. It was only passable in both directions from 1968 onwards. The last sections between [[Mayerling]] and [[Hinterbr\u00fchl]] were completed in 1982. Furthermore, the highway was planned to continue to Schwechat, where it would become the [[Ost Autobahn|A 4]]. This section was realized in the form of the [[Wiener Au\u00dfenring Schnellstra\u00dfe|S 1]] expressway, which opened in 2006.\n\nSoon after the opening of the continuous motorway, a rest area was to be built at the location of today's Hinterbr\u00fchl rest stop. After partial resistance from the local population, who feared that their habitat would be adversely affected, the plan was dropped and the rest area was built in Alland instead.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! style=\"background:#276FB7\" |<span style=\"color:white\"> Opening </span>\n! style=\"background:#276FB7\" |<span style=\"color:white\">Section</span>\n! style=\"background:#276FB7\" |<span style=\"color:white\"> Length</span>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |19.12.1962\n| align=\"center\" |ASt Brunn/Gebirge - Knoten V\u00f6sendorf (right carriageway)\n| align=\"center\" |2.116 km\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |11.04.1968\n| align=\"center\" |ASt Brunn/Gebirge - Knoten V\u00f6sendorf (left carriageway)\n| align=\"center\" |2.116 km\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |24.09.1971\n| align=\"center\" |Knoten Steinh\u00e4usl - Klausen-Leopoldsdorf\n| align=\"center\" |13.200 km\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |07.10.1977\n| align=\"center\" |Klausen-Leopoldsdorf - ASt Mayerling\n| align=\"center\" |4.017 km\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |24.10.1980\n| align=\"center\" |ASt Hinterbr\u00fchl - ASt Brunn/Gebirge\n| align=\"center\" |10.442 km\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |29.09.1982\n| align=\"center\" |ASt Heiligenkreuz - ASt Hinterbr\u00fchl\n| align=\"center\" |3.031 km\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |29.09.1982\n| align=\"center\" |ASt Mayerling - ASt Heiligenkreuz (left carriageway)\n| align=\"center\" |5.437 km\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |29.10.1982\n| align=\"center\" |ASt Mayerling - ASt Heiligenkreuz (right carriageway)\n| align=\"center\" |5.437 km\n|-\n|}\n\n== Accidents ==\nOn the night of 22 February 2010, a German coach bus traveling towards Steinh\u00e4usl collided with a truck in front of it. Six people were killed, ten seriously injured, and twenty slightly injured.  Temperatures around the freezing point made it difficult to use emergency services on the closed motorway.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://diepresse.com/home/panorama/oesterreich/541435/NOe_Busunfall-auf-A21-fordert-sechs-Todesopfer|title=N\u00d6: Busunfall auf A21 fordert sechs Todesopfer|last=|first=|date=|website=Die Presse|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615214757/http://diepresse.com/home/panorama/oesterreich/541435/NOe_Busunfall-auf-A21-fordert-sechs-Todesopfer|archive-date=15 June 2018|access-date=15 April 2020}} </ref><ref>[http://noe122.noet.at/filearchive/517b8607b76d14c5f957bba91a7e2790.pdf Die Trag\u00f6die auf der A{{NNBSP}}21] in Brandaus von 3/2010 (PDF)</ref>\n\n== Problems ==\nOn 2 December 2010, after heavy snowfall, 80 trucks were stuck on the A 21 and the entire highway was closed for five hours. After heavy snowfalls, the A 21 had to be closed on 1 December 2016 at the Steinh\u00e4usl interchange, because trucks got stuck there despite having winter equipment. One reason was the gradient of more than 5% there.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heute.at/s/-23244842|title=Wintereinbruch sorgte f\u00fcr Chaos auf A21 - Nieder\u00f6sterreich|website=Heute.at|language=de|access-date=2019-11-02}}</ref> On 19 April 2017, after heavy snowfall, the A 21 was closed again because several trucks and many cars that were already on summer tires got stuck on the A 21 for hours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fireworld.at/2017/04/21/noe-schnee-chaos-auf-der-a21-teil-2-feuerwehren-die-nacht-hindurch-im-einsatz/|title=N\u00f6: Schnee-Chaos auf der A21 Teil 2 \u2192 Feuerwehren die Nacht hindurch im Einsatz|last=Zukrigl|first=Gerald|date=2017-04-21|website=Fireworld.at|language=de-DE|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The [[ASFiNAG|ASFINAG]] responded to the criticism that they had responded too late to the snowfall by stating that they had sent the snowploughs on the road hours before the onset of the strongest snowfall. Crossed trucks and the failure to form the emergency lane (''Rettungsgasse'') by drivers would have made it impossible to get through with the snow plows.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://noe.orf.at/v2/news/stories/2762936/|title=A21 nach Schneechaos stundenlang gesperrt|date=2016-03-15|website=noe.orf.at|language=de|access-date=2019-11-02}}</ref> In a statement issued on 20 April 2017, Infrastructure Minister Leichtfried announced that the winter tires requirement for trucks would be extended until 15 May.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kurier.at/chronik/niederoesterreich/lenker-ueben-kritik-an-der-asfinag-nach-schneechaos-auf-a21/259.507.337|title=Lenker \u00fcben Kritik an der Asfinag nach Schneechaos auf A21|website=kurier.at|language=de|access-date=2019-11-02}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* Bernd Kreuzer: ''Der Bau der Autobahnen und Schnellstra\u00dfe in \u00d6sterreich.'' \u2013 In: ASFINAG (Hrsg.): ''[https://www.asfinag.at/media/1510/de_buch-30-jahre-asfinag.pdf Das Autobahnnetz in \u00d6sterreich. 30 Jahre Asfinag].'' \u2013 Vienna, 2012, S. 99\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://motorways-exitlists.com/europe/a/a21.htm Wiener Au\u00dfenring Autobahn in motorways-exitlists.com]\n* [https://www.asfinag.at/documents/10180/13369/de_Buch+30+Jahre+ASFINAG.pdf/8af1a7eb-9bda-4f3c-86a9-81181d4bacb9 30 Jahre \u201eAllander\u201c Autobahn \u2013 die A 21 feiert Geburtstag- Asfinag]\n\n{{Autobahn system in Austria}}\n[[Category:Roads in Europe]]\n[[Category:Sankt P\u00f6lten-Land District]]\n[[Category:M\u00f6dling District]]\n[[Category:Baden District, Austria]]\n[[Category:Autobahns in Austria]]\n", "name_user": "DraconicDark", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed number of next route in infobox", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wiener_Au%C3%9Fenring_Autobahn"}
{"title_page": "Monte de Fral\u00e3es", "text_new": "{{Infobox Portuguese subdivision \n|type = parish \n|official_name = Monte de Fral\u00e3es\n|image_shield =\n|region             = Norte\n|CIM                = [[C\u00e1vado (intermunicipal community)|C\u00e1vado]]\n|district           = [[Braga District|Braga]]\n|municipality       = [[Barcelos, Portugal|Barcelos]]\n|area_total = 1.58\n|population_total = 408\n|population_as_of = 2011\n|dissolved = 2013\n|coordinates = {{coord|41.458|-8.567|type:adm1st_region:PT_dim:50000|display=inline,title}}\n|website = \n|footnotes =\n}}\n'''Monte de Fral\u00e3es''' is a former [[Freguesia (Portugal)|civil parish]], located in the [[Municipalities of Portugal|municipality]] of [[Barcelos, Portugal|Barcelos]], Portugal. In 2013, the parish merged into the new parish [[Viatodos, Grimancelos, Minhot\u00e3es e Monte de Fral\u00e3es]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Law nr. 11-A/2013, pages 552 21-24|url=http://dre.pt/pdf1sdip/2013/01/01901/0000200147.pdf |accessdate=17 July 2014|author=''[[Di\u00e1rio da Rep\u00fablica]]''|language=Portuguese|format=pdf}}</ref> The population in 2011 was 408,<ref>[http://www.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xlang=en&xpid=INE&xpgid=ine_indicadores&indOcorrCod=0005889&contexto=pi&selTab=tab0 Instituto Nacional de Estat\u00edstica]</ref> in an area of 1.58&nbsp;km\u00b2.<ref>[http://epp.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/portal/page/portal/nuts_nomenclature/documents/PT-LAU.xls Eurostat]</ref>\n\nThe parish's [[patron saint]] is St. Peter and his feast has been celebrated for four centuries every 15 August by the Confraternity of Our Lady of Health.\n\nThe actual parish church was in ancient times the chapel of the Correias, a local noble family. Deeply modified, it is today a small and beautiful temple, which has substituted, since 1913, for the former church. It possesses a remarkable 18th-century ''talha'' ([[Gilding|gilt]] wood) altar. Remarkable also, dating from the 1910s, are the two lateral [[retable]]s which receive the images of the [[Sacred Heart of Jesus]] and Our Lady of Health.\n\nThe parish, that was born in the Mount of Assaia, where there was a very ancient town, a ''cit\u00e2nia'', had some important priests, like J\u00e1come Dias (16th century), Jo\u00e3o Rodrigues de Carvalho and the writer Jo\u00e3o Rosa (19th century). Its original name was S. Crist\u00f3v\u00e3o de Silveiros (11th century), as can be seen in the Censual do Bispo D. Pedro.\n\nIn the 13th century Monte de Fral\u00e3es (then S. Pedro do Monte) was born, the great conqueror [[Paio Peres Correia]].\n\nIn the 14th century, in the [[Solar (Spanish term)|Solar]] of the Correias (Solar of Fral\u00e3es), has been created the Municipality of Fral\u00e3es, known as Honra de Fral\u00e3es (that included also Viatodos and part of Silveiros); it would be extinguished in December 1836. Varied documentation of this autarchy is conserved in the parish and in Barcelos archives.\n\nThe pianist and composer Lu\u00eds Costa was born in Monte de Fral\u00e3es.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Monte de Fralaes}}\n[[Category:Former parishes of Portugal]]\n[[Category:Parishes of Barcelos, Portugal]]\n\n\n{{braga-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Portuguese subdivision \n|type = parish \n|official_name = Monte de Fral\u00e3es\n|image_shield =\n|region             = Norte\n|CIM                = [[C\u00e1vado (intermunicipal community)|C\u00e1vado]]\n|district           = [[Braga District|Braga]]\n|municipality       = [[Barcelos, Portugal|Barcelos]]\n|area_total = 1.58\n|population_total = 408\n|population_as_of = 2011\n|dissolved = 2013\n|coordinates = {{coord|41.458|-8.567|type:adm1st_region:PT_dim:50000|display=inline,title}}\n|website = \n|footnotes =\n}}\n'''Monte de Fral\u00e3es''' is a former [[Freguesia (Portugal)|civil parish]], located in the [[Municipalities of Portugal|municipality]] of [[Barcelos, Portugal|Barcelos]], Portugal. In 2013, the parish merged into the new parish [[Viatodos, Grimancelos, Minhot\u00e3es e Monte de Fral\u00e3es]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Law nr. 11-A/2013, pages 552 21-24|url=http://dre.pt/pdf1sdip/2013/01/01901/0000200147.pdf |accessdate=17 July 2014|author=''[[Di\u00e1rio da Rep\u00fablica]]''|language=Portuguese|format=pdf}}</ref> The population in 2011 was 408,<ref>[http://www.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xlang=en&xpid=INE&xpgid=ine_indicadores&indOcorrCod=0005889&contexto=pi&selTab=tab0 Instituto Nacional de Estat\u00edstica]</ref> in an area of 1.58&nbsp;km\u00b2.<ref>[http://epp.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/portal/page/portal/nuts_nomenclature/documents/PT-LAU.xls Eurostat]</ref>\n\nThe parish's [[patron saint]] is St. Peter and his feast has been celebrated for four centuries every 15 August by the Confraternity of Our Lady of Health.\n\nThe actual parish church was in ancient times the chapel of the Correias, a local noble family. Deeply modified, it is today a small and beautiful temple, which has substituted, since 1913, for the former church. It possesses a remarkable 18th-century ''talha'' ([[Gilding|gilt]] wood) altar. Remarkable also, dating from the 1910s, are the two lateral [[retable]]s which receive the images of the [[Sacred Heart of Jesus]] and Our Lady of Health.\n\nThe parish, that was born in the Mount of Assaia, where there was a very ancient town, a ''cit\u00e2nia'', had some important priests, like J\u00e1come Dias (16th century), Jo\u00e3o Rodrigues de Carvalho and the writer Jo\u00e3o Rosa (19th century). Its original name was S. Crist\u00f3v\u00e3o de Silveiros (11th century), as can be seen in the Censual do Bispo D. Pedro.\n\nIn the 13th century Monte de Fral\u00e3es (then S. Pedro do Monte) was born, the great conqueror [[Paio Peres Correia]].\n\nIn the 14th century, in the [[Solar (Spanish term)|Solar]] of the Correias (Solar of Fral\u00e3es), has been created the Municipality of Fral\u00e3es, known as Honra de Fral\u00e3es (that included also Viatodos and part of Silveiros); it would be extinguished in December 1836. Varied documentation of this autarchy is conserved in the parish and in Barcelos archives.\n\nThe pianist and composer Lu\u00eds Costa was born in Monte de Fral\u00e3es.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Monte de Fralaes}}\n[[Category:Former parishes of Portugal]]\n[[Category:Parishes of Barcelos, Portugal]]\n\n\n{{braga-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_de_Fral%C3%A3es"}
