{"title_page": "Monte Real", "text_new": "{{about|town in Portugal|the air force base|Monte Real Air Base|the parish|Monte Real e Carvide|\"Mont Real\"|Mount Royal|others|Mount Royal (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox Portuguese subdivision \n|type = parish \n | official_name      = Monte Real\n | image_shield = LRA-montereal.png\n|region             = [[Centro Region, Portugal|Centro]]\n|CIM                = [[Regi\u00e3o de Leiria]]\n|district           = [[Leiria District|Leiria]]\n|municipality       = [[Leiria]]\n|coordinates        = {{coord|39|49|52.4|N|8|52|42|W|source:ptwiki_region:PT_scale:4_type:city(2778)|display=inline,title}}\n | area_total         = 12.23\n |population_total   = 2778\n |population_as_of = 2001\n | dissolved = 2013\n | website            = \n}}\n\n'''Monte Real''' is a town (''vila'' in Portuguese) and a former [[Freguesia (Portugal)|civil parish]] in the municipality of [[Leiria]], Portugal. In 2013, the parish merged into the new parish [[Monte Real e Carvide]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Law nr. 11-A/2013, page 552 60|url=http://dre.pt/pdf1sdip/2013/01/01901/0000200147.pdf |accessdate=24 July 2014|author=''[[Di\u00e1rio da Rep\u00fablica]]''|language=Portuguese|format=pdf}}</ref> It covers an area of 12.23&nbsp;km\u00b2 and has a population of 2,778 people. Monte Real, which in English means Royal Mount, was once a municipality (pt: ''concelho''), before being annexed to Leiria municipality.\n\nMonte Real hosts an air base (''base a\u00e9rea''), [[Monte Real Air Base]] for the Portuguese Air Force.<ref>{{cite web|title=Base A\u00e9rea N\u00ba 5|url=http://www.emfa.pt/www/unidade-18-ba5|accessdate=16 October 2012|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\nMonte Real is also known for its [[hot springs]], (''Termas de Monte Real'').<ref>{{cite web|title=Termas Monte Real|url=http://www.termasdemontereal.pt/|accessdate=16 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130413053537/http://www.jf-montereal.pt/ Junta Freguesia]\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Monte Real}}\n[[Category:Parishes of Leiria]]\n[[Category:Former parishes of Portugal]]\n[[Category:Towns in Portugal]]\n\n\n{{Leiria-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{about|town in Portugal|the air force base|Monte Real Air Base|the parish|Monte Real e Carvide|\"Mont Real\"|Mount Royal|others|Mount Royal (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox Portuguese subdivision \n|type = parish \n | official_name      = Monte Real\n | image_shield = LRA-montereal.png\n|region             = [[Centro Region, Portugal|Centro]]\n|CIM                = [[Regi\u00e3o de Leiria]]\n|district           = [[Leiria District|Leiria]]\n|municipality       = [[Leiria]]\n|coordinates        = {{coord|39|49|52.4|N|8|52|42|W|source:ptwiki_region:PT_scale:4_type:city(2778)|display=inline,title}}\n | area_total         = 12.23\n |population_total   = 2778\n |population_as_of = 2001\n | dissolved = 2013\n | website            = \n}}\n\n'''Monte Real''' is a town (''vila'' in Portuguese) and a former [[Freguesia (Portugal)|civil parish]] in the municipality of [[Leiria]], Portugal. In 2013, the parish merged into the new parish [[Monte Real e Carvide]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Law nr. 11-A/2013, page 552 60|url=http://dre.pt/pdf1sdip/2013/01/01901/0000200147.pdf |accessdate=24 July 2014|author=''[[Di\u00e1rio da Rep\u00fablica]]''|language=Portuguese|format=pdf}}</ref> It covers an area of 12.23&nbsp;km\u00b2 and has a population of 2,778 people. Monte Real, which in English means Royal Mount, was once a municipality (pt: ''concelho''), before being annexed to Leiria municipality.\n\nMonte Real hosts an air base (''base a\u00e9rea''), [[Monte Real Air Base]] for the Portuguese Air Force.<ref>{{cite web|title=Base A\u00e9rea N\u00ba 5|url=http://www.emfa.pt/www/unidade-18-ba5|accessdate=16 October 2012|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\nMonte Real is also known for its [[hot springs]], (''Termas de Monte Real'').<ref>{{cite web|title=Termas Monte Real|url=http://www.termasdemontereal.pt/|accessdate=16 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130413053537/http://www.jf-montereal.pt/ Junta Freguesia]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Monte Real}}\n[[Category:Parishes of Leiria]]\n[[Category:Former parishes of Portugal]]\n[[Category:Towns in Portugal]]\n\n\n{{Leiria-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Real"}
{"title_page": "Truro and Penwith College", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{coord|50.262|-5.101|display=title|region:GB_scale:5000}}\n\n{{Redirects|Truro College|the Wesleyan Methodist institution which operated between 1879 and 1931|Truro School}}\n\n{{Infobox school \n| name         = Truro and Penwith College\n| image        = Truro and Penwith College logo.png|\n| motto        =\n| established  = 2008<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edumaritime.com/england/logistics-supply-chain-transport-college-level/truro-and-penwith-college|title=TRURO AND PENWITH COLLEGE AT TRURO, CORNWALL, UK|work=EduMaritime.com|accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref>\n| closed       =\n| type         = [[Tertiary College]]\n[[Further Education College]]\n| religious_affiliation     =\n| president    =\n| head_label   = Principal\n| head         = David Walrond\n| r_head_label =\n| r_head       =\n| chair_label  =\n| chair        =\n| founder      =\n| specialist   =\n| address       =\n| city         =[[Truro]] <br /> [[Penzance]]<br /> [[Carnon Downs]]\n| county       =\n| country      =\n| postcode     =\n| local_authority          =\n| dfeno        =\n| urn          = 130629\n| ofsted       = Outstanding\n| staff        =\n| enrolment   =\n| gender       =\n| lower_age    =\n| upper_age    =\n| houses       =\n| colours      =\n| publication  =\n| free_label_1 = Associated with\n| free_1       = [[Callywith College]]\n[[Stadium for Cornwall]]\n| website      = http://www.truro-penwith.ac.uk/\n}}\n\n'''Truro and Penwith College''' is a [[Tertiary College]] and [[Further Education College]] in [[Cornwall]] in the United Kingdom. It was the first college to be awarded 'Outstanding' status, the highest designation, by [[Ofsted]] in 2006,<ref>Truro and Penwith College Annual Report 2010/2011. http://www.truro-penwith.ac.uk/download/TPC_annual_report.pdf Accessed 1 February 2013.</ref><ref name=\"auto7\">Truro College Ofstead Inspection Report, 2006. http://www.ofsted.gov.uk/provider/files/857725/urn/130629.pdf Accessed 1 February 2013.</ref> and the first to retain an Outstanding rating, in 2016. <ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.westbriton.co.uk/truro-penwith-college-outstanding-say-ofsted/story-29102061-detail/story.html|title=Truro and Penwith College|date=13 April 2016|publisher=}}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"ofsted.gov.uk\">reports.ofsted.gov.uk/provider/files/2559347/urn/130629.pdf</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=http://feweek.co.uk/2016/04/13/first-college-outstanding-ofsted-rating-awarded-under-new-cif/|title=First college outstanding Ofsted rating awarded under CIF|date=13 April 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\nIn the [[2019 Six Nations Championship|2019 Six Nations]] [[Rugby Union]] game between [[England national rugby union team|England]] and [[Ireland national rugby union team|Ireland]], four of the players on the pitch were graduates from its Rugby Academy, [[Luke Cowan-Dickie]], [[Jack Nowell]], [[Henry_Slade_(rugby_player) |Henry Slade]], and [[Bundee Aki]]. <ref name=\"cornwalllive.com four former\">https://www.cornwalllive.com/sport/rugby/four-former-truro-college-students-2505780</ref>\nIt is the top non-selective provider of the [[IB Diploma Programme|International Baccalaureate Diploma]] in the UK, according to [[Sunday Times]] Parent Power league tables.<ref>https://www.cornwalllive.com/special-features/discover-excellent-alternative-levels-topping-3741168</ref> \nIn 2015 it had the highest A Level points-per-student and value-added progress score in the UK. <ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web|url=http://feweek.co.uk/2015/02/02/tables-joy-for-duo-on-a-levels-and-vocational-study/|title=Tables joy for duo on A-levels and vocational study|date=2 February 2015|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"westernmorningnews.co.uk\">http://www.westernmorningnews.co.uk/truro-penwith-college-flying-high-league-tables/story-25961230-detail/story.html http://www.falmouthpacket.co.uk/news/11774807.Truro_College_tops_league_tables_locally_and_nationally/</ref><ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.truro-penwith.ac.uk/latest-news/truro-and-penwith-college-tops-the-latest-government-league-tables/|title=Truro and Penwith College tops the latest government league tables|publisher=}}</ref>  \nIn 2012 two of its students got the highest marks in the country for English Language and Law.<ref name=\"auto5\">Cornwall duo are crowned UK's best in their exams, \u2018This is Cornwall\u2019, December 2069. http://www.thisiscornwall.co.uk/Cornwall-student-duo-crowned-UK-s-best-exams/story-17691055-detail/story.html Accessed 1 February 2013.</ref><ref name=\"auto6\">Top marks in the country for two Truro and penwith College students, \u2018Truro and Penwith College\u2019, December 2012. http://www.truro-penwith.ac.uk/news/top-marks-in-the-country-for-two-truro-and-penwith-college-students/ Accessed 1 February 2013.</ref> In 2015 one of its students was awarded the 'Outstanding BTEC Student of the Year' award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.falmouthpacket.co.uk/news/13382223.stephanie-strikes-gold-twice-at-national-btec-awards/|title=Stephanie strikes gold, twice, at National BTEC Awards|website=Falmouth Packet|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scillytoday.com/2015/07/14/truro-and-penwith-college-news-july-2015/|title=Truro And Penwith College News July 2015|date=2015-07-14|website=Scilly Today|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nTruro College was founded in 1993 as a new college in Gloweth near Threemilestone, [[Truro]], [[Cornwall]], to replace the Truro Sixth Form College. Penwith College was founded in 1980 in [[Penzance]], and was known until 1990 as Penwith Sixth Form College. The two colleges merged in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.truro-penwith.ac.uk/about-us/|title=Two colleges in one - Truro & Penwith College|publisher=|accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref><ref>Royal seal of approval for two new buildings, at Truro College, This is the Westcountry, October 2012. http://www.thisisthewestcountry.co.uk/news/cornwall_news/10003807.Royal_seal_of_approval_for_two_new_buildings_at_Truro_College/?ref=rss Accessed 1 February 2013.</ref>\nIt has assisted the creation of the [[Ofsted]] Outstanding [[Callywith College]], a [[Further Education]] college in [[Bodmin]] which opened in September 2017<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westbriton.co.uk/truro-penwith-college-s-planned-new-bodmin-campus/story-27846919-detail/story.html|title=Truro and Penwith College's planned new Bodmin campus to be named Callywith College|date=23 September 2015|publisher=}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>https://www.truro-penwith.ac.uk/downloads/callywith_consultation_booklet.pdf</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westernmorningnews.co.uk/controversial-college-cornwall-bodmin-gets-ahead/story-28386123-detail/story.html|title=Controversial college for Cornwall in Bodmin gets go-ahead|date=17 December 2015|publisher=}}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.truro-penwith.ac.uk/callywithcollege/|title=College courses in Cornwall - Callywith|publisher=|accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"www.gov.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/games-workshop-founder-and-entrepreneur-to-open-2-free-schools|title=Games Workshop founder and entrepreneur to open 2 free schools - Press releases - GOV.UK|publisher=}}</ref><ref>http://www.cornishguardian.co.uk/government-grants-free-school-status-new-college/story-28678208-detail/story.html{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and the development of the [[Stadium for Cornwall]] in Langarth, Threemilestone, Truro.<ref name=\"westbriton.co.uk1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.westbriton.co.uk/look-retail-park-fund-stadium-cornwall/story-29095026-detail/story.html|title=First look at retail park which will fund Stadium for Cornwall|date=12 April 2016|publisher=|accessdate=12 October 2016}}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"stadium4cornwall.co.uk\">http://stadium4cornwall.co.uk/</ref>\nThe Rick Stein Academy was launched in 2015 as a partnership between the [[Rick Stein]] Group and Truro and Penwith College.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rickstein.com/the-rick-stein-academy-is-launched/|title=The Rick Stein Academy launches with Truro & Penwith College|publisher=|accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref> In 2016 it was recognized as a Top 100 Apprenticeship Employer nationally.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rickstein.com/rick-stein-jill-stein-recognised-as-top-100-apprenticeship-employer/|title=Rick Stein recognised as top 100 apprenticeship employer|publisher=|accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bighospitality.co.uk/Business/The-Seafood-Restaurant-and-Lancaster-London-appear-in-Top-100-Apprenticeship-Employer-2016-list|title=The Seafood Restaurant and Lancaster London appear in Top 100 Apprenticeship Employer 2016 list|first=|last=BigHospitality.co.uk|publisher=|accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref>In 2016 Truro and Penwith College won the [[Association of Colleges]] Beacon Award for Leadership and Governance.<ref name=\"businesscornwall.co.uk\">https://www.businesscornwall.co.uk/news-by-location/truro-business-news/2016/11/college-wins-national-award/</ref>\nThe College hosts the annual Cornwall Apprenticeship Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.truro-penwith.ac.uk/courses-explained/apprenticeships/cornwall-apprenticeship-awards-2016/|title=Cornwall Apprenticeship Awards 2016|publisher=|accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.falmouthpacket.co.uk/trurocollege/13889278.The_apprentices_of_the_year_are_given_their_reward/|title=The apprentices of the year are given their reward|publisher=|accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Courses==\n\nCourses available include [[Further Education]]<ref>Further Education, Truro and Penwith College, http://www.truro-penwith.ac.uk/further-education/ Accessed 1 February 2013.</ref> such as [[A Levels]], [[T Level|T levels]], [[Vocational Qualifications]] (including [[BTEC Diplomas]], [[National Vocational Qualifications]] (NVQs) and [[Apprenticeships]]), Foundation Studies, and the [[International Baccalaureate Diploma]]; Higher Education<ref>Higher Education, Truro and Penwith College, http://www.truro-penwith.ac.uk/higher-education/ Accessed 1 February 2013.</ref> such as [[Honours Degrees]], [[Foundation Degrees]], [[Higher National Diplomas]], education qualifications, other professional qualifications;<ref>Business, Truro and Penwith College, http://www.truro-penwith.ac.uk/business/ Accessed 1 February 2013.</ref> part-time and evening courses.<ref>Part-time courses, Truro and Penwith College, http://www.truro-penwith.ac.uk/part-time/ Accessed 1 February 2013.</ref><ref>Courses, Truro and Penwith College, http://www.truro-penwith.ac.uk/courses-info/ Accessed 1 February 2013.</ref> Teacher training is done on PGCE, CertEd and Cornwall SCITT courses.<ref name=\"truro-penwith.ac.uk3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.truro-penwith.ac.uk/courses-explained/university-level/postgraduate-degree/|title=Study Cornwall SCITT or PGCE in Cornwall|publisher=|accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref> Cornwall SCITT (School Centred Initial Teacher Training, a partnership of 16 local secondary schools, one special school and Truro and Penwith College, offering postgraduate teacher training to the 11-16 age range, with post-16 enhancements) retained its own Ofsted Outstanding rating in 2016.<ref name=\"truro-penwith.ac.uk3\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.falmouthpacket.co.uk/news/truro/14609837.Fifty_two_new_teachers_celebrate_graduation/|title=Fifty-two new teachers celebrate graduation|publisher=|accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cornwallscitt.org/|title=Cornwall SCITT - Cornwall Teacher Training Programme|publisher=|accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n\nIn 2019 Truro and Penwith College had its best ever year for academic results. 34 A-level subjects achieved a 100% pass rate, including Maths, English Literature and Psychology, with an overall pass rate of over 99.5%, 88% achieving A*-C, 66% A*-B. With nearly 5,000 individual A and AS level entries this year, Truro and Penwith College is one of the largest providers of the qualification nationally. In Level 3 vocational qualifications, 64% achieved a triple distinction. Over 200 students achieved the highest possible grade, the Triple Distinction Star on BTEC Diploma courses.<ref>https://www.cornwalllive.com/news/cornwall-news/level-results-day-2019-live-3211800</ref> <ref>https://www.falmouthpacket.co.uk/news/17838726.a-level-results-2019-falmouth-helston-truro-camborne-redruth-penzance-across-cornwall</ref>\nTruro College was rated the top non-selective provider of the International Baccalaureate Diploma in the UK in the Sunday Times Parent Power league tables, with an average point score per student of 35 in 2019, which is equivalent to three A* grades and one A grade at A Level including one student achieving a perfect score of 45 <ref>https://www.cornwalllive.com/special-features/discover-excellent-alternative-levels-topping-3741168</ref> \nIn 2015 it had the highest A Level points-per-student and value-added progress score in the UK. <ref name=\"auto3\" /><ref name=\"westernmorningnews.co.uk\" /><ref name=\"auto4\" />  \n\n==2016 Ofsted Inspection==\n\nTruro and Penwith College was rated as being Outstanding by [[Ofsted]] in 2016, the first FE provider to be awarded this highest designation under the new Ofsted assessment framework, and making it the first college to ever retain an Outstanding rating.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.westbriton.co.uk/truro-penwith-college-outstanding-say-ofsted/story-29102061-detail/story.html|title=Truro and Penwith College|date=13 April 2016|publisher=}}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"ofsted.gov.uk\" />\n\n==Sport and Academies==\n\nIn the [[2019 Six Nations Championship|2019 Six Nations]] [[Rugby Union]] game between [[England national rugby union team|England]] and [[Ireland national rugby union team|Ireland]], four of the players on the pitch were graduates from its Rugby Academy, [[Luke Cowan-Dickie]], [[Jack Nowell]], [[Henry_Slade_(rugby_player) |Henry Slade]], and [[Bundee Aki]]. <ref name=\"cornwalllive.com four former\" />\nThe Truro College Rugby Academy is an [[Exeter Chiefs]] Academy team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://exeterchiefs.co.uk/academy/truro-college/|title=Truro College - Exeter Chiefs|publisher=|accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"trurocollege.ac.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.trurocollege.ac.uk/students-life/academies/rugby-academy-in-partnership-with-exeter-chiefs-rugby-academy/|title=Rugby Academy|publisher=|accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref> The College competes in the AASE league along with the other premiership academies and the Association of Colleges Sport Leagues and Cups and has won the Daily Mail Cup, British Colleges U19 Knock-Out Cup, National 10s and 7s, South West Colleges League, Samurai 7s, AASE League Plate and have been AoC Premier Cup Finalists.<ref name=\"trurocollege.ac.uk\"/> Rugby Academy players regularly sign for teams such as the [[Exeter Chiefs]], [[Cornish Pirates]], [[Redruth R.F.C.]] or [[Launceston RUFC|Cornish All-Blacks]] before their studies at the College have finished.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trelawnysarmy.org/cornish-pirates-strengthen-links-with-truro-college/|title=CORNISH PIRATES STRENGTHEN LINKS WITH TRURO COLLEGE|date=2 May 2013|publisher=|accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://exeterchiefs.co.uk/news/pellows-joy-academy-display/|title=Pellow's joy at Academy display - Exeter Chiefs|date=13 August 2014|publisher=|accessdate=12 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820014333/http://exeterchiefs.co.uk/news/pellows-joy-academy-display/|archive-date=20 August 2016|url-status = dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aocjobs.com/article/elite-sport-in-fe-jack-nowell-england-rugby/elite-rugby-at-truro-college/|title=The rise and rise of elite rugby at Truro College - AoC Jobs|publisher=|accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisiscornwall.co.uk/Rawlings-delighted-second-half/story-16687810-detail/story.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130505114650/http://www.thisiscornwall.co.uk/Rawlings-delighted-second-half/story-16687810-detail/story.html|url-status = dead|archive-date=5 May 2013|title=Rawlings delighted by second half show|date=10 August 2012|publisher=|accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisiscornwall.co.uk/Cornish-Pirates-complete-loan-deals-Exeter-Chiefs/story-18935720-detail/story.html#axzz2c4PJys3w|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130816032700/http://www.thisiscornwall.co.uk/Cornish-Pirates-complete-loan-deals-Exeter-Chiefs/story-18935720-detail/story.html%23axzz2c4PJys3w|url-status = dead|archive-date=16 August 2013|title=Cornish Pirates complete loan deals for Exeter Chiefs Academy quartet|date=9 May 2013|publisher=|accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref> The Academy team plays in the Sanix Tournament in Japan against the other best under-18s rugby teams from around the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westbriton.co.uk/japan-tour/story-29167183-detail/story.html|title=Truro College Rugby Academy off to Japan for fourth time|date=24 April 2016|publisher=|accessdate=12 October 2016}}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe Truro College Football Development program is in association with the [[Chelsea F.C.]] Foundation.  Truro and Penwith College's football teams play in official Chelsea kits and benefit from world-class training at Chelsea FC throughout the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.truro-penwith.ac.uk/latest-news/truro-and-penwith-college-scores-with-exclusive-chelsea-fc-foundation-assoc/|title=TRURO AND PENWITH COLLEGE SCORES WITH EXCLUSIVE CHELSEA FC FOUNDATION ASSOCIATION|publisher=|accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Notable Alumni==\n[[Jack Nowell]], [[England national rugby union team|England rugby]] player. \n\n[[Luke Cowan-Dickie]], [[England national rugby union team|England rugby]] player.\n\n[[Henry_Slade_(rugby_player) |Henry Slade]], [[England national rugby union team|England rugby]] player.\n\n[[Bundee Aki]], [[Ireland national rugby union team|Ireland rugby]] player.\n\n[[Josh Matavesi]], [[Fiji national rugby union team|Fiji rugby]] player.\n\n[[Sam Matavesi]], [[Fiji national rugby union team|Fiji rugby]] player.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n*[http://www.truro-penwith.ac.uk/ Truro and Penwith College website]\n\n{{Schools in Cornwall}}\n{{Universities and colleges in South West England |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Truro and Penwith College}}\n[[Category:Further education colleges in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Truro]]\n[[Category:Penzance]]\n[[Category:International Baccalaureate schools in England]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2008]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{coord|50.262|-5.101|display=title|region:GB_scale:5000}}\n\n{{Redirects|Truro College|the Wesleyan Methodist institution which operated between 1879 and 1931|Truro School}}\n\n{{Infobox school \n| name         = Truro and Penwith College\n| image        = Truro and Penwith College logo.png|\n| motto        =\n| established  = 2008<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edumaritime.com/england/logistics-supply-chain-transport-college-level/truro-and-penwith-college|title=TRURO AND PENWITH COLLEGE AT TRURO, CORNWALL, UK|work=EduMaritime.com|access