{"title_page": "Olho Marinho", "text_new": "{{Infobox Portuguese subdivision\n|type = parish\n|official_name      = Olho Marinho\n|image_skyline      = \n|image_caption      = \n|image_flag         =\n|image_shield       = \n|image_location     = \n|region             = [[Centro Region, Portugal|Centro]]\n|CIM                = [[Oeste (intermunicipal community)|Oeste]]\n|district           = [[Leiria District|Leiria]]\n|municipality       = [[\u00d3bidos, Portugal|\u00d3bidos]]\n|coordinates        = {{coord|39.329|-9.232|type:adm1st_region:PT_dim:50000|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation          = \n|area_total         = 18.12\n|population_as_of   = 2011\n|population_total   = 1279\n|patron             = \n|area_code          = \n|postal_code        = \n|website            = \n}}\n'''Olho Marinho''' is a [[Portugal|Portuguese]] [[freguesia|civil parish]] in the municipality of [[\u00d3bidos, Portugal|\u00d3bidos]]. The population in 2011 was 1,279,<ref name=ine>[http://www.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xlang=en&xpid=INE&xpgid=ine_indicadores&indOcorrCod=0005889&contexto=pi&selTab=tab0 Instituto Nacional de Estat\u00edstica]</ref> in an area of 18.12&nbsp;km\u00b2.<ref name=dgt>[http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ \u00c1reas das freguesias, concelhos, distritos e pa\u00eds]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.olhomarinho.net/ Official website] {{in lang|pt}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Parishes of \u00d3bidos, Portugal]]\n\n\n{{Leiria-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Portuguese subdivision\n|type = parish\n|official_name      = Olho Marinho\n|image_skyline      = \n|image_caption      = \n|image_flag         =\n|image_shield       = \n|image_location     = \n|region             = [[Centro Region, Portugal|Centro]]\n|CIM                = [[Oeste (intermunicipal community)|Oeste]]\n|district           = [[Leiria District|Leiria]]\n|municipality       = [[\u00d3bidos, Portugal|\u00d3bidos]]\n|coordinates        = {{coord|39.329|-9.232|type:adm1st_region:PT_dim:50000|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation          = \n|area_total         = 18.12\n|population_as_of   = 2011\n|population_total   = 1279\n|patron             = \n|area_code          = \n|postal_code        = \n|website            = \n}}\n'''Olho Marinho''' is a [[Portugal|Portuguese]] [[freguesia|civil parish]] in the municipality of [[\u00d3bidos, Portugal|\u00d3bidos]]. The population in 2011 was 1,279,<ref name=ine>[http://www.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xlang=en&xpid=INE&xpgid=ine_indicadores&indOcorrCod=0005889&contexto=pi&selTab=tab0 Instituto Nacional de Estat\u00edstica]</ref> in an area of 18.12&nbsp;km\u00b2.<ref name=dgt>[http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ \u00c1reas das freguesias, concelhos, distritos e pa\u00eds]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.olhomarinho.net/ Official website] {{in lang|pt}}\n\n[[Category:Parishes of \u00d3bidos, Portugal]]\n\n\n{{Leiria-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Olho_Marinho"}
{"title_page": "Haqqani network", "text_new": "{{short description|Afghan guerrilla insurgent group}}\n{{Infobox war faction\n|name = Haqqani network\n|war = the [[War in Afghanistan (1978\u2013present)]], and the [[War on Terror|Global War on Terrorism]]\n|image = \n|caption =\n|active = 1980s<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.quilliaminternational.com/who-are-the-haqqanis-3/|title=Who are the Haqqanis? |publisher=Quilliam|accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref>\u2013present\n|ideology = Islamic fundamentalism\n|leaders = [[Jalaluddin Haqqani]] (deceased)<br />[[Sirajuddin Haqqani]]\n|groups =\n|headquarters =\n|area = [[Afghanistan]]\n|strength = 4,000\u201315,000<ref name='rassler' /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/259314/sirajuddin-haqqani-dares-us-to-attack-n-waziristan/|title=Sirajuddin Haqqani dares US to attack N Waziristan|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=20 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes 15haqqani\" />\n|partof = {{flagicon image|Flag of Taliban.svg}} [[Taliban]]<ref>https://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2018/09/taliban-announced-death-of-jalaluddin-haqqani.php</ref><ref>http://www.understandingwar.org/report/haqqani-network</ref><ref name='rassler' /><ref name=Riechmann /><ref name=\"CSM1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Asia-South-Central/2009/0601/p10s01-wosc.html|title=The most deadly US foe in Afghanistan|work=The Christian Science Monitor|date=1 June 2009|accessdate=17 August 2012|author=Gopal, Anand}}</ref><ref>Syed Salaam Shahzaddate=5 May 2004. \"Through the eyes of the Taliban\". ''Asia Times''. Retrieved 10 February 2009.</ref>\n|previous =\n|next =\n|allies= {{flagicon image|Flag of al-Qaeda.svg}} [[al-Qaeda]]\n|opponents=  {{nowrap|{{flagicon|Afghanistan}} [[Islamic Republic of Afghanistan]]}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-25922743 |title=Rare look at Afghan National Army's Taliban fight |publisher=BBC News |date=28 January 2014 |accessdate=2014-08-18}}</ref><br>\n{{Flag|USA}}\n\n{{flagicon|NATO}} [[North Atlantic Treaty Organization|NATO]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia/2012/12/20121224051624851.html |title=Taliban attack NATO base in Afghanistan |publisher=Al Jazeera English |date=2 December 2012 |accessdate=2014-08-18}}</ref><br>\n*{{flagicon image|Resolute Support.svg}} [[Resolute Support Mission]]\n\n{{flagicon|Pakistan}} [[Pakistan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/786641/us-commander-commends-zarb-e-azb-for-disrupting-haqqani-networks-ability-to-target-afghanistan/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106165357/http://tribune.com.pk/story/786641/us-commander-commends-zarb-e-azb-for-disrupting-haqqani-networks-ability-to-target-afghanistan/|url-status=dead|archive-date=6 November 2014|title=US commander commends Zarb-e-Azb for disrupting Haqqani network's ability to target Afghanistan|date=6 November 2014|work=Express Tribune}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/international/world-news/pakistan-military-operation-disrupted-haqqani-network-us-commander/articleshow/45054621.cms|title=Pakistan military operation disrupted Haqqani network: US commander|date=6 November 2014|work=Economic Times}}</ref>\nFormerly:<br/>{{flag|Soviet Union}} (1979\u20131989)\n|battles = [[Soviet\u2013Afghan War]] <br /> [[Afghan Civil War (1989\u20131992)]] <br /> [[Afghan Civil War (1992\u20131996)]] <br /> [[Afghan Civil War (1996\u20132001)]] <br /> [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]] <br /> [[Taliban insurgency]] <br /> [[Operation Zarb-e-Azb]]\n|active2=}}\n\nThe '''Haqqani network''' is an Afghan guerrilla [[Taliban insurgency|insurgent group]] using [[asymmetric warfare]] to fight against [[United States armed forces|US]]-led [[International Security Assistance Force|NATO forces]] and the [[government of Afghanistan]]. [[Mawlawi (Islamic title)|Maulvi]] [[Jalaluddin Haqqani]] and his son [[Sirajuddin Haqqani]] have led the group.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/01/world/asia/founder-of-haqqani-network-died-nearly-a-year-ago-member-says.html |title=Founder of Haqqani Network Is Long Dead Aide Says|work=The New York Times|accessdate=7 January 2016}}</ref> It is an offshoot of the [[Taliban]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/ruthless-taliban-branch-is-center-stage-in-us-pakistan-tensions/2017/07/18/dc03b2b4-5a89-11e7-aa69-3964a7d55207_story.html |title=A much-feared Taliban offshoot returns from the dead|first1=Haq Nawaz|last1=Khan|first2=Pamela|last2=Constable|date=19 July 2017|accessdate=1 February 2018|work=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/afghan-general-haqqani-network-islamic-state/4206961.html|title=Afghan General: Haqqani Network, Not IS, Behind Spike in Violence|first=Hasib Danish|last=Alikozai|publisher=VoA News|accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/what-haqqani-network/3883271.html|title=What Is the Haqqani Network?|last=|first=|date=|publisher=VOA News|language=en|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe Haqqani network pledged allegiance to the Taliban in 1995,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/what-haqqani-network/3883271.html|title=What Is the Haqqani Network?|last=|first=|date=|publisher=VOA|language=en|access-date=}}</ref> and have been an increasingly incorporated wing of the group ever since.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/04/world/asia/jalaluddin-haqqani-dead-taliban.html |title=Taliban Say Haqqani Founder Is Dead. His Group Is More Vital Than Ever.|last=Mashal|first=Mujib|date=2018-09-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In the past, the Taliban and Haqqani leaders have denied the existence of the \"network\", calling it no different from the Taliban.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/what-haqqani-network/3883271.html |title=What Is the Haqqani Network?|last=|first=|date=|publisher=VOA News |language=en|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1980s, the Haqqani network was one of the most favored CIA-funded anti-Soviet guerrilla groups by the [[Reagan administration]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Abubakar Siddique |date= 26 Sep 2011 |agency=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty  |url=https://www.ethz.ch/content/specialinterest/gess/cis/center-for-securities-studies/en/services/digital-library/articles/article.html/133041 |title=Questions Raised About Haqqani Network Ties with Pakistan |publisher=[[ETH Zurich]] Center for Security Studies |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref name='rassler'>{{cite journal|title=The Haqqani Nexus and the Evolution of al-Qaida|journal=Harmony Program|date=14 July 2011|first=Don|last=Rassler|author2=Vahid Brown|publisher=[[Combating Terrorism Center]]|url=http://www.ctc.usma.edu/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/CTC-Haqqani-Report_Rassler-Brown-Final_Web.pdf|format=PDF|accessdate=2 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725024028/http://www.ctc.usma.edu/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/CTC-Haqqani-Report_Rassler-Brown-Final_Web.pdf|archive-date=25 July 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2012, the United States designated the Haqqani network a terrorist organization.<ref>{{cite news|title=Haqqani network to be designated a terrorist group|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/haqqani-network-to-be-designated-a-terrorist-group-obama-officials-say/2012/09/07/e6576ac0-f8f6-11e1-a073-78d05495927c_story.html}}</ref> In 2015, Pakistan also banned the Haqqani network as part of its [[National Action Plan (Pakistan)|National Action Plan]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Pakistan bans Haqqani network after security talks with Kerry|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pakistan-militants-haqqani/pakistan-bans-haqqani-network-after-security-talks-with-kerry-idUSKBN0KP1DA20150116}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe word \"Haqqani\" comes from [[Darul Uloom Haqqania]], a [[Madrassa]] in Pakistan attended by [[Jalaluddin Haqqani]].<ref name=\"ft20111113\">{{cite news |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/8e0c7b26-0dbf-11e1-91e5-00144feabdc0.html#axzz2BfbmEmS0 |title=\u2018Father of Taliban\u2019 urges US concessions |work=Financial Times |date=13 November 2011 |accessdate=9 November 2012 |author=Green, Matthew |quote=The school also has a place in the hearts of the commanders of the Haqqani network, a family-run insurgent dynasty that specialises in Kabul suicide bombings. Jalaluddin Haqqani, the group\u2019s patriarch, studied at the seminary, from which he derives his name.}}</ref>\n\n==Ideology and goals==\nThe Haqqani network's root values are nationalistic and religious. They are ideologically aligned with the [[Taliban]], who have worked to eradicate Western influence and transform Afghanistan into a strictly sharia-following state. This was exemplified in the government that formed after Soviet troops were driven from Afghanistan.  Both groups have the common goal of disrupting the Western military and political efforts in Afghanistan and driving them from the country permanently.<ref name=\"Jeffrey Dressler 2010\">\"Jeffrey Dressler; The Haqqani Network, A Strategic Threat.\" Institute for the Study of War 2010.</ref> Currently the group demands that US and Coalition Forces, made up mostly of NATO Nations, withdraw from Afghanistan and no longer interfere with the politics or educational systems of Islamic nations.<ref name=\"Jeffrey Dressler 2010\" />\n\n==History==\nJalaluddin Haqqani joined the [[Hezb-i Islami Khalis]] in 1978 and becoming a [[mujahid]] in [[Afghanistan]]. His personal Haqqani group was nurtured by the U.S. [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA) and [[Pakistan]]'s [[Inter-Services Intelligence]] (ISI) during the 1980s [[Soviet\u2013Afghan War]].<ref name=\"ISN\">{{cite news|url=http://www.isn.ethz.ch/isn/Current-Affairs/ISN-Insights/Detail?lng=en&id=133042&contextid734=133042&contextid735=133041&tabid=133041&dynrel=40db1b50-7439-887d-706e-8ec00590bdb9,4888caa0-b3db-1461-98b9-e20e7b9c13d4,0c54e3b3-1e9c-be1e-2c24-a6a8c7060233|title=Questions Raised About Haqqani Network Ties with Pakistan|work=International Relations and Security Network|date=26 September 2011|accessdate=15 October 2011}}</ref><ref>Coll, Steve ''Ghost Wars'' (New York:Penguin, 2004) pp. 201-202</ref>\n\n===Haqqani family===\nThe Haqqani family hails from southeastern [[Afghanistan]] and belongs to the Mezi Clan of the [[Zadran (Pashtun tribe)|Zadran]] [[Pashtun tribes|Pashtun tribe]].<ref name=\"ISN\" /><ref name=fp20100603 /><ref name='at20111015' /> Jalalludin Haqqani rose to prominence as a senior military leader during the Soviet occupation of Afghanistan.<ref name='at20111015' /> Like [[Gulbuddin Hekmatyar]], Haqqani was more successful than other resistance leaders at forging relationships with outsiders prepared to sponsor resistance to the Soviets, including the CIA, [[Pakistan]]'s [[Inter-Services Intelligence]] (ISI), and wealthy Arab private donors from the [[Persian Gulf]].\n\n===Al-Qaeda affiliation===\nJalaluddin Haqqani commanded the Mujahideen Army from 1980\u20131992 and is credited with the recruitment of foreign fighters. Notable jihadists are two well-known Arabs, Abdullah Azzam and Osama bin Laden, who both began their careers as volunteers for the Haqqanis and trained to fight the Soviets. [[Al-Qa'ida]] and the Haqqani network, in other words evolved together, and they have remained intertwined throughout their history and remain so to this day.<ref name=\"Brown, V. 2012\">Brown, V.; Rassler, D.; ''Fountainhead of Jihad: The Haqqani Network, 1973\u20132012''. Columbia University Press 2013.</ref> The Haqqani network's relationship with [[Al-Qaeda]] dates back to the founding of AQ. The significant difference between the two organizations is that Al-Qaeda pursues global goals using global means; whereas Haqqani is solely interested in Afghanistan and the Pashtun Tribal regions. Jalaluddin Haqqani is more interested in the influence of Islamic Law over Afghanistan than the global Jihad but his network has always been fully aware of Al-Qaeda's intentions and goals.\n\nThese two groups are intertwined in tactics, strategy, and Islamic extremism; J. Haqqani realized the importance of Azzam\u2019s \"foundational Islamic legal decisions declaring the Afghan jihad a universally and individually binding duty borne by all Muslims worldwide.\"  Though many Muslim leaders asked for aid from oil wealthy Arab nations in 1978 when Afghan Communists with the backing of the Soviet Union conquered Kabul. J. Haqqani was the only Afghan Islamic Resistance leader to also request foreign Muslim fighters, and was the only group to welcome non-Afghans into its ranks. Thus \"linking it to the broader Jihad struggles and giving birth to the following decade to what would come to be known as global jihadism.\"<ref name=\"Brown, V. 2012\" /><ref name=\"Fountainhead of Jihad\">''Fountainhead of Jihad''</ref> It is the Haqqani network's use of the Saudi Arabian financiers and other Arab investors in his mission that clearly highlights the groups understanding of Global Jihad. A major difference between the Haqqani network and Al-Qaeda is the spheres of influence they both seek to control.<ref name=\"Brown, V. 2012\" /><ref name=\"Fountainhead of Jihad\" /> Al-Qaeda's is global, Haqqani's is regional.\n\n[[File:Insurgent Regions in Afghanistan and Pakistan.jpg|thumb|left|upright=2.0|Insurgent regions in Afghanistan and border regions of Pakistan, as of 2010]]\n\nMany sources believe Jalaluddin Haqqani and his forces assisted with the escape of Al-Qaeda into safe-havens in Pakistan. Considering how closely the two groups are inter-twined it is not a stretch. It is well documented that the Haqqani network did assist with the establishment of safe-havens. Analyst [[Peter Bergen]] argues this point in his book \"The Battle for Tora Bora\"<ref>\"The Battle for Tora Bora\"</ref><ref>Bergen, Peter; \"The Battle for Tora Bora.\" ''The New Republic'', 30 Dec 2009.</ref><ref>\"Al-Qaeda's Great Escape\"</ref><ref>\"Smucker, Philip; Al-Qaeda's Great Escape: The military and media on Terror's\" Dulles, Virginia, Bassey's 2004.</ref> Judging by the possibilities and the amount of US Military assets focused on such a small region, the theory that the Haqqani network aided in the escape seems reasonable. Regardless of exactly what occurred in those mountains, the Haqqanis played a role. And their actions of providing safe-havens for [[Al-Qaeda]] and [[Osama Bin Laden]] show the strength of bond and some role in or knowledge of Al-Qaeda and Bin Laden's escape.\n\n===Taliban affiliation===\nForeign jihadists recognized the network as a distinct entity as early as 1994, but Haqqani was not affiliated with the [[Taliban]] until they captured [[Kabul]] and assumed de facto control of [[Afghanistan]] in 1996.<ref name='rassler' /><ref name=\"hinduonnet 19030560\">{{cite news|title=The failing campaign: A relentless American campaign seeking to kill Maulvi [[Jalaluddin Haqqani]] rains bombs on civilians as the most powerful mujahideen remains elusive|work=[[The Hindu]]|first=Marc|last=Herold|date=February 2002|issue=3|volume=19 }}{{dead link|date=October 2011}}</ref> After the Taliban came to power, Haqqani accepted a cabinet-level appointment as Minister of Tribal Affairs.<ref name=\"AsiaTimes040505\">{{cite news|url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/Central_Asia/FE05Ag02.html|title=Through the eyes of the Taliban|newspaper=[[Asia Times]]|author=Syed Salaam Shahzaddate=5 May 2004|accessdate=10 February 2009}}</ref> Following the U.S.-led invasion of Afghanistan in 2001 and the subsequent overthrow of the Taliban government, the Haqqanis fled to the bordering Pakistani tribal regions and regrouped to fight against coalition forces across the border.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia-pacific/us-drone-strike-kills-haqqani-insider/2011/10/13/gIQA5rT3gL_story.html|title=U.S. steps up drone strikes in Pakistan against Haqqani network|work=The Washington Post|date=13 October 2011|accessdate=15 October 2011|first=Karen|last=DeYoung}}</ref> As Jalaluddin has grown older his son Sirajuddin has taken over the responsibility of military operations.<ref name=\"NYTimes2008-06-17\" /> Journalist [[Syed Saleem Shahzad]] reported that President [[Hamid Karzai]] invited c. 2002 the elder Haqqani to serve as [[Prime Minister of Afghanistan|Prime Minister]] in an attempt to bring \"moderate\" Taliban into the government. However, the offer was refused by Jalaluddin.<ref name=\"AsiaTimes040505\" />\n\n===United States===\nAccording to US military commanders, it is \"the most resilient enemy network\" and one of the biggest threats to the U.S.-led NATO forces and the Afghan government in the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|current war in Afghanistan]].<ref name=\"NYTimes2008-06-17\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/17/world/asia/17iht-17warlord.13756827.html |title=Old-Line Taliban Commander is Face of Rising Afghan Threa|work=The New York Times|first=Carlotta|last=Gall|authorlink=Carlotta Gall|date=17 June 2008|accessdate=10 February 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Partlow|first=Joshua|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia-pacific/haqqani-insurgent-group-proves-resilient-foe-in-afghan-war/2011/05/27/AG0wfKEH_story.html|title=Haqqani insurgent group proves resilient foe in Afghan war |work=The Washington Post|date=27 May 2011|accessdate=27 July 2011}}</ref> It is also the most lethal network in Afghanistan.<ref name=dressler>{{cite web|last=Dressler|first=Jeffrey|title=The Haqqani Network: A Foreign Terrorist Organization |url=http://www.understandingwar.org/sites/default/files/Backgrounder_Haqqani-FTO.pdf|publisher=ISW|accessdate=15 September 2012|date=5 September 2012}}</ref> Presently, the [[United States]] is offering a reward for information leading to the capture of their leader, [[Sirajuddin Haqqani]], in the amount of [[United States dollar|$]]5,000,000.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wanted Sirajuddin Haqqani Up to $5 Million Reward|publisher=Rewards for Justice|url=http://www.rewardsforjustice.net/index.cfm?page=haqqani |accessdate=9 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090822063810/http://www.rewardsforjustice.net/index.cfm?page=haqqani |archivedate=22 August 2009}}</ref>\n\n====Obama administration====\nIn September 2012, the Obama administration labeled the network as a [[foreign terrorist organization]].<ref name=nytimes20120907 /> After this announcement, Taliban issued a statement arguing that there is \"no separate entity or network in [[Afghanistan]] by the name of Haqqani\" and that [[Jalaluddin Haqqani]] is a member of [[Quetta Shura|the Quetta Shura]], Taliban's top leadership council.<ref name=lwjroggi>{{cite news|last=Roggio|first=Bill|title=Taliban call Haqqani Network a 'conjured entity'|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2012/09/taliban_call_haqqani.php|accessdate=10 September 2012|newspaper=Long War Journal|date=9 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Leadership===\n* [[Jalaluddin Haqqani]] \u2013 following his time as a commander in the Mujahideen Army (1980\u20131992), the network was founded under Haqqani during the insurgency against Soviet forces in Afghanistan during the 1980s. Haqqani himself was trained in Pakistan during the 1970s, in order to fight Prime Minister Mohammad Daud Khan, who had overthrown the previous ruler (and cousin), King Zahir Shah. During the Soviet invasion, the Pakistani government's Inter-Services Intelligence Agency became close with Haqqani and his organization, allowing them to become a main benefactor of American weapons, intelligence, and training. In the 1990s, Haqqani agreed to join the Taliban, arising to the position of Interior Minister. The United States attempted to convince Haqqani to sever ties with the Taliban, which he refused to do. In 2005 when Merjuddin Pathan was governor of the Khost Province, Haqqani approached him and wanting a dialogue with the Hamid Karzai Government, but neither Americans nor Karzai heeded the pleas of the governor. Afterwards when insurgency accentuated that  Hamid Karzai's leadership  in Afghanistan, approached Haqqani and offered him the position as Minister of Tribal Affairs in his cabinet, which Haqqani has also refused as it was too late. Since the emergence of the Haqqani Network, Haqqani and his family have thrived off of the contacts made by Haqqani during the Cold War.<ref>name=Lawrence, Kendall. \"The Haqqani Network.\" Threat Convergence Profile Series. The Fund For Peace. October 2011. Last accessed 10 July 2012.</ref> The BBC reported in July 2015 that Jalaluddin Haqqani had died of an illness and been buried in Afghanistan at least a year prior.<ref>{{cite news|title=Afghan militant leader Jalaluddin Haqqani 'has died'|date=31 July 2015|publisher=BBC |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-33740337|accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref> The Taliban rejected these reports.<ref>{{cite news|title=Taliban deny reports of Haqqani network founder's death|url=https://news.yahoo.com/taliban-deny-reports-haqqani-network-founders-death-072622210.html|accessdate=1 August 2015|publisher=AFP|date=1 August 2015}}</ref> On 3 September 2018, the Taliban released a statement via [[Twitter]] proclaiming Haqqani's death of an unspecified terminal illness.<ref>[https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/haqqani-network-s-founder-dies-after-long-illness-afghan-taliban-n906116 \"Haqqani network's founder dies after long illness, Afghan Taliban says\", by Alexander Smith and Mushtaq Yusufzai, NBC News]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/Zabihullah_4/status/1036806652874444800 |title=Archived copy |access-date=4 September 2018 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20180904025542/https://twitter.com/Zabihullah_4/status/1036806652874444800 |archive-date=4 September 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Sirajuddin Haqqani]] \u2013 He is one of Jalaluddin's sons and currently leads the day-to-day activities of the network. \n* Badruddin Haqqani \u2013 He was Sirajuddin's brother and an operational commander of the network. He was killed in a U.S. drone strike in Pakistan on 24 August 2012. Some Taliban commanders claimed the reports of his death were true while others claimed the reports were inaccurate.<ref name='et20110922'>{{cite news|first=Zia|last=Khan|title=Who on earth are the Haqqanis?|date=22 September 2011|newspaper=The Express Tribune News Network|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/257761/who-on-earth-are-the-haqqanis/|accessdate=23 September 2011}}</ref><ref name='et20120825'>{{cite news|title=Top Haqqani network militant 'killed in Pakistan'|date=25 August 2012|publisher=BBC|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-19378474|accessdate=25 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=state>{{cite news|title=Taliban deny report of Haqqani commander's death|url=http://www.thestate.com/2012/08/26/2413107/taliban-deny-report-of-haqqani.html#.UDnKIsFgKWY|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120827194434/http://www.thestate.com/2012/08/26/2413107/taliban-deny-report-of-haqqani.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=27 August 2012|accessdate=26 August 2012|newspaper=The State|date=26 August 2012|author=Rahim Faiez|author2=Rebecca Santana|agency=AP}}</ref><ref name=\"ap20120826\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/taliban-spokesman-denies-report-that-key-militant-commander-was-killed-in-drone-strike/2012/08/26/3cd5d248-ef46-11e1-b624-99dee49d8d67_story.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120826211555/http://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/taliban-spokesman-denies-report-that-key-militant-commander-was-killed-in-drone-strike/2012/08/26/3cd5d248-ef46-11e1-b624-99dee49d8d67_story.html|archive-date=26 August 2012|title=Afghanistan says sources confirm militant commander Badruddin Haqqani has been killed|work=The Washington Post|date=26 August 2012|agency=AP|accessdate=28 August 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> However, U.S. and Pakistani officials confirmed his death.<ref>{{cite news|author=Karen DeYoung |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-confirms-killing-of-haqqani-leader-in-pakistan/2012/08/29/e5973424-f20e-11e1-a612-3cfc842a6d89_story.html |title=U.S. confirms killing of Haqqani leader in Pakistan |work=The Washington Post |date=29 August 2012 |accessdate=11 October 2012}}</ref><ref name=time>{{cite news|title=Pakistani Officials Confirm Death of Key Militant |url=http://world.time.com/2012/08/30/pakistani-officials-confirm-death-of-key-militant/ |accessdate=31 August 2012 |newspaper=Time Magazine |date=30 August 2012 |agency=AP |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120903033736/http://world.time.com/2012/08/30/pakistani-officials-confirm-death-of-key-militant/ |archivedate=3 September 2012 }}</ref> The Taliban officially confirmed Badruddin's death a year later.<ref>{{cite web|author=Bill RoggioSeptember 8, 2013 |url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2013/09/taliban_confirm_deat_1.php |title=Taliban confirm death of Badruddin Haqqani in drone strike last year |work=The Long War Journal |date=2013-09-08 |accessdate=2014-08-18}}</ref>\n* Sangeen Zadran (killed 6 September 2013)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/09/06/us-pakistan-drone-idUSBRE98503S20130906|title=Taliban-linked militant killed in U.S. drone strike in Pakistan|date=6 September 2013|agency=Reuters|accessdate=6 September 2013}}</ref> \u2013 According to the US State Department, he was a senior lieutenant to Sirajuddin and the shadow governor for [[Paktika province]] in [[Afghanistan]]. He was also one of the captors of U.S. soldier [[Bowe Bergdahl]].<ref name='et20110922' /><ref>\"Designation of Haqqani Network Commander Sangeen Zadran.\" Office of the Spokesperson. 16 August 2011. http://www.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2011/08/170582.htm. Accessed 17 July 2012.</ref><ref name='afp20110816' /><ref name='state20110816' /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-201_162-57590189/afghan-taliban-offers-to-swap-captive-u.s-soldier-bowe-bergdahl-for-5-guantanamo-detainees/ |title=Afghan Taliban offers to swap captive U.S. soldier Bowe Bergdahl for 5 Guantanamo detainees|publisher=CBS News}}</ref>\n* Nasiruddin Haqqani \u2013 He was Sirajuddin's brother and a key financier and emissary of the network. As the son of Jalaluddin's Arab wife, he spoke fluent Arabic and traveled to Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates for fundraising.<ref name='et20110922' /><ref name='lwj20100722'>{{cite news|first=Bill|last=Roggio|authorlink=Bill Roggio|title=US adds Haqqani Network, Taliban leaders to list of designated terrorists|date=22 July 2010|publisher=Public Multimedia Inc.|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2010/07/us_adds_haqqani_netw.php|work=The Long War Journal|accessdate=1 November 2011}}</ref> He was killed by unknown assailants in Islamabad, Pakistan, on 11 November 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last=Khan |first=Tahir |url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/630360/senior-haqqani-network-leader-killed-near-islamabad/ |title=Senior Haqqani Network leader killed near Islamabad |work=The Express Tribune |date= |accessdate=2014-08-18}}</ref>\n* [[Ahmad Jan (Taliban governor)|Maulvi Ahmad Jan]] (killed 21 November 2013)<ref name=yahooafp>{{cite news|url=https://news.yahoo.com/first-us-drone-strike-pakistans-khyber-pakhtunkhwa-kills-041441452.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131124032159/http://news.yahoo.com/first-us-drone-strike-pakistans-khyber-pakhtunkhwa-kills-041441452.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=24 November 2013|title=US drone strike kills senior Haqqani leader in Pakistan|author=S.B. Shah|publisher=[[Agence France-Presse]]|date=21 November 2013|accessdate=5 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The network's spiritual leader who was also responsible for organizing some of the network's most deadly attacks in Afghanistan.<ref name=\"yahooafp\" />  He was subjected to UN sanctions<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/News/Press/docs/2012/sc10805.doc.htm|title=Security Council 1988 Sanctions Committee Adds Individual Abdul Rauf Zakir,|publisher=United Nations|accessdate=20 May 2015}}</ref> in March 2010<ref name=uooafb>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/Todays-News-2-216246-Who-was-Maulvi-Ahmad-Jan-the-droned-Haqqani-leader|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131125140056/http://www.thenews.com.pk/Todays-News-2-216246-Who-was-Maulvi-Ahmad-Jan-the-droned-Haqqani-leader|url-status=dead|archive-date=25 November 2013|title=Who was Maulvi Ahmad Jan, the droned Haqqani leader?|author=Amir Mir|publisher=The News International|date=25 November 2013|accessdate=5 December 2013}}</ref> and had also served the Taliban government of Mullah Omar as federal minister for water and power,<ref name=uooafb /> before being appointed the Governor of the Zabul Province in 2000.<ref name=uooafb /> At the time of his death, Jan was thought be Sirajuddin Haqqani's chief deputy.<ref name=uooafb />\n* Abdul Aziz Abbasin \u2013 According to the U.S. Treasury, he is \"a key commander in the Haqqani Network\" and serves as the \"Taliban shadow governor of [[Orgun District]], [[Paktika Province]], Afghanistan.\"<ref name='treasury20110929'>{{cite web|url=http://www.treasury.gov/press-center/press-releases/Pages/tg1316.aspx|title=Treasury Continues Efforts Targeting Terrorist Organizations Operating in Afghanistan and Pakistan|accessdate=29 September 2011|date=29 September 2011|publisher=U.S. Department of Treasury}}</ref>\n* Haji Mali Khan \u2013 According to NATO, he is \"the senior Haqqani commander in Afghanistan\" and is uncle to Sirajuddin and Badaruddin.<ref name='ft20111001'>{{cite news|title=Haqqani leader captured in Afghanistan|date=1 October 2011|url= http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/0/7da32c2a-ec2d-11e0-8c66-00144feab49a.html#axzz1bQDJGyc2|work=Financial Times|accessdate=21 October 2011}}</ref><ref name='npr20111001'>{{cite news| title=NATO: Haqqani Leader Captured in Afghanistan|date=1 October 2011|url=https://www.npr.org/2011/10/01/140973497/nato-senior-haqqani-leader-captured-in-afghanistan| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002043542/http://www.npr.org/2011/10/01/140973497/nato-senior-haqqani-leader-captured-in-afghanistan| url-status=dead|archive-date=2 October 2011| work=NPR| accessdate=21 October 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=30 June 2011|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-13971385|title=Nato 'kills senior Haqqani militant in Afghanistan'|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> ISAF also reported that he acted as an emissary between [[Baitullah Mehsud]] and the Haqqanis.<ref name=lwj20111101 /> He was captured by ISAF forces on 27 September 2011.<ref name='npr20111001' /> He was released in a prisoner swap in November 2019.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/19/world/asia/afghanistan-taliban-prisoner-exchange-peace-talks.html</ref>\n\nFollowing [[WikiLeaks]]' July 2010 publication of 75,000 classified documents the public learned that Sirajuddin Haqqani was in the tier one of the [[International Security Assistance Force]]'s Joint Prioritized Effects List \u2013 its \"kill or capture\" list.<ref name=DerSpeigel2010-07-26>{{cite news |url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/0,1518,708393,00.html |title=The Helpless Germans: War Logs Illustrate Lack of Progress in Bundeswehr Deployment |author1=Matthias Gebauer |author2=John Goetz |author3=Hans Hoyng |author4=Susanne Koelbl |author5=Marcel Rosenbach |author6=Gregor Peter Schmitz |newspaper=[[Der Spiegel]] |date=26 July 2010 |accessdate=15 August 2010 |quote=Sirajuddin Haqqani is also associated with the foreign jihadists. Haqqani, known as 'Siraj,' is the son of the legendary Afghan mujahedeen leader [[Jalaluddin Haqqani]]. Together with the Taliban and Hekmatyar, the Haqqani clan of warlords are among the three greatest opponents of Western forces in Afghanistan. In the digital war logs, his name appeared in 'Tier 1' on a list of targets to be killed or taken captive, which qualified him as one of the Western alliance's most wanted terrorists. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100728174357/http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/0,1518,708393,00.html |archivedate=28 July 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Activities==\nAnand Gopal of the ''[[Christian Science Monitor]]'', citing unnamed US and Afghan sources, reported in June 2009 that the leadership is based in [[Miranshah]], [[North Waziristan]] in the [[Federally Administered Tribal Areas]] of Pakistan along the Afghan border.<ref name=\"CSM1\" /> It operates from at least three compounds: a Miranshah bazaar camp containing a madrassa and computer facilities, a compound in the nearby suburb of Sarai Darpa Khel and another compound in Danday Darpa Khel, where some of Jalaluddin's family stay.<ref name=fp20100603>{{cite web|url= http://afpak.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2010/06/03/inside_the_haqqani_network_0|title=Inside the Haqqani network|accessdate =23 November 2011|last=Gopal|first=Anand|author2=Mansur Khan Mahsud |author3=Brian Fishman |date=3 June 2010|work=Foreign Policy|publisher=The Slate Group, LLC}}</ref> The network is active in Afghanistan's southeastern areas of [[Paktia Province]], [[Paktika Province]], [[Khost Province]], [[Wardak Province]], [[Logar Province]], and [[Ghazni Province]].<ref name=\"CSM1\" /> In September 2011, Sirajuddin Haqqani told [[Reuters]] that the group feels \"more secure in Afghanistan besides the Afghan people.\"<ref name=\"et\" />\n\n===Publications===\nThe Haqqanis have been described as notable writers, having published a number of books as well as editing and contributing to magazines, three of them, ''Manba\u2019 al-Jihad'' (one version in Pashto and another in Arabic) and ''Nusrat al-Jihad'' (\u201cSupport for Jihad,\u201d in Urdu), totalizing more than 1000 pages between 1989 and 1993.<ref>Vahid Brown and Don Rassler, ''Fountainhead of Jihad: The Haqqani Nexus, 1973-2012'', Oxford University Press (2013), p. 14</ref>\n\n===Funding===\nSome of Sirajuddin's brothers travel to the [[Persian Gulf]] region to raise funds from wealthy donors.<ref name=fp20100603 /><ref name='et20110922' /> ''The New York Times'' reported in September 2011 that the Haqqanis have set up a \"ministate\" in Miranshah with courts, tax offices and madrassas, and that the network runs a series of front companies selling automobiles and real estate. They also receive funds from extortion, [[Child abduction|kidnappings]] and smuggling operations throughout eastern [[Afghanistan]].<ref name=fp20100603 /> In an interview a former Haqqani commander called the extortion \"the most important source of funding for the Haqqanis.\"<ref name='nytimes20110924'>{{cite news|first=Mark|last=Mazzetti |author2=Scott Shane |author3=Alissa J. Rubin |title=Brutal Haqqani Crime Clan Bedevils U.S. in Afghanistan|date=24 September 2011 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/25/world/asia/brutal-haqqani-clan-bedevils-united-states-in-afghanistan.html|work=The New York Times|accessdate=27 September 2011}}</ref> According to a tribal elder in [[Paktika Province|Paktia]], \"Haqqani's people ask for [[Afghan afghani|money]] from contractors working on road construction. They are asking [[Afghan afghani|money]] or goods from shopkeepers\u2026 District elders and contractors are paying [[Afghan afghani|money]] to Afghan workers, but sometimes half of the [[Afghan afghani|money]] will go to Haqqani's people.\"<ref name='ap20091229'>{{cite news|first=Nahal|last=Toosi|title=Haqqani network challenges US-Pakistan relations|date=29 December 2009 |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2010624388_apaspakistanhandlingthehaqqanis.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130130030439/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2010624388_apaspakistanhandlingthehaqqanis.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=30 January 2013|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=25 October 2011|work=The Seattle Times}}</ref>\n\n===Military strength===\nHaqqani is reported to run his own training camps, to recruit his own foreign fighters, and to seek out financial and logistic support on his own, from his old contacts.<ref name=\"NYTimes2008-06-17\" /> Estimates of the Haqqanis's numbers vary. A 2009 ''New York Times'' article indicates that they are thought to have about 4,000 to 12,000 Taliban under their command while a 2011 report from the [[Combating Terrorism Center]] places its strength roughly at 10,000-15,000.<ref name='rassler' /><ref name=\"nytimes 15haqqani\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/15/world/asia/15haqqani.html |title=Rebuffing U.S., Pakistan Balks at Crackdown|work=The New York Times|date=14 December 2009|first=Jane|last=Perlez}}</ref> During a September 2011 interview, Sirajuddin Haqqani said the figure of 10,000 fighters, as quoted in some media reports, \"is actually less than the actual number.\"<ref name=\"et\" /> Throughout its history the network's operations have been conducted by small, semi-autonomous units organized according to tribal and sub-tribal affiliations often at the direction of and with the logistical support of Haqqani commanders.<ref name='rassler' />\n\nThe network is comprised broadly of four groups: those who have been with Jalalludin since the Soviet-era jihad, those from [[Loya Paktiya]] who have joined since 2001, those from North Waziristan who have joined in more recent years, and foreign militants of primarily Arab, Chechen and Uzbek origins. Leadership roles are mostly filled with personnel from the first group while the relative neophytes from Loya Paktia and non-Pushtuns are not part of this inner circle.<ref name=fp20100603 /><ref name='at20111015'>{{cite news|first=Amir|last=Mir|title=Haqqanis sidestep US terror list|date=15 October 2011|url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/South_Asia/MJ15Df01.html|work=Asia Times Online| accessdate=28 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Haqqani network pioneered the use of suicide attacks in Afghanistan and tend to use mostly foreign bombers whereas the Taliban tend to rely on locals in attacks.<ref name=CSM1 /> The network, according to the ''[[National Journal]]'', supplies much of the [[potassium chlorate]] used in bombs employed by the Taliban in Afghanistan. Also, the network's bombs use more sophisticated remote triggering devices than the pressure-plated activators used elsewhere in Afghanistan. Sirajuddin Haqqani told [[MSNBC]] in April 2009 that his fighters had, \"acquired the modern technology that we were lacking, and we have mastered new and innovative methods of making bombs and explosives.\"<ref>[[Yochi Dreazen|Dreazen, Yochi J.]], \"The New Enemy\", ''[[National Journal]]'', 16 July 2011.</ref>\n\nIn late 2011, a 144-page book attributed to Sirajuddin Haqqani began circulating in Afghanistan and Pakistan. Described by ''Newsweek'' as a \"manual for guerrillas and terrorists,\" the Pashto-language book details instructions on setting up a jihadi cell, receiving financing, recruiting and training. The manual advises recruits that parental permission is not necessary for jihad, that all debts should be paid before joining, and that suicide bombings and beheadings are allowed by Islam.<ref name='db20111114'>{{cite news|first=Ron|last=Moreau|author2=Sami Yousafzai|title=Dueling Manifestos|date=14 November 2011|publisher=The Newsweek|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2011/11/13/afghanistan-haqqani-s-jihad-manual-the-secret-taliban-letter.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111114114846/http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2011/11/13/afghanistan-haqqani-s-jihad-manual-the-secret-taliban-letter.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 November 2011|work=The Daily Beast|accessdate=23 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Attacks and alleged attacks===\n* 14 January 2008: The [[2008 Kabul Serena Hotel attack]] is thought to have been carried out by the network.<ref name=\"NYTimes2008-06-17\" />\n* March 2008: Kidnapping of British journalist [[Sean Langan]] was blamed on the network.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/jun/21/new-york-times-reporter-taliban Kidnapped US reporter makes dramatic escape from Taliban], [[The Guardian]], 21 June 2009</ref>\n* 27 April 2008: [[Assassination attempts on Hamid Karzai]].<ref name=\"CSM1\" />\n* 7 July 2008: US intelligence blamed the network for [[2008 Indian embassy bombing in Kabul]].<ref name=WP1 />\n* 10 November 2008: The [[Kidnapping of David Rohde]] was blamed on Sirajuddin Haqqani.<ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/Blotter/story?id=7895078&page=1 Taliban Wanted $25 Million for Life of New York Times Reporter], [[ABC News]], 22 June 2009</ref>\n* 30 December 2009: [[Camp Chapman attack]] is thought to have been carried out by the network.<ref>[http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/31b2dd72-f898-11de-beb8-00144feab49a.html Pakistan urges united reaction after CIA blast], [[Financial Times]], 3 January 2010</ref>\n* 18 May 2010: [[May 2010 Kabul bombing]] was allegedly carried out by the network.<ref name=\"LWJ20100524\">{{cite web|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2010/05/haqqani_network_exec.php|title=Haqqani Network executed Kabul suicide attack|last=Rogio|first=Bill|date=24 May 2010|publisher=[[Public Multimedia]]|accessdate=25 May 2010}}</ref>\n* 19 February 2011: [[Kabul Bank]] in [[Jalalabad]], Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.pajhwok.com/en/2011/06/15/haqqani-network-threatens-attacks-judges|title=Haqqani network threatens attacks on judges|publisher=Pajhwok Afghan News|date=15 June 2011|accessdate=27 July 2011}}</ref>\n* 28 June 2011: According to [[ISAF]], elements of the Haqqani network provided \"material support\" in the [[Hotel Inter-Continental Kabul#2011 attack|2011 attack on the Hotel Inter-Continental]] in Kabul.<ref>[[Bill Roggio|Roggio, Bill]], \"[http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2011/06/isaf_airstrike_kills.php ISAF airstrike kills senior Haqqani Network commander involved in Kabul hotel attack]\", ''[[Long War Journal]]'', 30 June 2011.</ref> The Taliban claimed responsibility.<ref>{{cite news|first=Safeeyah|last=Kharsany|author2=Mujib Mashal|title=Manager gives account of Kabul hotel attack|date=29 June 2011|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/asia/2011/06/2011629122328109278.html|work=Al Jazeera| accessdate=15 September 2011}}</ref>\n* 10 September 2011: A massive truck bomb exploded outside Combat Outpost Sayed Abad in Wardak province, Afghanistan, killing five Afghans, including four civilians, and wounding 77 U.S. soldiers, 14 Afghan civilians, and three policemen. The Pentagon blamed the network for the attack.<ref>Jelinek, Pauline ([[Associated Press]]), \"[https://archive.today/20120717175624/http://www.armytimes.com/news/2011/09/ap-afghanistan-us-says-haqqani-behind-bombing-091211/ Haqqani group behind Afghan bombing, U.S. says]\", ''[[Military Times]]'', 12 September 2011.</ref>\n* 12 September 2011: US Ambassador [[Ryan Crocker]] blamed the Haqqani network for an attack on the US Embassy and nearby NATO bases in Kabul. The attack lasted 19 hours and resulted in the deaths of four police officers and four civilians. 17 civilians and six NATO soldiers were injured. Three coalition soldiers were killed. Eleven insurgent attackers were killed.<ref name='nyt20110914'>{{cite news|first=Alissa J|last=Rubin|author2=Ray Rivera |author3=Jack Healy |title=U.S. Blames Kabul Assault on Pakistan-Based Group|date=14 September 2011|publisher=The New York Times Company|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/15/world/asia/us-blames-kabul-assault-on-pakistan-based-group.html|work=The New York Times| accessdate=14 September 2011}}</ref>\n* October 2011: Afghanistan's [[National Directorate of Security]] said that six people arrested in an alleged plot to assassinate President Karzai had ties to the Haqqani network.<ref name='aljazeera20111005'>{{cite news|title=Six arrested over 'Karzai death plot'|date=5 October 2011|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/asia/2011/10/2011105125621748395.html| work=Al Jazeera|accessdate=12 October 2011}}</ref>\n* 15 April 2012: Haqqani network fighters initiate the summer fighting season, conducting a complex attack across Kabul, Logar and Paktia provinces.  Several western embassies in Kabul were attacked in the Say Wallah district.\n* 1 June 2012: A massive suicide truck bomb breaches the southern perimeter wall of US [[Forward Operating Base Salerno]] in Khost province.  A dozen Haqqani fighters wearing suicide vests entered the breach, but were isolated and killed by US Forces.\n* 31 May 2017: [[May 2017 Kabul attack|a truck bomb exploded]] in a crowded intersection in [[Kabul]], Afghanistan, near the German embassy,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-40102903 |title=Kabul bomb: Dozens killed in Afghan capital's diplomatic zone |date=31 May 2017 |work=BBC News |access-date=31 May 2017 |language=en-GB |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531060542/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-40102903 |archivedate=31 May 2017 }}</ref> killing over 150 and injuring 413,<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/31/world/asia/kabul-explosion-afghanistan.html |title=Huge Bombing in Kabul Is One of Afghan War\u2019s Worst |last=Mashal |first=Mujib |date=31 May 2017 |work=The New York Times |access-date=31 May 2017 |last2=Abed |first2=Fahim |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531053728/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/31/world/asia/kabul-explosion-afghanistan.html |archivedate=31 May 2017 }}</ref> mostly civilians, and damaging several buildings in the embassy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tolonews.com/afghanistan/rs-claims-police-stopped-truck-entering-green-zone |title=RS Claims Police Stopped Truck From Entering Green Zone |publisher=Tolonews |accessdate=31 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531111332/http://www.tolonews.com/afghanistan/rs-claims-police-stopped-truck-entering-green-zone |archivedate=31 May 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.rt.com/news/390254-afghan-blast-kabul-embassies/ |title=Kabul blast: At least 80 killed & over 350 wounded in explosion in Afghan capital\u2019s embassy district |work=RT International |access-date=31 May 2017 |language=en-US |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531091216/https://www.rt.com/news/390254-afghan-blast-kabul-embassies/ |archivedate=31 May 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/31/asia/kabul-explosion-hits-diplomatic-area/index.html |title=Afghanistan explosion: 80 killed in blast near diplomatic area |author1=Ehsan Popalzai |author2=Faith Karimi |website=CNN |access-date=31 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531061825/http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/31/asia/kabul-explosion-hits-diplomatic-area/index.html |archivedate=31 May 2017 }}</ref> The attack was the deadliest terror attack to take place in Kabul. Afghanistan's intelligence agency [[National Directorate of Security|NDS]] claimed that the blast was planned by the Haqqani Network.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kabul bomb: Afghans blame Haqqani and Pakistan|url=http://news.sky.com/story/kabul-bombing-afghans-blame-haqqani-network-and-pakistan-10900078|website=Sky News}}</ref><ref name=\"Gul\">{{cite web|last1=Gul|first1=Ayaz|title=Deadly Truck Bomb Rocks Kabul|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/massive-car-bomb-in-kabul/3878752.html|website=VOA|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nThe Haqqani network operates in the Federally Administered Tribal Areas (FATA) in Northern Pakistan, near the southeastern border of Afghanistan.<ref>\"Threat Convergence Profile Series: The Haqqani Network.\"</ref><ref>Lawrence, Kendall. \"Threat Convergence Profile Series: The Haqqani Network.\" The Fund For Peace. June 2010. p. 3. <http://www.fundforpeace.org/global/library/ttcvr1127-threatconvergence-haqqani-11b.pdf {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140726005609/http://www.fundforpeace.org/global/library/ttcvr1127-threatconvergence-haqqani-11b.pdf |date=26 July 2014 }}</ref> The network has used the ambiguity of the FATA to cloak its activities and avoid interference. The strategy worked well until President Obama ramped up [[UAV]] strikes in the Northern Waziristan region. The organizational headquarters is supposedly in Miram Shah, where the group operates base camps to facilitate activities such as weapons acquisitions, logistical planning and military strategy formulation. Haqqani-controlled regions of northern Pakistan have also served as strategic safe-havens for other Islamic militant organizations, such as [[Al-Qaeda]], the [[Pakistani Taliban]] (TTP), [[Jaish-e-Mohammad]] (JeM), [[Lashkar-e-Taiba]] (LeT), and members of the [[Islamic Movement of Uzbekistan]] (IMU). The strategic location of the Haqqani network facilitates interaction between many of the insurgent groups. <ref>\"Inside the Haqqani Network.\"</ref><ref>\"Inside the Haqqani Network.\" Foreign Policy Group. 3 June 2010. <http:b//afpak.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2010/06/03/inside_the_haqqani_network_0</ref>\n\n[[File:ISAF image Insurgent Routes.jpg|Insurgent Routes of Infiltration from training camps in Pakistan|thumb|right|upright=2.0]]\n\nThe Haqqani network's tribal connections in Northern Waziristan and the de facto regime that it has established with courts, law enforcement, medical care, and governance have often brought it great support from locals.<ref name=\"Brown, V. 2012\" /> Its familiarity of terrain, such as mountain passes, also grants them excellent access between Afghanistan and Pakistan.\n\nIn September 2011, Sirajuddin Haqqani claimed during a telephonic interview to [[Reuters]] that the Haqqani network no longer maintained sanctuaries in northwestern Pakistan and the robust presence that it once had there and instead now felt safer in Afghanistan: \"Gone are the days when we were hiding in the mountains along the Pakistan-Afghanistan border. Now we consider ourselves more secure in Afghanistan besides the Afghan people.\"<ref name=\"et\">{{cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/254368/no-haqqani-network-sanctuaries-in-pakistan-sirajuddin/|title=No sanctuaries in Pakistan\u2019: Haqqani network shifts base to Afghanistan|work=Express Tribune|date=18 September 2011|accessdate=20 September 2011}}</ref> According to Haqqani, there were \"senior military and police officials\" who are aligned with the group and there are even sympathetic and \"sincere people in the Afghan government who are loyal to the Taliban\" who support the group's aim of liberating Afghanistan \"from the clutches of occupying forces.\"<ref name=\"et\" /> In response to questions from the BBC's Pashto service, Siraj denied any links to the ISI and stated that Mullah Omar is \"our leader and we totally obey him.\"<ref name='bbc20111003'>{{cite news|title=Haqqani network denies killing Afghan envoy Rabbani|date=3 October 2010|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-15143513|work=BBC|accessdate=3 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Alleged Pakistani involvement==\n{{See also|Pakistan\u2013United States relations}}\nWhile some Afghan and American officials accuse Pakistan of harboring the Haqqani network, Pakistan has denied any links.<ref>{{cite news|title=What Is the Haqqani Network?|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/what-haqqani-network/3883271.html}}</ref>\n\nAbdul Rashid Waziri, a specialist at Kabul's Center for Regional Studies of Afghanistan, explains that links between the Haqqani network and Pakistan can be traced back to the mid-1970s,<ref name=\"ISN\" /> before the 1978 [[Saur Revolution|Marxist revolution]] in [[Kabul]]. During the rule of President [[Mohammed Daoud Khan|Daoud Khan]] in Afghanistan (1973\u201378), [[Jalaluddin Haqqani]] went into exile and based himself in and around [[Miranshah]], Pakistan.<ref name='iswprofile'>{{cite web |url=http://www.understandingwar.org/themenode/haqqani-network|title=Haqqani Network|accessdate=17 October 2011|publisher=The [[Institute for the Study of War]]}}</ref> From there he began to form a rebellion against the government of Daoud Khan in 1975.<ref name=\"ISN\" /> The network allegedly maintains ties with the [[Inter-Services Intelligence]] (ISI), and Pakistan's army had been reportedly reluctant to move against them in the past.<ref name=NYTimes2008-06-17 /><ref name=\"nytimes080909\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/09/world/asia/09iht-09pstan.15996896.html|title=U.S. attack on Taliban kills 23 in Pakistan|work=The New York Times|date=9 September 2008|accessdate=27 July 2011|first1=Jane|last1=Perlez}}</ref>\n\nHowever, recently there has been a paradigm shift within the Pakistani military and as of 2014 a massive military offensive launched in North Waziristan, named [[Operation Zarb-e-Azb]] has targeted all militants including the Haqqanni network. The operation is currently on-going and is commanded by General Qamar Javed Bajwa.<ref name=\"Express News\">{{cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/786641/us-commander-commends-zarb-e-azb-for-disrupting-haqqani-networks-ability-to-target-afghanistan/|title=US commander commends Zarb-e-Azb for disrupting Haqqani network's ability to target Afghanistan|work=Express News|date=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n''The New York Times'' reported in September 2008 that Pakistan regards the Haqqani as an important force for protecting its interests in Afghanistan in the event of American withdrawal from there and therefore is unwilling to move against them.<ref name=\"nytimes080909\" /> Pakistan presumably{{by whom|date=October 2011}} feels pressured that India, Russia, and Iran are gaining a foothold in Afghanistan. Since it lacks the financial clout of the other countries, Pakistan hopes that by being a sanctuary for the Haqqani network, it can assert some influence over its turbulent neighbor. In the words of a retired senior Pakistani official: \"[We] have no money. All we have are the crazies. So the crazies it is.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Snake country|url=http://www.economist.com/node/21531042|accessdate=8 January 2013|newspaper=The Economist|date=1 October 2011|location=Islamabad}}</ref> ''The New York Times'' and [[Al Jazeera]] later reported in June 2010 that Pakistan's Army chief General [[Ashfaq Parvez Kayani]] and chief of the ISI General [[Ahmad Shuja Pasha]] were in talks with Afghan President [[Hamid Karzai]] to broker a power-sharing agreement between the Haqqani network and the Afghan government.<ref name=\"nyt20100624\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/25/world/asia/25islamabad.html|title=Pakistan Is Said to Pursue Foothold in Afghanistan|last=Perlez|first=Jane|author2=Gall, Carlotta|date=24 June 2010|work=The New York Times|accessdate=29 June 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"aje20100628\">{{cite web|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/asia/2010/06/20106277582708497.html|title=Karzai 'holds talks' with Haqqani|date=28 June 2010|publisher=[[Al Jazeera English]]|accessdate=29 June 2010}}</ref> Reacting to this report both President [[Barack Obama]] and CIA director [[Leon Panetta]] responded with skepticism that such an effort could succeed.<ref name=\"nyt20100627\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/28/world/asia/28taliban.html|title=Pakistan\u2019s Plan on Afghan Peace Leaves U.S. Wary| last=Shane| first=Scott|date=27 June 2010|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=29 June 2010}}</ref> The effort to mediate between the Haqqanis and the Afghan government was launched by Pakistan after intense pressure by the US to take military action against the group in [[North Waziristan]].<ref name=\"dawn20100616\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/wps/wcm/connect/dawn-content-library/dawn/the-newspaper/front-page/35-Pakistan-trying-to-broker-Afghan-deal-ak-03 |title=Pakistan trying to broker Afghan deal |last=Syed |first=Baqir Sajjad |date=16 June 2010 |publisher=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]] |accessdate=29 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619081056/http://www.dawn.com/wps/wcm/connect/dawn-content-library/dawn/the-newspaper/front-page/35-Pakistan-trying-to-broker-Afghan-deal-ak-03 |archivedate=19 June 2010}}</ref> Karzai later denied meeting anyone from the Haqqani network.<ref name=\"afp20100629\">{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5iZlFFvVcAbhdUv3PV9UHCLH4FBnQ|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130125034721/http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5iZlFFvVcAbhdUv3PV9UHCLH4FBnQ|url-status=dead|archive-date=25 January 2013|title=Kabul dismisses report Karzai met militant leader|date=29 June 2010|publisher=[[Agence France-Presse]]| accessdate=30 June 2010}}</ref> Subsequently, Kayani also denied that he took part in the talks.<ref name=\"dawn20100702\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/wps/wcm/connect/dawn-content-library/dawn/the-newspaper/front-page/kayani-says-he-did-not-broker-karzais-talks-with-haqqani-270 |title=Kayani says he did not broker Karzai\u2019s talks with Haqqani |date=2 July 2010 |work=Dawn |accessdate=2 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100703231827/http://www.dawn.com/wps/wcm/connect/dawn-content-library/dawn/the-newspaper/front-page/kayani-says-he-did-not-broker-karzais-talks-with-haqqani-270 |archivedate=3 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nAnti-American groups of [[Gul Bahadur]] and Haqqani carry out their activities in Afghanistan and use North [[Waziristan]] as rear.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://outlookafghanistan.net/topics?post_id=669 |title=Militant Networks in North Waziristan |publisher=OutlookAfghanistan.net |date=26 May 2011 |accessdate=27 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723235021/http://outlookafghanistan.net/topics?post_id=669 |archivedate=23 July 2011 }}</ref> The group's links to Pakistan have been a sour point in [[Pakistan \u2013 United States relations]]. In September 2011, the [[Obama administration]] warned Pakistan that it must do more to cut ties with the Haqqani network and help eliminate its leaders, adding that \"the United States will act unilaterally if Pakistan does not comply.\"<ref name='wapo20110921'>{{cite news| first=Karen|last=DeYoung|title=U.S. sharpens warning to Pakistan|date=21 September 2011|url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-sharpens-warning-to-pakistan/2011/09/20/gIQAdqlNjK_story.html?wpisrc=al_national|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=21 September 2011}}</ref> In testimony before a [[US Senate]] panel, Admiral [[Mike Mullen]] stated that the network \"acts as a veritable arm of Pakistan's [[Inter-Services Intelligence Agency]].\"<ref name='bbc20110922b'>{{cite news|title=Pakistan 'backed Haqqani attack on Kabul' \u2013 Mike Mullen|date=22 September 2011|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-15024344|work=BBC|accessdate=22 September 2011}}</ref> Although some U.S. officials allege that the ISI supports and guides the Haqqanis,<ref name='bbc20110922b' /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.yahoo.com/pakistan-condemns-us-comments-spy-agency-044440789.html;_ylt=A2KJ3vVYX3xOdRkA9EZXNyoA?rnd=005681253004174930714413 |title=Pakistan condemns US comments about spy agency |agency=Associated Press |date=23 September 2011 |accessdate=23 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130727053454/http://news.yahoo.com/pakistan-condemns-us-comments-spy-agency-044440789.html;_ylt=A2KJ3vVYX3xOdRkA9EZXNyoA?rnd=005681253004174930714413 |archivedate=27 July 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2011/09/18/clinton-presses-pakistan-to-help-fight-haqqani-insurgent-group/|title=Clinton Presses Pakistan to Help Fight Haqqani Insurgent Group|publisher=Fox News|date=18 September 2011|accessdate=21 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=US-blames-Pakistan>{{cite news|url=https://news.yahoo.com/pakistan-isi-urged-attacks-u-targets-officials-002201562.html |title=U.S. blames Pakistan agency in Kabul attack |publisher=Reuters |date=22 September 2011 |accessdate=22 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110925075845/http://news.yahoo.com/pakistan-isi-urged-attacks-u-targets-officials-002201562.html |archivedate=25 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/09/17/us-pakistan-usa-haqqani-idUSTRE78G1RM20110917|title=U.S. links Pakistan to group it blames for Kabul attack|date=17 September 2011|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=21 September 2011}}</ref> President [[Barack Obama]] declined to endorse that position and stated that \"the intelligence is not as clear as we might like in terms of what exactly that relationship is\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/world/obama-wont-back-mullens-claim-on-pakistan-137813|title=Obama won't back Mullen's claim on Pakistan|date=1 October 2011|work=NDTV|accessdate=20 May 2015}}</ref> and [[US Secretary of State]] [[Hillary Clinton]] said \"We have no evidence of\" Pakistani involvement in attacks on the [[Embassy of the United States, Kabul|US embassy in Kabul]].<ref>[https://archive.today/20111023235027/http://www.dawn.com/2011/10/22/pakistan-urged-to-play-role-of-peacemaker-clinton-demands-action-in-days-and-weeks-2.html Clinton demands action in \u2018days and weeks\u2019]</ref>\n\nPakistan in return rejected the notion that it maintained ties with the Haqqani network or used it in a policy of waging a [[proxy war]] in neighboring Afghanistan. Pakistani officials deny the allegations by asserting that Pakistan had no relations with the network. In response to the allegations, [[Ministry of Interior (Pakistan)|Interior Minister]] [[Rehman Malik]] claimed that the [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA) had \"trained and produced\" the Haqqani network and other [[mujahideen]] during the [[Soviet\u2013Afghan War]].<ref name=\"TOI\">{{cite news|title=Defiant Pak refuses to go after Haqqanis| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-09-27/pakistan/30207711_1_haqqani-network-pakistan-army-north-waziristan| archive-url=https://archive.today/20130127001651/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-09-27/pakistan/30207711_1_haqqani-network-pakistan-army-north-waziristan| url-status=dead| archive-date=27 January 2013|work=Times of India|date=27 September 2011|accessdate=27 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"dawn\">{{cite news|title=CIA created Haqqani network: Rehman Malik|url=http://www.dawn.com/2011/09/25/cia-created-haqqani-network-rehman-malik.html|date=25 September 2011|work=Dawn|accessdate=26 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"tribune\">{{cite news|title=Haqqani network created by the CIA: Rehman Malik|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/260065/haqqani-network-created-by-the-cia-rehman-malik/|date=25 September 2011|work=Tribune|accessdate=26 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"thenews\">{{cite news|title=CIA, not Pakistan, created Haqqani network: Malik|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/TodaysPrintDetail.aspx?ID=9102&Cat=13|date=26 September 2011|publisher=The News|accessdate=26 September 2011}}</ref> The Pakistani interior minister also warned that any incursion on Pakistani territory by U.S. forces will not be tolerated. A Pakistani intelligence official insisted that the American allegations are part of \"pressure tactics\" used by the United States as a strategy \"to shift the war theatre.\"<ref name=tribune20110923>{{cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/257977/pakistan-warns-us-no-boots-on-our-ground/|title=Brittle relations: Islamabad \u2018vehemently\u2019 rejects US \u2018proxy war\u2019 claims|work=Express Tribune|date=22 September 2011|accessdate=23 September 2011}}</ref> An unnamed Pakistani official was reported to have said after a meeting of the nation's top military officials that \"We have already conveyed to the US that Pakistan cannot go beyond what it has already done\".<ref>Zirulnick, Ariel. [http://www.csmonitor.com/World/terrorism-security/2011/0926/Pakistan-refuses-to-battle-Haqqani-network \"Pakistan refuses to battle Haqqani network.\"] ''[[The Christian Science Monitor]]'', 26 September 2011.</ref> However, Pakistani claims were contradicted by the network's warnings against any U.S. military incursions into [[North Waziristan]].<ref name=\"TOI\" /><ref name=\"tribune\" /> However a month after the allegation, ties improved slightly and the US asked Pakistan to assist it in starting negotiation talks with the [[Taliban]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/NewsDetail.aspx?ID=25732|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120913005136/http://www.thenews.com.pk/NewsDetail.aspx?ID=25732|url-status=dead|archive-date=13 September 2012|title=US seeks Pak aid in peace efffort|date=31 October 2011|work=The News International, Pakistan|accessdate=20 May 2015}}</ref> In 2014, the Pakistani Armed Forces launched a major offensive [[Operation Zarb-e-Azb]] in North Waziristan aimed at displacing all militants foreign and domestic, including the Haqqani network from its soil. The operation is currently ongoing.\n\n==Opponents==\n===ISAF Military offensives===\nIn July 2008, Jalaluddin's son Omar Haqqani was killed in a firefight with coalition forces in Paktia.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080924043949/http://www.thenews.com.pk/print3.asp?id=15932 Haqqani\u2019s son killed in Paktia], ''[[The News International]]'', 11 July 2008</ref> In September 2008, [[Daande Darpkhel airstrike]] drones fired six missiles at the home of the Haqqanis and a [[madrasah]] run by the network. However both Jalaluddin and Sirajuddin were not present though several family members were killed.<ref name=WP1>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/09/08/AR2008090800263.html U.S. Missiles Said To Kill 20 in Pakistan Near Afghan Border], [[The Washington Post]], 9 September 2008</ref> Among 23 people killed was one of Jalaluddin's two wives, sister, sister-in-law and eight of his grandchildren.<ref name=\"nytimes080909\" /> In March 2009, the US State Department announced a reward of $5 million for information leading to the location, arrest, or conviction of Sirajuddin under the [[Rewards for Justice Program]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2009/03/120864.htm|title=Rewards For Justice: Sirajuddin Haqqani|publisher=U.S. State Department|date=14 January 2008|accessdate=27 July 2011}}</ref> In May 2010, US senator and [[United States Senate Select Committee on Intelligence]] Chair [[Dianne Feinstein]] wrote to [[United States Secretary of State]] [[Hillary Clinton]] urging her to add the Haqqani network to [[U.S. State Department list of Foreign Terrorist Organizations]].<ref name=\"AFP20100513\">{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5h5i-QzMfNV5Em8FX2BRBWDhUIQOQ|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100517152313/http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5h5i-QzMfNV5Em8FX2BRBWDhUIQOQ|url-status=dead|archive-date=17 May 2010|title=US Senator: Label Pakistan Taliban, Haqqani, as terrorists|date=13 May 2010|publisher=[[Agence France-Presse]]|accessdate=25 May 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nISAF and Afghan forces killed a network leader, Fazil Subhan, plus an unknown number of Haqqani militiamen, in a raid in [[Khost]] in the second week of June 2010. In a press release, ISAF reported that Subhan helped facilitate the movement of Al-Qaeda fighters into Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite web|last=Roggio|first=Bill|title=US, Afghan Forces Kill Haqqani Network Commander During Raid In Khost|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2010/06/us_afghan_forces_kil_1.php|work=Long War Journal|date=14 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.isaf.nato.int/article/isaf-releases/afghan-international-force-clears-haqqani-stronghold.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120129064954/http://www.isaf.nato.int/article/isaf-releases/afghan-international-force-clears-haqqani-stronghold.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=29 January 2012|title=Afghan, International Force Clears Haqqani Stronghold|accessdate= 22 September 2011|date=14 June 2010|publisher=ISAF}}</ref>\n\nIn late July 2011, U.S. and [[Afghan National Army#Special Forces|Afghan special forces]] killed dozens of insurgents during an operation in eastern [[Paktika province]] to clear a training camp the Haqqani network used for foreign (Arab and Chechen) fighters; reports of the number killed varied, with one source saying \"more than 50\"<ref name=\"reuters2011\" /> to \"nearly 80\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://security.blogs.cnn.com/2011/07/26/rare-glimpse-into-u-s-special-operations-forces-in-afghanistan/|title=Rare glimpse into U.S. special operations forces in Afghanistan|publisher=CNN |work=Security Clearance (blog)|date=26 July 2011|accessdate=27 July 2011|quote=U.S. and Afghan troops attacked an insurgent encampment, killing nearly 80 foreign fighters\u2026. The camp they attacked and the fighters there were part of the so-called Haqqanni network, which is responsible for many recent attacks in Afghanistan and is closely tied to al Qaeda. The Haqqanis traditionally rely on Afghan and Pakistani fighters, but in this instance most of the fighters there who were killed were Arabs and Chechens, brought into Afghanistan from Pakistan.}}</ref> Disenfranchised insurgents told security forces where the camp was located, the coalition said.<ref name=\"reuters2011\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/07/22/us-afghanistan-violence-idUSTRE76L36220110722|title=NATO kills 50 fighters, clears Afghan training camp|publisher=Reuters|first=Michelle |last=Nichols|date=22 July 2011|accessdate=23 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 October 2011, NATO announced the capture of Haji Mali Khan, \"the senior Haqqani commander in Afghanistan,\" during an operation in Jani Khel district of Afghanistan's Paktia province. Taliban spokesman [[Zabiullah Mujahid]] denied that the capture occurred while Haqqani network members declined to respond to the announcement.<ref name='ft20111001' /><ref name='npr20111001' />\n\nAccording to an unnamed Pakistani official a US drone strike on a compound killed [[Jan Baz Zadran|Jamil Haqqani]], an \"important Afghan commander of Haqqani network\" responsible for logistics in North Waziristan, on 13 October 2011. Three other network fighters were also killed in the two missile blasts. The compound was located in Dandey Darpakhel village, about 7&nbsp;km (4 miles) north of Miranshah.<ref name='et20111013'>{{cite news|title=US drones strike in North, South Waziristan|date=13 October 2011| publisher=The Express Tribune News Network|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/273122/us-drone-strike-kills-four-in-n-waziristan-2/|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=13 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-October 2011, Afghan and NATO forces launched \"Operation Shamshir\" and \"Operation Knife Edge\" against the Haqqani network in south-eastern Afghanistan, with the intent to counter possible security threats in the border regions. An ISAF spokesman said that Operation Shamshir \"was aimed at securing key population centers and expanding the Kabul security zone,\"<ref name='aljazeera20111025'>{{cite news|first=Mujib|last=Mashal|title=Afghan forces target Haqqani strongholds|date=25 October 2011|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/asia/2011/10/2011102415575819318.html|work=Al Jazeera|accessdate=26 October 2011}}</ref> while [[Ministry of Defense (Afghanistan)|Afghan Defense Minister]], [[Abdul Rahim Wardak]], explained that Operation Knife Edge would \"help eliminate the insurgents before they struck in areas along the troubled frontier.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pajhwok.com/en/2011/10/18/push-launched-against-haqqanis-border-areas|title=Push launched against Haqqanis in border areas|work=pajhwok.com|accessdate=20 May 2015}}</ref> The two operations ended on 23 October 2011 and at least 20 insurgents, of the some 200 killed or captured, had ties to the Haqqani network according to ISAF.<ref name=Riechmann>[https://news.yahoo.com/nato-200-afghan-militants-killed-captured-074709256.html NATO: 200 Afghan militants killed, captured] by Deb Riechmann. 24 October 2011.</ref><ref name='aljazeera20111025' />\n\nOn 2 November 2011, ''The Express Tribune'' reported that the Pakistani Army had agreed with the United States to restrict the network's movement along the Afghan border in exchange for America dropping its demands for a full-scale offensive. The report emerged soon after a visit by Hillary Clinton to Pakistan.<ref name='et20111102'>{{cite news|first=Kamran |last=Yousaf|title=Pakistan looks to restrict Haqqanis\u2019 movement|date=2 November 2011|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/286354/pakistan-looks-to-restrict-haqqanis-movement/?cid=nlc-dailybrief-daily_news_brief-link19-20111102|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=3 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nCurtis M. Scaparrotti, commander of International Security Assistance Force Joint Command, has said that Haqqani can be defeated through a combination of a layered defense in Afghanistan and interdiction against the sanctuaries in Pakistan.<ref>Marshall, Tyrone C. Jr. [https://web.archive.org/web/20120205070511/http://www.defense.gov/News/NewsArticle.aspx?ID=65845 \"Objectives Achievable Despite Pakistan Sanctuaries, General Says.\"] ''American Forces Press Service'', 27 October 2011.</ref>\n\nIn June 2014 a drone attack reportedly killed 10 members of the Haqqani network including a high-level commander, Haji Gul, in the country's tribal area of North Waziristan. The Pakistan government publicly condemned the attack, but according to a government official had privately approved it.<ref name=\"HaqqaniDrone\">{{cite news|title=Controversial US drone attack in Pakistan, 16 killed|url=http://www.pakistannews.net/index.php/sid/222852683/scat/8c3d7d78943a99c7/ht/Controversial-US-drone-attack-in-Pakistan-16-killed|archive-url=https://archive.today/20140615080349/http://www.pakistannews.net/index.php/sid/222852683/scat/8c3d7d78943a99c7/ht/Controversial-US-drone-attack-in-Pakistan-16-killed|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 June 2014|accessdate=12 June 2014|publisher=Pakistan News.Net}}</ref>\n\n===Pakistani military offensive===\nIn 2014, the Pakistani Armed Forces launched a major offensive [[Operation Zarb-e-Azb]] in North Waziristan aimed at displacing all militants foreign and domestic, including the Haqqani network from its soil. On 5 November 2014, Lt. Gen. Joseph Anderson, a senior commander for US and Nato forces in Afghanistan, said in a Pentagon-hosted video briefing from Afghanistan that the Haqqani network is now \"fractured\" like the Taliban. \"They are fractured. They are fractured like the Taliban is. That's based pretty much on the Pakistan's operations in North Waziristan this entire summer-fall,\" he said, acknowledging the effectiveness of Pakistan's military offensive. \"That has very much disrupted their efforts in Afghanistan and has caused them to be less effective in terms of their ability to pull off an attack in Kabul,\" Anderson added. The operation is currently ongoing.<ref name=OperationZarb>{{cite news|title=Operation Zarb-i-Azb disrupted Haqqani network: US general|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1142664/|date=6 November 2014|work=Dawn|accessdate=7 November 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106124030/http://www.dawn.com/news/1142664|archivedate=6 November 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Sanctions===\nUntil 1 November 2011, six Haqqani network commanders were designated as terrorists under [[Executive Order 13224]] since 2008 and their assets were frozen while prohibiting others from engaging in financial transactions with them:<ref name=lwj20111101>{{cite web|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2011/11/us_adds_senior_haqqa.php|title=US adds senior Haqqani Network leader to terrorist list|work=The Long War Journal|accessdate=20 May 2015}}</ref>\n* In March 2008, the US State Department designated Sirajuddin Haqqani a terrorist and a year later issued a $5 million bounty for information leading to his capture.<ref name=lwj20111101 />\n* The State Department placed Nasiruddin Haqqani on its list of terrorists in July 2010.<ref name=lwj20111101 />\n* In February 2011, Khalil al Rahman Haqqani was designated a terrorist by the US State Department.<ref name=lwj20111101 />\n* In an effort to stop the flow of funds to the network, the US State Department announced on 16 August 2011 measures against [[Sangeen Zadran]] as \"Shadow Governor for [[Paktika Province]], [[Afghanistan]] and a commander of the Haqqani Network.\" The US designated Zadran under Executive Order 13224 while the United Nations listed him under [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1988|Security Council Resolution 1988]].<ref name='afp20110816'>{{cite news|title=US tries to stem funds to Haqqani network commander|date=16 August 2011|publisher=AFP|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/232918/us-tries-to-stem-funds-to-haqqani-network-commander/|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=17 August 2011}}</ref><ref name='state20110816'>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2011/08/170582.htm|title=Designation of Haqqani Network Commander Sangeen Zadran|accessdate=17 August 2011|date=16 August 2011|publisher=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n* The U.S. Department of Treasury added Abdul Aziz Abbasin, \"a key commander in the Haqqani Network\", to the list of individuals on the executive order in September 2011.<ref name='treasury20110929' /><ref name=lwj20111101 />\n* On 1 November 2011, Haji Mali Khan, who was already in ISAF custody, was added to the list.<ref name=lwj20111101 />\n\nIn September 2011, the US [[Senate Appropriations Committee]] voted to make a $1 billion counter-insurgency aid package to the Pakistani military conditional upon Pakistani action against militant groups, including the Haqqani network. The decision would still need to receive approval from the [[US House of Representatives]] and the [[US Senate]].<ref name='bbc20110922'>{{cite news|title=US senators link Pakistan aid to Haqqani crackdown|date=22 September 2011|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-15014800|work=BBC|accessdate=22 September 2011}}</ref> According to the press release, \"[t]he bill includes strengthened restrictions on assistance for Pakistan by conditioning all funds to the Government of Pakistan on cooperation against the Haqqani network, al Qaeda, and other terrorist organizations, with a waiver, and funding based on achieving benchmarks.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://appropriations.senate.gov/news.cfm?method=news.view&id=3105a024-f546-4e7a-9931-7b95ad620dba|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926051438/http://appropriations.senate.gov/news.cfm?method=news.view&id=3105a024-f546-4e7a-9931-7b95ad620dba|url-status=dead|archive-date=26 September 2011|title=Summary: FY12 State, Foreign Operations Appropriations Bill|accessdate=22 September 2011|date=21 September 2011|publisher=U.S. Senate Committee on Appropriations|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 September 2012, the Obama administration blacklisted the group as a [[foreign terrorist organization]]. The decision was mandated by Congress and was a source of debate within the administration.<ref name=nytimes20120907>{{cite news|last=Schmitt|first=Eric|title=U.S. Backs Blacklisting Militant Organization|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/07/world/asia/white-house-backs-blacklisting-militant-organization.html?_r=1&emc=na|work=The New York Times|accessdate=7 September 2012|date=6 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"aljazeera20120907\">{{cite news| url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia/2012/09/201297134941881703.html|title=US designates Haqqani group as 'terrorists'|agency=Al Jazeera|date=7 September 2012|accessdate=7 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"wapo20120907\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/haqqani-network-to-be-designated-a-terrorist-group/2012/09/07/e6576ac0-f8f6-11e1-a073-78d05495927c_story.html|title=Haqqani network to be designated a terrorist group|work=The Washington Post|date=7 September 2012|accessdate=7 September 2012|author=DeYoung, Karen}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 November 2012, the United Nations Security Council added the network to a [[blacklist]] of Taliban-related groups.<ref name=\"bbc20121105\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-20214211 |title=UN adds Haqqani network to Taliban sanctions list |publisher=BBC News |date=5 November 2012 |accessdate=6 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 May 2013 the government of Canada listed it as a terror group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.publicsafety.gc.ca/cnt/ntnl-scrt/cntr-trrrsm/lstd-ntts/crrnt-lstd-ntts-eng.aspx#2011|title=About the listing process|accessdate=20 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015 the UK proscribed the Haqqani network as a terror group.<ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/509003/20160318proscription.pdf PROSCRIBED TERRORIST ORGANISATIONS] UK Home Office.</ref>\n\n===Attempts to negotiate===\nUS officials confirmed that they held preliminary talks during the summer of 2011 with representatives of the militant network at the request of the ISI. Secretary of State Hillary Clinton said that the US had reached out to the Haqqanis to gauge their willingness to engage in a peace process and that \"Pakistani government officials helped to facilitate such a meeting.\"<ref name='bbc20111021'>{{cite news|title=Hillary Clinton: US held meeting with Haqqani network|date=21 October 2011|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-15399820|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=22 October 2011}}</ref> ''The New York Times'' reported that talks secretly began in late August 2011 in the [[United Arab Emirates]] between a midlevel American diplomat and Ibrahim Haqqani, Jalalludin's brother. Gen. [[Ahmed Shuja Pasha]], head of the ISI, brokered the discussion, but little resulted from the meeting.<ref name='nytimes20111030'>{{cite news|first=Eric|last=Schmitt|author2=David E. Sanger|title=U.S. Seeks Aid From Pakistan in Peace Effort|date=30 October 2011 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/31/world/asia/united-states-seeks-pakistan-spy-agencys-help-for-afghan-talks.html|work=The New York Times|accessdate=31 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Drone strikes in Pakistan]]\n* [[Hafiz Gul Bahadur]]\n* [[International Security Assistance Force]]\n* [[War in North-West Pakistan]]\n* [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n* [[Bowe Bergdahl]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite book| last=Vahid Brown |first=Don Rassler|title=Fountainhead of Jihad: The Haqqani Nexus, 1973\u20132012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |date=1 February 2013 |edition=1|page=320|isbn=978-0-19-932798-0}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/para/haqqani.htm Haqqani Network], GlobalSecurity.org\n* [http://www.understandingwar.org/themenode/haqqani-network Haqqani Network], [[Institute for the Study of War]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090330072513/http://www.rewardsforjustice.net/index.cfm?page=haqqani Sirajuddin Haqqani], [[Rewards for Justice Program]]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-14912957 Haqqanis: Growth of a militant network], ''[[BBC News]]'', 14 September 2011\n* [https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE60622S20100107 Q&A: Who are the Haqqanis?], ''[[Reuters]]''\n* {{NYTtopic|organizations/h/haqqani_network}}\n* [http://www.ctc.usma.edu/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/CTC_Haqqani_Network_Financing-Report__Final.pdf Haqqani Network Financing: The Evolution of an Industry] \u2013 The Combating Terrorism Center at West Point, July 2012\n* [http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/NSAEBB/NSAEBB389/ The Haqqani History: Bin Ladin's Advocate inside the Taliban] \u2013 National Security Archive Electronic Briefing Book, 11 September 2012\n\n{{Taliban}}\n{{Militant Islamism in South Asia}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n\n[[Category:Afghanistan\u2013Pakistan relations]]\n[[Category:Anti-Soviet factions in the Soviet\u2013Afghan War]]\n[[Category:Organizations designated as terrorist in Asia]]\n[[Category:Jihadist groups in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Jihadist groups in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Pakistan\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:Modern history of Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Organizations designated as terrorist by the United States]]\n[[Category:Taliban]]\n[[Category:War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:Waziristan]]\n[[Category:Organisations designated as terrorist by the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Organizations designated as terrorist by Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Afghan guerrilla insurgent group}}\n{{Infobox war faction\n|name = Haqqani network\n|war = the [[War in Afghanistan (1978\u2013present)]], and the [[War on Terror|Global War on Terrorism]]\n|image = \n|caption =\n|active = 1980s<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.quilliaminternational.com/who-are-the-haqqanis-3/|title=Who are the Haqqanis? |publisher=Quilliam|accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref>\u2013present\n|ideology = Islamic fundamentalism\n|leaders = [[Jalaluddin Haqqani]] (deceased)<br />[[Sirajuddin Haqqani]]\n|groups =\n|headquarters =\n|area = [[Afghanistan]]\n|strength = 4,000\u201315,000<ref name='rassler' /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/259314/sirajuddin-haqqani-dares-us-to-attack-n-waziristan/|title=Sirajuddin Haqqani dares US to attack N Waziristan|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=20 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes 15haqqani\" />\n|partof = {{flagicon image|Flag of Taliban.svg}} [[Taliban]]<ref>https://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2018/09/taliban-announced-death-of-jalaluddin-haqqani.php</ref><ref>http://www.understandingwar.org/report/haqqani-network</ref><ref name='rassler' /><ref name=Riechmann /><ref name=\"CSM1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Asia-South-Central/2009/0601/p10s01-wosc.html|title=The most deadly US foe in Afghanistan|work=The Christian Science Monitor|date=1 June 2009|accessdate=17 August 2012|author=Gopal, Anand}}</ref><ref>Syed Salaam Shahzaddate=5 May 2004. \"Through the eyes of the Taliban\". ''Asia Times''. Retrieved 10 February 2009.</ref>\n|previous =\n|next =\n|allies= {{flagicon image|Flag of al-Qaeda.svg}} [[al-Qaeda]]\n|opponents=  {{nowrap|{{flagicon|Afghanistan}} [[Islamic Republic of Afghanistan]]}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-25922743 |title=Rare look at Afghan National Army's Taliban fight |publisher=BBC News |date=28 January 2014 |accessdate=2014-08-18}}</ref><br>\n{{Flag|USA}}\n\n{{flagicon|NATO}} [[North Atlantic Treaty Organization|NATO]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia/2012/12/20121224051624851.html |title=Taliban attack NATO base in Afghanistan |publisher=Al Jazeera English |date=2 December 2012 |accessdate=2014-08-18}}</ref><br>\n*{{flagicon image|Resolute Support.svg}} [[Resolute Support Mission]]\n\n{{flagicon|Pakistan}} [[Pakistan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/786641/us-commander-commends-zarb-e-azb-for-disrupting-haqqani-networks-ability-to-target-afghanistan/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106165357/http://tribune.com.pk/story/786641/us-commander-commends-zarb-e-azb-for-disrupting-haqqani-networks-ability-to-target-afghanistan/|url-status=dead|archive-date=6 November 2014|title=US commander commends Zarb-e-Azb for disrupting Haqqani network's ability to target Afghanistan|date=6 November 2014|work=Express Tribune}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/international/world-news/pakistan-military-operation-disrupted-haqqani-network-us-commander/articleshow/45054621.cms|title=Pakistan military operation disrupted Haqqani network: US commander|date=6 November 2014|work=Economic Times}}</ref>\nFormerly:<br/>{{flag|Soviet Union}} (1979\u20131989)\n|battles = [[Soviet\u2013Afghan War]] <br /> [[Afghan Civil War (1989\u20131992)]] <br /> [[Afghan Civil War (1992\u20131996)]] <br /> [[Afghan Civil War (1996\u20132001)]] <br /> [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]] <br /> [[Taliban insurgency]] <br /> [[Operation Zarb-e-Azb]]\n|active2=}}\n\nThe '''Haqqani network''' is an Afghan guerrilla [[Taliban insurgency|insurgent group]] using [[asymmetric warfare]] to fight against [[United States armed forces|US]]-led [[International Security Assistance Force|NATO forces]] and the [[government of Afghanistan]]. [[Mawlawi (Islamic title)|Maulvi]] [[Jalaluddin Haqqani]] and his son [[Sirajuddin Haqqani]] have led the group.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/01/world/asia/founder-of-haqqani-network-died-nearly-a-year-ago-member-says.html |title=Founder of Haqqani Network Is Long Dead Aide Says|work=The New York Times|accessdate=7 January 2016}}</ref> It is an offshoot of the [[Taliban]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/ruthless-taliban-branch-is-center-stage-in-us-pakistan-tensions/2017/07/18/dc03b2b4-5a89-11e7-aa69-3964a7d55207_story.html |title=A much-feared Taliban offshoot returns from the dead|first1=Haq Nawaz|last1=Khan|first2=Pamela|last2=Constable|date=19 July 2017|accessdate=1 February 2018|work=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/afghan-general-haqqani-network-islamic-state/4206961.html|title=Afghan General: Haqqani Network, Not IS, Behind Spike in Violence|first=Hasib Danish|last=Alikozai|publisher=VoA News|accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/what-haqqani-network/3883271.html|title=What Is the Haqqani Network?|last=|first=|date=|publisher=VOA News|language=en|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe Haqqani network pledged allegiance to the Taliban in 1995,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/what-haqqani-network/3883271.html|title=What Is the Haqqani Network?|last=|first=|date=|publisher=VOA|language=en|access-date=}}</ref> and have been an increasingly incorporated wing of the group ever since.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/04/world/asia/jalaluddin-haqqani-dead-taliban.html |title=Taliban Say Haqqani Founder Is Dead. His Group Is More Vital Than Ever.|last=Mashal|first=Mujib|date=2018-09-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In the past, the Taliban and Haqqani leaders have denied the existence of the \"network\", calling it no different from the Taliban.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/what-haqqani-network/3883271.html |title=What Is the Haqqani Network?|last=|first=|date=|publisher=VOA News |language=en|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1980s, the Haqqani network was one of the most favored CIA-funded anti-Soviet guerrilla groups by the [[Reagan administration]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Abubakar Siddique |date= 26 Sep 2011 |agency=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty  |url=https://www.ethz.ch/content/specialinterest/gess/cis/center-for-securities-studies/en/services/digital-library/articles/article.html/133041 |title=Questions Raised About Haqqani Network Ties with Pakistan |publisher=[[ETH Zurich]] Center for Security Studies |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref name='rassler'>{{cite journal|title=The Haqqani Nexus and the Evolution of al-Qaida|journal=Harmony Program|date=14 July 2011|first=Don|last=Rassler|author2=Vahid Brown|publisher=[[Combating Terrorism Center]]|url=http://www.ctc.usma.edu/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/CTC-Haqqani-Report_Rassler-Brown-Final_Web.pdf|format=PDF|accessdate=2 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725024028/http://www.ctc.usma.edu/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/CTC-Haqqani-Report_Rassler-Brown-Final_Web.pdf|archive-date=25 July 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2012, the United States designated the Haqqani network a terrorist organization.<ref>{{cite news|title=Haqqani network to be designated a terrorist group|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/haqqani-network-to-be-designated-a-terrorist-group-obama-officials-say/2012/09/07/e6576ac0-f8f6-11e1-a073-78d05495927c_story.html}}</ref> In 2015, Pakistan also banned the Haqqani network as part of its [[National Action Plan (Pakistan)|National Action Plan]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Pakistan bans Haqqani network after security talks with Kerry|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pakistan-militants-haqqani/pakistan-bans-haqqani-network-after-security-talks-with-kerry-idUSKBN0KP1DA20150116}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe word \"Haqqani\" comes from [[Darul Uloom Haqqania]], a [[Madrassa]] in Pakistan attended by [[Jalaluddin Haqqani]].<ref name=\"ft20111113\">{{cite news |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/8e0c7b26-0dbf-11e1-91e5-00144feabdc0.html#axzz2BfbmEmS0 |title=\u2018Father of Taliban\u2019 urges US concessions |work=Financial Times |date=13 November 2011 |accessdate=9 November 2012 |author=Green, Matthew |quote=The school also has a place in the hearts of the commanders of the Haqqani network, a family-run insurgent dynasty that specialises in Kabul suicide bombings. Jalaluddin Haqqani, the group\u2019s patriarch, studied at the seminary, from which he derives his name.}}</ref>\n\n==Ideology and goals==\nThe Haqqani network's root values are nationalistic and religious. They are ideologically aligned with the [[Taliban]], who have worked to eradicate Western influence and transform Afghanistan into a strictly sharia-following state. This was exemplified in the government that formed after Soviet troops were driven from Afghanistan.  Both groups have the common goal of disrupting the Western military and political efforts in Afghanistan and driving them from the country permanently.<ref name=\"Jeffrey Dressler 2010\">\"Jeffrey Dressler; The Haqqani Network, A Strategic Threat.\" Institute for the Study of War 2010.</ref> Currently the group demands that US and Coalition Forces, made up mostly of NATO Nations, withdraw from Afghanistan and no longer interfere with the politics or educational systems of Islamic nations.<ref name=\"Jeffrey Dressler 2010\" />\n\n==History==\nJalaluddin Haqqani joined the [[Hezb-i Islami Khalis]] in 1978 and becoming a [[mujahid]] in [[Afghanistan]]. His personal Haqqani group was nurtured by the U.S. [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA) and [[Pakistan]]'s [[Inter-Services Intelligence]] (ISI) during the 1980s [[Soviet\u2013Afghan War]].<ref name=\"ISN\">{{cite news|url=http://www.isn.ethz.ch/isn/Current-Affairs/ISN-Insights/Detail?lng=en&id=133042&contextid734=133042&contextid735=133041&tabid=133041&dynrel=40db1b50-7439-887d-706e-8ec00590bdb9,4888caa0-b3db-1461-98b9-e20e7b9c13d4,0c54e3b3-1e9c-be1e-2c24-a6a8c7060233|title=Questions Raised About Haqqani Network Ties with Pakistan|work=International Relations and Security Network|date=26 September 2011|accessdate=15 October 2011}}</ref><ref>Coll, Steve ''Ghost Wars'' (New York:Penguin, 2004) pp. 201-202</ref>\n\n===Haqqani family===\nThe Haqqani family hails from southeastern [[Afghanistan]] and belongs to the Mezi Clan of the [[Zadran (Pashtun tribe)|Zadran]] [[Pashtun tribes|Pashtun tribe]].<ref name=\"ISN\" /><ref name=fp20100603 /><ref name='at20111015' /> Jalalludin Haqqani rose to prominence as a senior military leader during the Soviet occupation of Afghanistan.<ref name='at20111015' /> Like [[Gulbuddin Hekmatyar]], Haqqani was more successful than other resistance leaders at forging relationships with outsiders prepared to sponsor resistance to the Soviets, including the CIA, [[Pakistan]]'s [[Inter-Services Intelligence]] (ISI), and wealthy Arab private donors from the [[Persian Gulf]].\n\n===Al-Qaeda affiliation===\nJalaluddin Haqqani commanded the Mujahideen Army from 1980\u20131992 and is credited with the recruitment of foreign fighters. Notable jihadists are two well-known Arabs, Abdullah Azzam and Osama bin Laden, who both began their careers as volunteers for the Haqqanis and trained to fight the Soviets. [[Al-Qa'ida]] and the Haqqani network, in other words evolved together, and they have remained intertwined throughout their history and remain so to this day.<ref name=\"Brown, V. 2012\">Brown, V.; Rassler, D.; ''Fountainhead of Jihad: The Haqqani Network, 1973\u20132012''. Columbia University Press 2013.</ref> The Haqqani network's relationship with [[Al-Qaeda]] dates back to the founding of AQ. The significant difference between the two organizations is that Al-Qaeda pursues global goals using global means; whereas Haqqani is solely interested in Afghanistan and the Pashtun Tribal regions. Jalaluddin Haqqani is more interested in the influence of Islamic Law over Afghanistan than the global Jihad but his network has always been fully aware of Al-Qaeda's intentions and goals.\n\nThese two groups are intertwined in tactics, strategy, and Islamic extremism; J. Haqqani realized the importance of Azzam\u2019s \"foundational Islamic legal decisions declaring the Afghan jihad a universally and individually binding duty borne by all Muslims worldwide.\"  Though many Muslim leaders asked for aid from oil wealthy Arab nations in 1978 when Afghan Communists with the backing of the Soviet Union conquered Kabul. J. Haqqani was the only Afghan Islamic Resistance leader to also request foreign Muslim fighters, and was the only group to welcome non-Afghans into its ranks. Thus \"linking it to the broader Jihad struggles and giving birth to the following decade to what would come to be known as global jihadism.\"<ref name=\"Brown, V. 2012\" /><ref name=\"Fountainhead of Jihad\">''Fountainhead of Jihad''</ref> It is the Haqqani network's use of the Saudi Arabian financiers and other Arab investors in his mission that clearly highlights the groups understanding of Global Jihad. A major difference between the Haqqani network and Al-Qaeda is the spheres of influence they both seek to control.<ref name=\"Brown, V. 2012\" /><ref name=\"Fountainhead of Jihad\" /> Al-Qaeda's is global, Haqqani's is regional.\n\n[[File:Insurgent Regions in Afghanistan and Pakistan.jpg|thumb|left|upright=2.0|Insurgent regions in Afghanistan and border regions of Pakistan, as of 2010]]\n\nMany sources believe Jalaluddin Haqqani and his forces assisted with the escape of Al-Qaeda into safe-havens in Pakistan. Considering how closely the two groups are inter-twined it is not a stretch. It is well documented that the Haqqani network did assist with the establishment of safe-havens. Analyst [[Peter Bergen]] argues this point in his book \"The Battle for Tora Bora\"<ref>\"The Battle for Tora Bora\"</ref><ref>Bergen, Peter; \"The Battle for Tora Bora.\" ''The New Republic'', 30 Dec 2009.</ref><ref>\"Al-Qaeda's Great Escape\"</ref><ref>\"Smucker, Philip; Al-Qaeda's Great Escape: The military and media on Terror's\" Dulles, Virginia, Bassey's 2004.</ref> Judging by the possibilities and the amount of US Military assets focused on such a small region, the theory that the Haqqani network aided in the escape seems reasonable. Regardless of exactly what occurred in those mountains, the Haqqanis played a role. And their actions of providing safe-havens for [[Al-Qaeda]] and [[Osama Bin Laden]] show the strength of bond and some role in or knowledge of Al-Qaeda and Bin Laden's escape.\n\n===Taliban affiliation===\nForeign jihadists recognized the network as a distinct entity as early as 1994, but Haqqani was not affiliated with the [[Taliban]] until they captured [[Kabul]] and assumed de facto control of [[Afghanistan]] in 1996.<ref name='rassler' /><ref name=\"hinduonnet 19030560\">{{cite news|title=The failing campaign: A relentless American campaign seeking to kill Maulvi [[Jalaluddin Haqqani]] rains bombs on civilians as the most powerful mujahideen remains elusive|work=[[The Hindu]]|first=Marc|last=Herold|date=February 2002|issue=3|volume=19 }}{{dead link|date=October 2011}}</ref> After the Taliban came to power, Haqqani accepted a cabinet-level appointment as Minister of Tribal Affairs.<ref name=\"AsiaTimes040505\">{{cite news|url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/Central_Asia/FE05Ag02.html|title=Through the eyes of the Taliban|newspaper=[[Asia Times]]|author=Syed Salaam Shahzaddate=5 May 2004|accessdate=10 February 2009}}</ref> Following the U.S.-led invasion of Afghanistan in 2001 and the subsequent overthrow of the Taliban government, the Haqqanis fled to the bordering Pakistani tribal regions and regrouped to fight against coalition forces across the border.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia-pacific/us-drone-strike-kills-haqqani-insider/2011/10/13/gIQA5rT3gL_story.html|title=U.S. steps up drone strikes in Pakistan against Haqqani network|work=The Washington Post|date=13 October 2011|accessdate=15 October 2011|first=Karen|last=DeYoung}}</ref> As Jalaluddin has grown older his son Sirajuddin has taken over the responsibility of military operations.<ref name=\"NYTimes2008-06-17\" /> Journalist [[Syed Saleem Shahzad]] reported that President [[Hamid Karzai]] invited c. 2002 the elder Haqqani to serve as [[Prime Minister of Afghanistan|Prime Minister]] in an attempt to bring \"moderate\" Taliban into the government. However, the offer was refused by Jalaluddin.<ref name=\"AsiaTimes040505\" />\n\n===United States===\nAccording to US military commanders, it is \"the most resilient enemy network\" and one of the biggest threats to the U.S.-led NATO forces and the Afghan government in the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|current war in Afghanistan]].<ref name=\"NYTimes2008-06-17\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/17/world/asia/17iht-17warlord.13756827.html |title=Old-Line Taliban Commander is Face of Rising Afghan Threa|work=The New York Times|first=Carlotta|last=Gall|authorlink=Carlotta Gall|date=17 June 2008|accessdate=10 February 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Partlow|first=Joshua|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia-pacific/haqqani-insurgent-group-proves-resilient-foe-in-afghan-war/2011/05/27/AG0wfKEH_story.html|title=Haqqani insurgent group proves resilient foe in Afghan war |work=The Washington Post|date=27 May 2011|accessdate=27 July 2011}}</ref> It is also the most lethal network in Afghanistan.<ref name=dressler>{{cite web|last=Dressler|first=Jeffrey|title=The Haqqani Network: A Foreign Terrorist Organization |url=http://www.understandingwar.org/sites/default/files/Backgrounder_Haqqani-FTO.pdf|publisher=ISW|accessdate=15 September 2012|date=5 September 2012}}</ref> Presently, the [[United States]] is offering a reward for information leading to the capture of their leader, [[Sirajuddin Haqqani]], in the amount of [[United States dollar|$]]5,000,000.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wanted Sirajuddin Haqqani Up to $5 Million Reward|publisher=Rewards for Justice|url=http://www.rewardsforjustice.net/index.cfm?page=haqqani |accessdate=9 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090822063810/http://www.rewardsforjustice.net/index.cfm?page=haqqani |archivedate=22 August 2009}}</ref>\n\n====Obama administration====\nIn September 2012, the Obama administration labeled the network as a [[foreign terrorist organization]].<ref name=nytimes20120907 /> After this announcement, Taliban issued a statement arguing that there is \"no separate entity or network in [[Afghanistan]] by the name of Haqqani\" and that [[Jalaluddin Haqqani]] is a member of [[Quetta Shura|the Quetta Shura]], Taliban's top leadership council.<ref name=lwjroggi>{{cite news|last=Roggio|first=Bill|title=Taliban call Haqqani Network a 'conjured entity'|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2012/09/taliban_call_haqqani.php|accessdate=10 September 2012|newspaper=Long War Journal|date=9 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Leadership===\n* [[Jalaluddin Haqqani]] \u2013 following his time as a commander in the Mujahideen Army (1980\u20131992), the network was founded under Haqqani during the insurgency against Soviet forces in Afghanistan during the 1980s. Haqqani himself was trained in Pakistan during the 1970s, in order to fight Prime Minister Mohammad Daud Khan, who had overthrown the previous ruler (and cousin), King Zahir Shah. During the Soviet invasion, the Pakistani government's Inter-Services Intelligence Agency became close with Haqqani and his organization, allowing them to become a main benefactor of American weapons, intelligence, and training. In the 1990s, Haqqani agreed to join the Taliban, arising to the position of Interior Minister. The United States attempted to convince Haqqani to sever ties with the Taliban, which he refused to do. In 2005 when Merjuddin Pathan was governor of the Khost Province, Haqqani approached him and wanting a dialogue with the Hamid Karzai Government, but neither Americans nor Karzai heeded the pleas of the governor. Afterwards when insurgency accentuated that  Hamid Karzai's leadership  in Afghanistan, approached Haqqani and offered him the position as Minister of Tribal Affairs in his cabinet, which Haqqani has also refused as it was too late. Since the emergence of the Haqqani Network, Haqqani and his family have thrived off of the contacts made by Haqqani during the Cold War.<ref>name=Lawrence, Kendall. \"The Haqqani Network.\" Threat Convergence Profile Series. The Fund For Peace. October 2011. Last accessed 10 July 2012.</ref> The BBC reported in July 2015 that Jalaluddin Haqqani had died of an illness and been buried in Afghanistan at least a year prior.<ref>{{cite news|title=Afghan militant leader Jalaluddin Haqqani 'has died'|date=31 July 2015|publisher=BBC |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-33740337|accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref> The Taliban rejected these reports.<ref>{{cite news|title=Taliban deny reports of Haqqani network founder's death|url=https://news.yahoo.com/taliban-deny-reports-haqqani-network-founders-death-072622210.html|accessdate=1 August 2015|publisher=AFP|date=1 August 2015}}</ref> On 3 September 2018, the Taliban released a statement via [[Twitter]] proclaiming Haqqani's death of an unspecified terminal illness.<ref>[https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/haqqani-network-s-founder-dies-after-long-illness-afghan-taliban-n906116 \"Haqqani network's founder dies after long illness, Afghan Taliban says\", by Alexander Smith and Mushtaq Yusufzai, NBC News]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/Zabihullah_4/status/1036806652874444800 |title=Archived copy |access-date=4 September 2018 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20180904025542/https://twitter.com/Zabihullah_4/status/1036806652874444800 |archive-date=4 September 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Sirajuddin Haqqani]] \u2013 He is one of Jalaluddin's sons and currently leads the day-to-day activities of the network. \n* Badruddin Haqqani \u2013 He was Sirajuddin's brother and an operational commander of the network. He was killed in a U.S. drone strike in Pakistan on 24 August 2012. Some Taliban commanders claimed the reports of his death were true while others claimed the reports were inaccurate.<ref name='et20110922'>{{cite news|first=Zia|last=Khan|title=Who on earth are the Haqqanis?|date=22 September 2011|newspaper=The Express Tribune News Network|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/257761/who-on-earth-are-the-haqqanis/|accessdate=23 September 2011}}</ref><ref name='et20120825'>{{cite news|title=Top Haqqani network militant 'killed in Pakistan'|date=25 August 2012|publisher=BBC|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-19378474|accessdate=25 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=state>{{cite news|title=Taliban deny report of Haqqani commander's death|url=http://www.thestate.com/2012/08/26/2413107/taliban-deny-report-of-haqqani.html#.UDnKIsFgKWY|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120827194434/http://www.thestate.com/2012/08/26/2413107/taliban-deny-report-of-haqqani.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=27 August 2012|accessdate=26 August 2012|newspaper=The State|date=26 August 2012|author=Rahim Faiez|author2=Rebecca Santana|agency=AP}}</ref><ref name=\"ap20120826\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/taliban-spokesman-denies-report-that-key-militant-commander-was-killed-in-drone-strike/2012/08/26/3cd5d248-ef46-11e1-b624-99dee49d8d67_story.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120826211555/http://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/taliban-spokesman-denies-report-that-key-militant-commander-was-killed-in-drone-strike/2012/08/26/3cd5d248-ef46-11e1-b624-99dee49d8d67_story.html|archive-date=26 August 2012|title=Afghanistan says sources confirm militant commander Badruddin Haqqani has been killed|work=The Washington Post|date=26 August 2012|agency=AP|accessdate=28 August 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> However, U.S. and Pakistani officials confirmed his death.<ref>{{cite news|author=Karen DeYoung |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-confirms-killing-of-haqqani-leader-in-pakistan/2012/08/29/e5973424-f20e-11e1-a612-3cfc842a6d89_story.html |title=U.S. confirms killing of Haqqani leader in Pakistan |work=The Washington Post |date=29 August 2012 |accessdate=11 October 2012}}</ref><ref name=time>{{cite news|title=Pakistani Officials Confirm Death of Key Militant |url=http://world.time.com/2012/08/30/pakistani-officials-confirm-death-of-key-militant/ |accessdate=31 August 2012 |newspaper=Time Magazine |date=30 August 2012 |agency=AP |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120903033736/http://world.time.com/2012/08/30/pakistani-officials-confirm-death-of-key-militant/ |archivedate=3 September 2012 }}</ref> The Taliban officially confirmed Badruddin's death a year later.<ref>{{cite web|author=Bill RoggioSeptember 8, 2013 |url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2013/09/taliban_confirm_deat_1.php |title=Taliban confirm death of Badruddin Haqqani in drone strike last year |work=The Long War Journal |date=2013-09-08 |accessdate=2014-08-18}}</ref>\n* Sangeen Zadran (killed 6 September 2013)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/09/06/us-pakistan-drone-idUSBRE98503S20130906|title=Taliban-linked militant killed in U.S. drone strike in Pakistan|date=6 September 2013|agency=Reuters|accessdate=6 September 2013}}</ref> \u2013 According to the US State Department, he was a senior lieutenant to Sirajuddin and the shadow governor for [[Paktika province]] in [[Afghanistan]]. He was also one of the captors of U.S. soldier [[Bowe Bergdahl]].<ref name='et20110922' /><ref>\"Designation of Haqqani Network Commander Sangeen Zadran.\" Office of the Spokesperson. 16 August 2011. http://www.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2011/08/170582.htm. Accessed 17 July 2012.</ref><ref name='afp20110816' /><ref name='state20110816' /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-201_162-57590189/afghan-taliban-offers-to-swap-captive-u.s-soldier-bowe-bergdahl-for-5-guantanamo-detainees/ |title=Afghan Taliban offers to swap captive U.S. soldier Bowe Bergdahl for 5 Guantanamo detainees|publisher=CBS News}}</ref>\n* Nasiruddin Haqqani \u2013 He was Sirajuddin's brother and a key financier and emissary of the network. As the son of Jalaluddin's Arab wife, he spoke fluent Arabic and traveled to Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates for fundraising.<ref name='et20110922' /><ref name='lwj20100722'>{{cite news|first=Bill|last=Roggio|authorlink=Bill Roggio|title=US adds Haqqani Network, Taliban leaders to list of designated terrorists|date=22 July 2010|publisher=Public Multimedia Inc.|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2010/07/us_adds_haqqani_netw.php|work=The Long War Journal|accessdate=1 November 2011}}</ref> He was killed by unknown assailants in Islamabad, Pakistan, on 11 November 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last=Khan |first=Tahir |url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/630360/senior-haqqani-network-leader-killed-near-islamabad/ |title=Senior Haqqani Network leader killed near Islamabad |work=The Express Tribune |date= |accessdate=2014-08-18}}</ref>\n* [[Ahmad Jan (Taliban governor)|Maulvi Ahmad Jan]] (killed 21 November 2013)<ref name=yahooafp>{{cite news|url=https://news.yahoo.com/first-us-drone-strike-pakistans-khyber-pakhtunkhwa-kills-041441452.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131124032159/http://news.yahoo.com/first-us-drone-strike-pakistans-khyber-pakhtunkhwa-kills-041441452.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=24 November 2013|title=US drone strike kills senior Haqqani leader in Pakistan|author=S.B. Shah|publisher=[[Agence France-Presse]]|date=21 November 2013|accessdate=5 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The network's spiritual leader who was also responsible for organizing some of the network's most deadly attacks in Afghanistan.<ref name=\"yahooafp\" />  He was subjected to UN sanctions<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/News/Press/docs/2012/sc10805.doc.htm|title=Security Council 1988 Sanctions Committee Adds Individual Abdul Rauf Zakir,|publisher=United Nations|accessdate=20 May 2015}}</ref> in March 2010<ref name=uooafb>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/Todays-News-2-216246-Who-was-Maulvi-Ahmad-Jan-the-droned-Haqqani-leader|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131125140056/http://www.thenews.com.pk/Todays-News-2-216246-Who-was-Maulvi-Ahmad-Jan-the-droned-Haqqani-leader|url-status=dead|archive-date=25 November 2013|title=Who was Maulvi Ahmad Jan, the droned Haqqani leader?|author=Amir Mir|publisher=The News International|date=25 November 2013|accessdate=5 December 2013}}</ref> and had also served the Taliban government of Mullah Omar as federal minister for water and power,<ref name=uooafb /> before being appointed the Governor of the Zabul Province in 2000.<ref name=uooafb /> At the time of his death, Jan was thought be Sirajuddin Haqqani's chief deputy.<ref name=uooafb />\n* Abdul Aziz Abbasin \u2013 According to the U.S. Treasury, he is \"a key commander in the Haqqani Network\" and serves as the \"Taliban shadow governor of [[Orgun District]], [[Paktika Province]], Afghanistan.\"<ref name='treasury20110929'>{{cite web|url=http://www.treasury.gov/press-center/press-releases/Pages/tg1316.aspx|title=Treasury Continues Efforts Targeting Terrorist Organizations Operating in Afghanistan and Pakistan|accessdate=29 September 2011|date=29 September 2011|publisher=U.S. Department of Treasury}}</ref>\n* Haji Mali Khan \u2013 According to NATO, he is \"the senior Haqqani commander in Afghanistan\" and is uncle to Sirajuddin and Badaruddin.<ref name='ft20111001'>{{cite news|title=Haqqani leader captured in Afghanistan|date=1 October 2011|url= http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/0/7da32c2a-ec2d-11e0-8c66-00144feab49a.html#axzz1bQDJGyc2|work=Financial Times|accessdate=21 October 2011}}</ref><ref name='npr20111001'>{{cite news| title=NATO: Haqqani Leader Captured in Afghanistan|date=1 October 2011|url=https://www.npr.org/2011/10/01/140973497/nato-senior-haqqani-leader-captured-in-afghanistan| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002043542/http://www.npr.org/2011/10/01/140973497/nato-senior-haqqani-leader-captured-in-afghanistan| url-status=dead|archive-date=2 October 2011| work=NPR| accessdate=21 October 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=30 June 2011|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-13971385|title=Nato 'kills senior Haqqani militant in Afghanistan'|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> ISAF also reported that he acted as an emissary between [[Baitullah Mehsud]] and the Haqqanis.<ref name=lwj20111101 /> He was captured by ISAF forces on 27 September 2011.<ref name='npr20111001' /> He was released in a prisoner swap in November 2019.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/19/world/asia/afghanistan-taliban-prisoner-exchange-peace-talks.html</ref>\n\nFollowing [[WikiLeaks]]' July 2010 publication of 75,000 classified documents the public learned that Sirajuddin Haqqani was in the tier one of the [[International Security Assistance Force]]'s Joint Prioritized Effects List \u2013 its \"kill or capture\" list.<ref name=DerSpeigel2010-07-26>{{cite news |url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/0,1518,708393,00.html |title=The Helpless Germans: War Logs Illustrate Lack of Progress in Bundeswehr Deployment |author1=Matthias Gebauer |author2=John Goetz |author3=Hans Hoyng |author4=Susanne Koelbl |author5=Marcel Rosenbach |author6=Gregor Peter Schmitz |newspaper=[[Der Spiegel]] |date=26 July 2010 |accessdate=15 August 2010 |quote=Sirajuddin Haqqani is also associated with the foreign jihadists. Haqqani, known as 'Siraj,' is the son of the legendary Afghan mujahedeen leader [[Jalaluddin Haqqani]]. Together with the Taliban and Hekmatyar, the Haqqani clan of warlords are among the three greatest opponents of Western forces in Afghanistan. In the digital war logs, his name appeared in 'Tier 1' on a list of targets to be killed or taken captive, which qualified him as one of the Western alliance's most wanted terrorists. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100728174357/http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/0,1518,708393,00.html |archivedate=28 July 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Activities==\nAnand Gopal of the ''[[Christian Science Monitor]]'', citing unnamed US and Afghan sources, reported in June 2009 that the leadership is based in [[Miranshah]], [[North Waziristan]] in the [[Federally Administered Tribal Areas]] of Pakistan along the Afghan border.<ref name=\"CSM1\" /> It operates from at least three compounds: a Miranshah bazaar camp containing a madrassa and computer facilities, a compound in the nearby suburb of Sarai Darpa Khel and another compound in Danday Darpa Khel, where some of Jalaluddin's family stay.<ref name=fp20100603>{{cite web|url= http://afpak.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2010/06/03/inside_the_haqqani_network_0|title=Inside the Haqqani network|accessdate =23 November 2011|last=Gopal|first=Anand|author2=Mansur Khan Mahsud |author3=Brian Fishman |date=3 June 2010|work=Foreign Policy|publisher=The Slate Group, LLC}}</ref> The network is active in Afghanistan's southeastern areas of [[Paktia Province]], [[Paktika Province]], [[Khost Province]], [[Wardak Province]], [[Logar Province]], and [[Ghazni Province]].<ref name=\"CSM1\" /> In September 2011, Sirajuddin Haqqani told [[Reuters]] that the group feels \"more secure in Afghanistan besides the Afghan people.\"<ref name=\"et\" />\n\n===Publications===\nThe Haqqanis have been described as notable writers, having published a number of books as well as editing and contributing to magazines, three of them, ''Manba\u2019 al-Jihad'' (one version in Pashto and another in Arabic) and ''Nusrat al-Jihad'' (\u201cSupport for Jihad,\u201d in Urdu), totalizing more than 1000 pages between 1989 and 1993.<ref>Vahid Brown and Don Rassler, ''Fountainhead of Jihad: The Haqqani Nexus, 1973-2012'', Oxford University Press (2013), p. 14</ref>\n\n===Funding===\nSome of Sirajuddin's brothers travel to the [[Persian Gulf]] region to raise funds from wealthy donors.<ref name=fp20100603 /><ref name='et20110922' /> ''The New York Times'' reported in September 2011 that the Haqqanis have set up a \"ministate\" in Miranshah with courts, tax offices and madrassas, and that the network runs a series of front companies selling automobiles and real estate. They also receive funds from extortion, [[Child abduction|kidnappings]] and smuggling operations throughout eastern [[Afghanistan]].<ref name=fp20100603 /> In an interview a former Haqqani commander called the extortion \"the most important source of funding for the Haqqanis.\"<ref name='nytimes20110924'>{{cite news|first=Mark|last=Mazzetti |author2=Scott Shane |author3=Alissa J. Rubin |title=Brutal Haqqani Crime Clan Bedevils U.S. in Afghanistan|date=24 September 2011 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/25/world/asia/brutal-haqqani-clan-bedevils-united-states-in-afghanistan.html|work=The New York Times|accessdate=27 September 2011}}</ref> According to a tribal elder in [[Paktika Province|Paktia]], \"Haqqani's people ask for [[Afghan afghani|money]] from contractors working on road construction. They are asking [[Afghan afghani|money]] or goods from shopkeepers\u2026 District elders and contractors are paying [[Afghan afghani|money]] to Afghan workers, but sometimes half of the [[Afghan afghani|money]] will go to Haqqani's people.\"<ref name='ap20091229'>{{cite news|first=Nahal|last=Toosi|title=Haqqani network challenges US-Pakistan relations|date=29 December 2009 |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2010624388_apaspakistanhandlingthehaqqanis.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130130030439/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2010624388_apaspakistanhandlingthehaqqanis.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=30 January 2013|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=25 October 2011|work=The Seattle Times}}</ref>\n\n===Military strength===\nHaqqani is reported to run his own training camps, to recruit his own foreign fighters, and to seek out financial and logistic support on his own, from his old contacts.<ref name=\"NYTimes2008-06-17\" /> Estimates of the Haqqanis's numbers vary. A 2009 ''New York Times'' article indicates that they are thought to have about 4,000 to 12,000 Taliban under their command while a 2011 report from the [[Combating Terrorism Center]] places its strength roughly at 10,000-15,000.<ref name='rassler' /><ref name=\"nytimes 15haqqani\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/15/world/asia/15haqqani.html |title=Rebuffing U.S., Pakistan Balks at Crackdown|work=The New York Times|date=14 December 2009|first=Jane|last=Perlez}}</ref> During a September 2011 interview, Sirajuddin Haqqani said the figure of 10,000 fighters, as quoted in some media reports, \"is actually less than the actual number.\"<ref name=\"et\" /> Throughout its history the network's operations have been conducted by small, semi-autonomous units organized according to tribal and sub-tribal affiliations often at the direction of and with the logistical support of Haqqani commanders.<ref name='rassler' />\n\nThe network is comprised broadly of four groups: those who have been with Jalalludin since the Soviet-era jihad, those from [[Loya Paktiya]] who have joined since 2001, those from North Waziristan who have joined in more recent years, and foreign militants of primarily Arab, Chechen and Uzbek origins. Leadership roles are mostly filled with personnel from the first group while the relative neophytes from Loya Paktia and non-Pushtuns are not part of this inner circle.<ref name=fp20100603 /><ref name='at20111015'>{{cite news|first=Amir|last=Mir|title=Haqqanis sidestep US terror list|date=15 October 2011|url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/South_Asia/MJ15Df01.html|work=Asia Times Online| accessdate=28 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Haqqani network pioneered the use of suicide attacks in Afghanistan and tend to use mostly foreign bombers whereas the Taliban tend to rely on locals in attacks.<ref name=CSM1 /> The network, according to the ''[[National Journal]]'', supplies much of the [[potassium chlorate]] used in bombs employed by the Taliban in Afghanistan. Also, the network's bombs use more sophisticated remote triggering devices than the pressure-plated activators used elsewhere in Afghanistan. Sirajuddin Haqqani told [[MSNBC]] in April 2009 that his fighters had, \"acquired the modern technology that we were lacking, and we have mastered new and innovative methods of making bombs and explosives.\"<ref>[[Yochi Dreazen|Dreazen, Yochi J.]], \"The New Enemy\", ''[[National Journal]]'', 16 July 2011.</ref>\n\nIn late 2011, a 144-page book attributed to Sirajuddin Haqqani began circulating in Afghanistan and Pakistan. Described by ''Newsweek'' as a \"manual for guerrillas and terrorists,\" the Pashto-language book details instructions on setting up a jihadi cell, receiving financing, recruiting and training. The manual advises recruits that parental permission is not necessary for jihad, that all debts should be paid before joining, and that suicide bombings and beheadings are allowed by Islam.<ref name='db20111114'>{{cite news|first=Ron|last=Moreau|author2=Sami Yousafzai|title=Dueling Manifestos|date=14 November 2011|publisher=The Newsweek|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2011/11/13/afghanistan-haqqani-s-jihad-manual-the-secret-taliban-letter.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111114114846/http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2011/11/13/afghanistan-haqqani-s-jihad-manual-the-secret-taliban-letter.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 November 2011|work=The Daily Beast|accessdate=23 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Attacks and alleged attacks===\n* 14 January 2008: The [[2008 Kabul Serena Hotel attack]] is thought to have been carried out by the network.<ref name=\"NYTimes2008-06-17\" />\n* March 2008: Kidnapping of British journalist [[Sean Langan]] was blamed on the network.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/jun/21/new-york-times-reporter-taliban Kidnapped US reporter makes dramatic escape from Taliban], [[The Guardian]], 21 June 2009</ref>\n* 27 April 2008: [[Assassination attempts on Hamid Karzai]].<ref name=\"CSM1\" />\n* 7 July 2008: US intelligence blamed the network for [[2008 Indian embassy bombing in Kabul]].<ref name=WP1 />\n* 10 November 2008: The [[Kidnapping of David Rohde]] was blamed on Sirajuddin Haqqani.<ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/Blotter/story?id=7895078&page=1 Taliban Wanted $25 Million for Life of New York Times Reporter], [[ABC News]], 22 June 2009</ref>\n* 30 December 2009: [[Camp Chapman attack]] is thought to have been carried out by the network.<ref>[http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/31b2dd72-f898-11de-beb8-00144feab49a.html Pakistan urges united reaction after CIA blast], [[Financial Times]], 3 January 2010</ref>\n* 18 May 2010: [[May 2010 Kabul bombing]] was allegedly carried out by the network.<ref name=\"LWJ20100524\">{{cite web|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2010/05/haqqani_network_exec.php|title=Haqqani Network executed Kabul suicide attack|last=Rogio|first=Bill|date=24 May 2010|publisher=[[Public Multimedia]]|accessdate=25 May 2010}}</ref>\n* 19 February 2011: [[Kabul Bank]] in [[Jalalabad]], Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.pajhwok.com/en/2011/06/15/haqqani-network-threatens-attacks-judges|title=Haqqani network threatens attacks on judges|publisher=Pajhwok Afghan News|date=15 June 2011|accessdate=27 July 2011}}</ref>\n* 28 June 2011: According to [[ISAF]], elements of the Haqqani network provided \"material support\" in the [[Hotel Inter-Continental Kabul#2011 attack|2011 attack on the Hotel Inter-Continental]] in Kabul.<ref>[[Bill Roggio|Roggio, Bill]], \"[http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2011/06/isaf_airstrike_kills.php ISAF airstrike kills senior Haqqani Network commander involved in Kabul hotel attack]\", ''[[Long War Journal]]'', 30 June 2011.</ref> The Taliban claimed responsibility.<ref>{{cite news|first=Safeeyah|last=Kharsany|author2=Mujib Mashal|title=Manager gives account of Kabul hotel attack|date=29 June 2011|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/asia/2011/06/2011629122328109278.html|work=Al Jazeera| accessdate=15 September 2011}}</ref>\n* 10 September 2011: A massive truck bomb exploded outside Combat Outpost Sayed Abad in Wardak province, Afghanistan, killing five Afghans, including four civilians, and wounding 77 U.S. soldiers, 14 Afghan civilians, and three policemen. The Pentagon blamed the network for the attack.<ref>Jelinek, Pauline ([[Associated Press]]), \"[https://archive.today/20120717175624/http://www.armytimes.com/news/2011/09/ap-afghanistan-us-says-haqqani-behind-bombing-091211/ Haqqani group behind Afghan bombing, U.S. says]\", ''[[Military Times]]'', 12 September 2011.</ref>\n* 12 September 2011: US Ambassador [[Ryan Crocker]] blamed the Haqqani network for an attack on the US Embassy and nearby NATO bases in Kabul. The attack lasted 19 hours and resulted in the deaths of four police officers and four civilians. 17 civilians and six NATO soldiers were injured. Three coalition soldiers were killed. Eleven insurgent attackers were killed.<ref name='nyt20110914'>{{cite news|first=Alissa J|last=Rubin|author2=Ray Rivera |author3=Jack Healy |title=U.S. Blames Kabul Assault on Pakistan-Based Group|date=14 September 2011|publisher=The New York Times Company|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/15/world/asia/us-blames-kabul-assault-on-pakistan-based-group.html|work=The New York Times| accessdate=14 September 2011}}</ref>\n* October 2011: Afghanistan's [[National Directorate of Security]] said that six people arrested in an alleged plot to assassinate President Karzai had ties to the Haqqani network.<ref name='aljazeera20111005'>{{cite news|title=Six arrested over 'Karzai death plot'|date=5 October 2011|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/asia/2011/10/2011105125621748395.html| work=Al Jazeera|accessdate=12 October 2011}}</ref>\n* 15 April 2012: Haqqani network fighters initiate the summer fighting season, conducting a complex attack across Kabul, Logar and Paktia provinces.  Several western embassies in Kabul were attacked in the Say Wallah district.\n* 1 June 2012: A massive suicide truck bomb breaches the southern perimeter wall of US [[Forward Operating Base Salerno]] in Khost province.  A dozen Haqqani fighters wearing suicide vests entered the breach, but were isolated and killed by US Forces.\n* 31 May 2017: [[May 2017 Kabul attack|a truck bomb exploded]] in a crowded intersection in [[Kabul]], Afghanistan, near the German embassy,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-40102903 |title=Kabul bomb: Dozens killed in Afghan capital's diplomatic zone |date=31 May 2017 |work=BBC News |access-date=31 May 2017 |language=en-GB |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531060542/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-40102903 |archivedate=31 May 2017 }}</ref> killing over 150 and injuring 413,<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/31/world/asia/kabul-explosion-afghanistan.html |title=Huge Bombing in Kabul Is One of Afghan War\u2019s Worst |last=Mashal |first=Mujib |date=31 May 2017 |work=The New York Times |access-date=31 May 2017 |last2=Abed |first2=Fahim |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531053728/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/31/world/asia/kabul-explosion-afghanistan.html |archivedate=31 May 2017 }}</ref> mostly civilians, and damaging several buildings in the embassy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tolonews.com/afghanistan/rs-claims-police-stopped-truck-entering-green-zone |title=RS Claims Police Stopped Truck From Entering Green Zone |publisher=Tolonews |accessdate=31 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531111332/http://www.tolonews.com/afghanistan/rs-claims-police-stopped-truck-entering-green-zone |archivedate=31 May 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.rt.com/news/390254-afghan-blast-kabul-embassies/ |title=Kabul blast: At least 80 killed & over 350 wounded in explosion in Afghan capital\u2019s embassy district |work=RT International |access-date=31 May 2017 |language=en-US |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531091216/https://www.rt.com/news/390254-afghan-blast-kabul-embassies/ |archivedate=31 May 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/31/asia/kabul-explosion-hits-diplomatic-area/index.html |title=Afghanistan explosion: 80 killed in blast near diplomatic area |author1=Ehsan Popalzai |author2=Faith Karimi |website=CNN |access-date=31 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531061825/http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/31/asia/kabul-explosion-hits-diplomatic-area/index.html |archivedate=31 May 2017 }}</ref> The attack was the deadliest terror attack to take place in Kabul. Afghanistan's intelligence agency [[National Directorate of Security|NDS]] claimed that the blast was planned by the Haqqani Network.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kabul bomb: Afghans blame Haqqani and Pakistan|url=http://news.sky.com/story/kabul-bombing-afghans-blame-haqqani-network-and-pakistan-10900078|website=Sky News}}</ref><ref name=\"Gul\">{{cite web|last1=Gul|first1=Ayaz|title=Deadly Truck Bomb Rocks Kabul|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/massive-car-bomb-in-kabul/3878752.html|website=VOA|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nThe Haqqani network operates in the Federally Administered Tribal Areas (FATA) in Northern Pakistan, near the southeastern border of Afghanistan.<ref>\"Threat Convergence Profile Series: The Haqqani Network.\"</ref><ref>Lawrence, Kendall. \"Threat Convergence Profile Series: The Haqqani Network.\" The Fund For Peace. June 2010. p. 3. <http://www.fundforpeace.org/global/library/ttcvr1127-threatconvergence-haqqani-11b.pdf {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140726005609/http://www.fundforpeace.org/global/library/ttcvr1127-threatconvergence-haqqani-11b.pdf |date=26 July 2014 }}</ref> The network has used the ambiguity of the FATA to cloak its activities and avoid interference. The strategy worked well until President Obama ramped up [[UAV]] strikes in the Northern Waziristan region. The organizational headquarters is supposedly in Miram Shah, where the group operates base camps to facilitate activities such as weapons acquisitions, logistical planning and military strategy formulation. Haqqani-controlled regions of northern Pakistan have also served as strategic safe-havens for other Islamic militant organizations, such as [[Al-Qaeda]], the [[Pakistani Taliban]] (TTP), [[Jaish-e-Mohammad]] (JeM), [[Lashkar-e-Taiba]] (LeT), and members of the [[Islamic Movement of Uzbekistan]] (IMU). The strategic location of the Haqqani network facilitates interaction between many of the insurgent groups. <ref>\"Inside the Haqqani Network.\"</ref><ref>\"Inside the Haqqani Network.\" Foreign Policy Group. 3 June 2010. <http:b//afpak.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2010/06/03/inside_the_haqqani_network_0</ref>\n\n[[File:ISAF image Insurgent Routes.jpg|Insurgent Routes of Infiltration from training camps in Pakistan|thumb|right|upright=2.0]]\n\nThe Haqqani network's tribal connections in Northern Waziristan and the de facto regime that it has established with courts, law enforcement, medical care, and governance have often brought it great support from locals.<ref name=\"Brown, V. 2012\" /> Its familiarity of terrain, such as mountain passes, also grants them excellent access between Afghanistan and Pakistan.\n\nIn September 2011, Sirajuddin Haqqani claimed during a telephonic interview to [[Reuters]] that the Haqqani network no longer maintained sanctuaries in northwestern Pakistan and the robust presence that it once had there and instead now felt safer in Afghanistan: \"Gone are the days when we were hiding in the mountains along the Pakistan-Afghanistan border. Now we consider ourselves more secure in Afghanistan besides the Afghan people.\"<ref name=\"et\">{{cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/254368/no-haqqani-network-sanctuaries-in-pakistan-sirajuddin/|title=No sanctuaries in Pakistan\u2019: Haqqani network shifts base to Afghanistan|work=Express Tribune|date=18 September 2011|accessdate=20 September 2011}}</ref> According to Haqqani, there were \"senior military and police officials\" who are aligned with the group and there are even sympathetic and \"sincere people in the Afghan government who are loyal to the Taliban\" who support the group's aim of liberating Afghanistan \"from the clutches of occupying forces.\"<ref name=\"et\" /> In response to questions from the BBC's Pashto service, Siraj denied any links to the ISI and stated that Mullah Omar is \"our leader and we totally obey him.\"<ref name='bbc20111003'>{{cite news|title=Haqqani network denies killing Afghan envoy Rabbani|date=3 October 2010|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-15143513|work=BBC|accessdate=3 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Alleged Pakistani involvement==\n{{See also|Pakistan\u2013United States relations}}\nWhile some Afghan and American officials accuse Pakistan of harboring the Haqqani network, Pakistan has denied any links.<ref>{{cite news|title=What Is the Haqqani Network?|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/what-haqqani-network/3883271.html}}</ref>\n\nAbdul Rashid Waziri, a specialist at Kabul's Center for Regional Studies of Afghanistan, explains that links between the Haqqani network and Pakistan can be traced back to the mid-1970s,<ref name=\"ISN\" /> before the 1978 [[Saur Revolution|Marxist revolution]] in [[Kabul]]. During the rule of President [[Mohammed Daoud Khan|Daoud Khan]] in Afghanistan (1973\u201378), [[Jalaluddin Haqqani]] went into exile and based himself in and around [[Miranshah]], Pakistan.<ref name='iswprofile'>{{cite web |url=http://www.understandingwar.org/themenode/haqqani-network|title=Haqqani Network|accessdate=17 October 2011|publisher=The [[Institute for the Study of War]]}}</ref> From there he began to form a rebellion against the government of Daoud Khan in 1975.<ref name=\"ISN\" /> The network allegedly maintains ties with the [[Inter-Services Intelligence]] (ISI), and Pakistan's army had been reportedly reluctant to move against them in the past.<ref name=NYTimes2008-06-17 /><ref name=\"nytimes080909\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/09/world/asia/09iht-09pstan.15996896.html|title=U.S. attack on Taliban kills 23 in Pakistan|work=The New York Times|date=9 September 2008|accessdate=27 July 2011|first1=Jane|last1=Perlez}}</ref>\n\nHowever, recently there has been a paradigm shift within the Pakistani military and as of 2014 a massive military offensive launched in North Waziristan, named [[Operation Zarb-e-Azb]] has targeted all militants including the Haqqanni network. The operation is currently on-going and is commanded by General Qamar Javed Bajwa.<ref name=\"Express News\">{{cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/786641/us-commander-commends-zarb-e-azb-for-disrupting-haqqani-networks-ability-to-target-afghanistan/|title=US commander commends Zarb-e-Azb for disrupting Haqqani network's ability to target Afghanistan|work=Express News|date=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n''The New York Times'' reported in September 2008 that Pakistan regards the Haqqani as an important force for protecting its interests in Afghanistan in the event of American withdrawal from there and therefore is unwilling to move against them.<ref name=\"nytimes080909\" /> Pakistan presumably{{by whom|date=October 2011}} feels pressured that India, Russia, and Iran are gaining a foothold in Afghanistan. Since it lacks the financial clout of the other countries, Pakistan hopes that by being a sanctuary for the Haqqani network, it can assert some influence over its turbulent neighbor. In the words of a retired senior Pakistani official: \"[We] have no money. All we have are the crazies. So the crazies it is.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Snake country|url=http://www.economist.com/node/21531042|accessdate=8 January 2013|newspaper=The Economist|date=1 October 2011|location=Islamabad}}</ref> ''The New York Times'' and [[Al Jazeera]] later reported in June 2010 that Pakistan's Army chief General [[Ashfaq Parvez Kayani]] and chief of the ISI General [[Ahmad Shuja Pasha]] were in talks with Afghan President [[Hamid Karzai]] to broker a power-sharing agreement between the Haqqani network and the Afghan government.<ref name=\"nyt20100624\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/25/world/asia/25islamabad.html|title=Pakistan Is Said to Pursue Foothold in Afghanistan|last=Perlez|first=Jane|author2=Gall, Carlotta|date=24 June 2010|work=The New York Times|accessdate=29 June 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"aje20100628\">{{cite web|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/asia/2010/06/20106277582708497.html|title=Karzai 'holds talks' with Haqqani|date=28 June 2010|publisher=[[Al Jazeera English]]|accessdate=29 June 2010}}</ref> Reacting to this report both President [[Barack Obama]] and CIA director [[Leon Panetta]] responded with skepticism that such an effort could succeed.<ref name=\"nyt20100627\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/28/world/asia/28taliban.html|title=Pakistan\u2019s Plan on Afghan Peace Leaves U.S. Wary| last=Shane| first=Scott|date=27 June 2010|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=29 June 2010}}</ref> The effort to mediate between the Haqqanis and the Afghan government was launched by Pakistan after intense pressure by the US to take military action against the group in [[North Waziristan]].<ref name=\"dawn20100616\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/wps/wcm/connect/dawn-content-library/dawn/the-newspaper/front-page/35-Pakistan-trying-to-broker-Afghan-deal-ak-03 |title=Pakistan trying to broker Afghan deal |last=Syed |first=Baqir Sajjad |date=16 June 2010 |publisher=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]] |accessdate=29 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619081056/http://www.dawn.com/wps/wcm/connect/dawn-content-library/dawn/the-newspaper/front-page/35-Pakistan-trying-to-broker-Afghan-deal-ak-03 |archivedate=19 June 2010}}</ref> Karzai later denied meeting anyone from the Haqqani network.<ref name=\"afp20100629\">{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5iZlFFvVcAbhdUv3PV9UHCLH4FBnQ|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130125034721/http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5iZlFFvVcAbhdUv3PV9UHCLH4FBnQ|url-status=dead|archive-date=25 January 2013|title=Kabul dismisses report Karzai met militant leader|date=29 June 2010|publisher=[[Agence France-Presse]]| accessdate=30 June 2010}}</ref> Subsequently, Kayani also denied that he took part in the talks.<ref name=\"dawn20100702\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/wps/wcm/connect/dawn-content-library/dawn/the-newspaper/front-page/kayani-says-he-did-not-broker-karzais-talks-with-haqqani-270 |title=Kayani says he did not broker Karzai\u2019s talks with Haqqani |date=2 July 2010 |work=Dawn |accessdate=2 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100703231827/http://www.dawn.com/wps/wcm/connect/dawn-content-library/dawn/the-newspaper/front-page/kayani-says-he-did-not-broker-karzais-talks-with-haqqani-270 |archivedate=3 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nAnti-American groups of [[Gul Bahadur]] and Haqqani carry out their activities in Afghanistan and use North [[Waziristan]] as rear.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://outlookafghanistan.net/topics?post_id=669 |title=Militant Networks in North Waziristan |publisher=OutlookAfghanistan.net |date=26 May 2011 |accessdate=27 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723235021/http://outlookafghanistan.net/topics?post_id=669 |archivedate=23 July 2011 }}</ref> The group's links to Pakistan have been a sour point in [[Pakistan \u2013 United States relations]]. In September 2011, the [[Obama administration]] warned Pakistan that it must do more to cut ties with the Haqqani network and help eliminate its leaders, adding that \"the United States will act unilaterally if Pakistan does not comply.\"<ref name='wapo20110921'>{{cite news| first=Karen|last=DeYoung|title=U.S. sharpens warning to Pakistan|date=21 September 2011|url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-sharpens-warning-to-pakistan/2011/09/20/gIQAdqlNjK_story.html?wpisrc=al_national|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=21 September 2011}}</ref> In testimony before a [[US Senate]] panel, Admiral [[Mike Mullen]] stated that the network \"acts as a veritable arm of Pakistan's [[Inter-Services Intelligence Agency]].\"<ref name='bbc20110922b'>{{cite news|title=Pakistan 'backed Haqqani attack on Kabul' \u2013 Mike Mullen|date=22 September 2011|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-15024344|work=BBC|accessdate=22 September 2011}}</ref> Although some U.S. officials allege that the ISI supports and guides the Haqqanis,<ref name='bbc20110922b' /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.yahoo.com/pakistan-condemns-us-comments-spy-agency-044440789.html;_ylt=A2KJ3vVYX3xOdRkA9EZXNyoA?rnd=005681253004174930714413 |title=Pakistan condemns US comments about spy agency |agency=Associated Press |date=23 September 2011 |accessdate=23 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130727053454/http://news.yahoo.com/pakistan-condemns-us-comments-spy-agency-044440789.html;_ylt=A2KJ3vVYX3xOdRkA9EZXNyoA?rnd=005681253004174930714413 |archivedate=27 July 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2011/09/18/clinton-presses-pakistan-to-help-fight-haqqani-insurgent-group/|title=Clinton Presses Pakistan to Help Fight Haqqani Insurgent Group|publisher=Fox News|date=18 September 2011|accessdate=21 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=US-blames-Pakistan>{{cite news|url=https://news.yahoo.com/pakistan-isi-urged-attacks-u-targets-officials-002201562.html |title=U.S. blames Pakistan agency in Kabul attack |publisher=Reuters |date=22 September 2011 |accessdate=22 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110925075845/http://news.yahoo.com/pakistan-isi-urged-attacks-u-targets-officials-002201562.html |archivedate=25 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/09/17/us-pakistan-usa-haqqani-idUSTRE78G1RM20110917|title=U.S. links Pakistan to group it blames for Kabul attack|date=17 September 2011|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=21 September 2011}}</ref> President [[Barack Obama]] declined to endorse that position and stated that \"the intelligence is not as clear as we might like in terms of what exactly that relationship is\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/world/obama-wont-back-mullens-claim-on-pakistan-137813|title=Obama won't back Mullen's claim on Pakistan|date=1 October 2011|work=NDTV|accessdate=20 May 2015}}</ref> and [[US Secretary of State]] [[Hillary Clinton]] said \"We have no evidence of\" Pakistani involvement in attacks on the [[Embassy of the United States, Kabul|US embassy in Kabul]].<ref>[https://archive.today/20111023235027/http://www.dawn.com/2011/10/22/pakistan-urged-to-play-role-of-peacemaker-clinton-demands-action-in-days-and-weeks-2.html Clinton demands action in \u2018days and weeks\u2019]</ref>\n\nPakistan in return rejected the notion that it maintained ties with the Haqqani network or used it in a policy of waging a [[proxy war]] in neighboring Afghanistan. Pakistani officials deny the allegations by asserting that Pakistan had no relations with the network. In response to the allegations, [[Ministry of Interior (Pakistan)|Interior Minister]] [[Rehman Malik]] claimed that the [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA) had \"trained and produced\" the Haqqani network and other [[mujahideen]] during the [[Soviet\u2013Afghan War]].<ref name=\"TOI\">{{cite news|title=Defiant Pak refuses to go after Haqqanis| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-09-27/pakistan/30207711_1_haqqani-network-pakistan-army-north-waziristan| archive-url=https://archive.today/20130127001651/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-09-27/pakistan/30207711_1_haqqani-network-pakistan-army-north-waziristan| url-status=dead| archive-date=27 January 2013|work=Times of India|date=27 September 2011|accessdate=27 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"dawn\">{{cite news|title=CIA created Haqqani network: Rehman Malik|url=http://www.dawn.com/2011/09/25/cia-created-haqqani-network-rehman-malik.html|date=25 September 2011|work=Dawn|accessdate=26 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"tribune\">{{cite news|title=Haqqani network created by the CIA: Rehman Malik|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/260065/haqqani-network-created-by-the-cia-rehman-malik/|date=25 September 2011|work=Tribune|accessdate=26 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"thenews\">{{cite news|title=CIA, not Pakistan, created Haqqani network: Malik|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/TodaysPrintDetail.aspx?ID=9102&Cat=13|date=26 September 2011|publisher=The News|accessdate=26 September 2011}}</ref> The Pakistani interior minister also warned that any incursion on Pakistani territory by U.S. forces will not be tolerated. A Pakistani intelligence official insisted that the American allegations are part of \"pressure tactics\" used by the United States as a strategy \"to shift the war theatre.\"<ref name=tribune20110923>{{cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/257977/pakistan-warns-us-no-boots-on-our-ground/|title=Brittle relations: Islamabad \u2018vehemently\u2019 rejects US \u2018proxy war\u2019 claims|work=Express Tribune|date=22 September 2011|accessdate=23 September 2011}}</ref> An unnamed Pakistani official was reported to have said after a meeting of the nation's top military officials that \"We have already conveyed to the US that Pakistan cannot go beyond what it has already done\".<ref>Zirulnick, Ariel. [http://www.csmonitor.com/World/terrorism-security/2011/0926/Pakistan-refuses-to-battle-Haqqani-network \"Pakistan refuses to battle Haqqani network.\"] ''[[The Christian Science Monitor]]'', 26 September 2011.</ref> However, Pakistani claims were contradicted by the network's warnings against any U.S. military incursions into [[North Waziristan]].<ref name=\"TOI\" /><ref name=\"tribune\" /> However a month after the allegation, ties improved slightly and the US asked Pakistan to assist it in starting negotiation talks with the [[Taliban]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/NewsDetail.aspx?ID=25732|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120913005136/http://www.thenews.com.pk/NewsDetail.aspx?ID=25732|url-status=dead|archive-date=13 September 2012|title=US seeks Pak aid in peace efffort|date=31 October 2011|work=The News International, Pakistan|accessdate=20 May 2015}}</ref> In 2014, the Pakistani Armed Forces launched a major offensive [[Operation Zarb-e-Azb]] in North Waziristan aimed at displacing all militants foreign and domestic, including the Haqqani network from its soil. The operation is currently ongoing.\n\n==Opponents==\n===ISAF Military offensives===\nIn July 2008, Jalaluddin's son Omar Haqqani was killed in a firefight with coalition forces in Paktia.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080924043949/http://www.thenews.com.pk/print3.asp?id=15932 Haqqani\u2019s son killed in Paktia], ''[[The News International]]'', 11 July 2008</ref> In September 2008, [[Daande Darpkhel airstrike]] drones fired six missiles at the home of the Haqqanis and a [[madrasah]] run by the network. However both Jalaluddin and Sirajuddin were not present though several family members were killed.<ref name=WP1>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/09/08/AR2008090800263.html U.S. Missiles Said To Kill 20 in Pakistan Near Afghan Border], [[The Washington Post]], 9 September 2008</ref> Among 23 people killed was one of Jalaluddin's two wives, sister, sister-in-law and eight of his grandchildren.<ref name=\"nytimes080909\" /> In March 2009, the US State Department announced a reward of $5 million for information leading to the location, arrest, or conviction of Sirajuddin under the [[Rewards for Justice Program]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2009/03/120864.htm|title=Rewards For Justice: Sirajuddin Haqqani|publisher=U.S. State Department|date=14 January 2008|accessdate=27 July 2011}}</ref> In May 2010, US senator and [[United States Senate Select Committee on Intelligence]] Chair [[Dianne Feinstein]] wrote to [[United States Secretary of State]] [[Hillary Clinton]] urging her to add the Haqqani network to [[U.S. State Department list of Foreign Terrorist Organizations]].<ref name=\"AFP20100513\">{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5h5i-QzMfNV5Em8FX2BRBWDhUIQOQ|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100517152313/http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5h5i-QzMfNV5Em8FX2BRBWDhUIQOQ|url-status=dead|archive-date=17 May 2010|title=US Senator: Label Pakistan Taliban, Haqqani, as terrorists|date=13 May 2010|publisher=[[Agence France-Presse]]|accessdate=25 May 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nISAF and Afghan forces killed a network leader, Fazil Subhan, plus an unknown number of Haqqani militiamen, in a raid in [[Khost]] in the second week of June 2010. In a press release, ISAF reported that Subhan helped facilitate the movement of Al-Qaeda fighters into Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite web|last=Roggio|first=Bill|title=US, Afghan Forces Kill Haqqani Network Commander During Raid In Khost|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2010/06/us_afghan_forces_kil_1.php|work=Long War Journal|date=14 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.isaf.nato.int/article/isaf-releases/afghan-international-force-clears-haqqani-stronghold.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120129064954/http://www.isaf.nato.int/article/isaf-releases/afghan-international-force-clears-haqqani-stronghold.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=29 January 2012|title=Afghan, International Force Clears Haqqani Stronghold|accessdate= 22 September 2011|date=14 June 2010|publisher=ISAF}}</ref>\n\nIn late July 2011, U.S. and [[Afghan National Army#Special Forces|Afghan special forces]] killed dozens of insurgents during an operation in eastern [[Paktika province]] to clear a training camp the Haqqani network used for foreign (Arab and Chechen) fighters; reports of the number killed varied, with one source saying \"more than 50\"<ref name=\"reuters2011\" /> to \"nearly 80\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://security.blogs.cnn.com/2011/07/26/rare-glimpse-into-u-s-special-operations-forces-in-afghanistan/|title=Rare glimpse into U.S. special operations forces in Afghanistan|publisher=CNN |work=Security Clearance (blog)|date=26 July 2011|accessdate=27 July 2011|quote=U.S. and Afghan troops attacked an insurgent encampment, killing nearly 80 foreign fighters\u2026. The camp they attacked and the fighters there were part of the so-called Haqqanni network, which is responsible for many recent attacks in Afghanistan and is closely tied to al Qaeda. The Haqqanis traditionally rely on Afghan and Pakistani fighters, but in this instance most of the fighters there who were killed were Arabs and Chechens, brought into Afghanistan from Pakistan.}}</ref> Disenfranchised insurgents told security forces where the camp was located, the coalition said.<ref name=\"reuters2011\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/07/22/us-afghanistan-violence-idUSTRE76L36220110722|title=NATO kills 50 fighters, clears Afghan training camp|publisher=Reuters|first=Michelle |last=Nichols|date=22 July 2011|accessdate=23 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 October 2011, NATO announced the capture of Haji Mali Khan, \"the senior Haqqani commander in Afghanistan,\" during an operation in Jani Khel district of Afghanistan's Paktia province. Taliban spokesman [[Zabiullah Mujahid]] denied that the capture occurred while Haqqani network members declined to respond to the announcement.<ref name='ft20111001' /><ref name='npr20111001' />\n\nAccording to an unnamed Pakistani official a US drone strike on a compound killed [[Jan Baz Zadran|Jamil Haqqani]], an \"important Afghan commander of Haqqani network\" responsible for logistics in North Waziristan, on 13 October 2011. Three other network fighters were also killed in the two missile blasts. The compound was located in Dandey Darpakhel village, about 7&nbsp;km (4 miles) north of Miranshah.<ref name='et20111013'>{{cite news|title=US drones strike in North, South Waziristan|date=13 October 2011| publisher=The Express Tribune News Network|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/273122/us-drone-strike-kills-four-in-n-waziristan-2/|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=13 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-October 2011, Afghan and NATO forces launched \"Operation Shamshir\" and \"Operation Knife Edge\" against the Haqqani network in south-eastern Afghanistan, with the intent to counter possible security threats in the border regions. An ISAF spokesman said that Operation Shamshir \"was aimed at securing key population centers and expanding the Kabul security zone,\"<ref name='aljazeera20111025'>{{cite news|first=Mujib|last=Mashal|title=Afghan forces target Haqqani strongholds|date=25 October 2011|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/asia/2011/10/2011102415575819318.html|work=Al Jazeera|accessdate=26 October 2011}}</ref> while [[Ministry of Defense (Afghanistan)|Afghan Defense Minister]], [[Abdul Rahim Wardak]], explained that Operation Knife Edge would \"help eliminate the insurgents before they struck in areas along the troubled frontier.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pajhwok.com/en/2011/10/18/push-launched-against-haqqanis-border-areas|title=Push launched against Haqqanis in border areas|work=pajhwok.com|accessdate=20 May 2015}}</ref> The two operations ended on 23 October 2011 and at least 20 insurgents, of the some 200 killed or captured, had ties to the Haqqani network according to ISAF.<ref name=Riechmann>[https://news.yahoo.com/nato-200-afghan-militants-killed-captured-074709256.html NATO: 200 Afghan militants killed, captured] by Deb Riechmann. 24 October 2011.</ref><ref name='aljazeera20111025' />\n\nOn 2 November 2011, ''The Express Tribune'' reported that the Pakistani Army had agreed with the United States to restrict the network's movement along the Afghan border in exchange for America dropping its demands for a full-scale offensive. The report emerged soon after a visit by Hillary Clinton to Pakistan.<ref name='et20111102'>{{cite news|first=Kamran |last=Yousaf|title=Pakistan looks to restrict Haqqanis\u2019 movement|date=2 November 2011|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/286354/pakistan-looks-to-restrict-haqqanis-movement/?cid=nlc-dailybrief-daily_news_brief-link19-20111102|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=3 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nCurtis M. Scaparrotti, commander of International Security Assistance Force Joint Command, has said that Haqqani can be defeated through a combination of a layered defense in Afghanistan and interdiction against the sanctuaries in Pakistan.<ref>Marshall, Tyrone C. Jr. [https://web.archive.org/web/20120205070511/http://www.defense.gov/News/NewsArticle.aspx?ID=65845 \"Objectives Achievable Despite Pakistan Sanctuaries, General Says.\"] ''American Forces Press Service'', 27 October 2011.</ref>\n\nIn June 2014 a drone attack reportedly killed 10 members of the Haqqani network including a high-level commander, Haji Gul, in the country's tribal area of North Waziristan. The Pakistan government publicly condemned the attack, but according to a government official had privately approved it.<ref name=\"HaqqaniDrone\">{{cite news|title=Controversial US drone attack in Pakistan, 16 killed|url=http://www.pakistannews.net/index.php/sid/222852683/scat/8c3d7d78943a99c7/ht/Controversial-US-drone-attack-in-Pakistan-16-killed|archive-url=https://archive.today/20140615080349/http://www.pakistannews.net/index.php/sid/222852683/scat/8c3d7d78943a99c7/ht/Controversial-US-drone-attack-in-Pakistan-16-killed|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 June 2014|accessdate=12 June 2014|publisher=Pakistan News.Net}}</ref>\n\n===Pakistani military offensive===\nIn 2014, the Pakistani Armed Forces launched a major offensive [[Operation Zarb-e-Azb]] in North Waziristan aimed at displacing all militants foreign and domestic, including the Haqqani network from its soil. On 5 November 2014, Lt. Gen. Joseph Anderson, a senior commander for US and Nato forces in Afghanistan, said in a Pentagon-hosted video briefing from Afghanistan that the Haqqani network is now \"fractured\" like the Taliban. \"They are fractured. They are fractured like the Taliban is. That's based pretty much on the Pakistan's operations in North Waziristan this entire summer-fall,\" he said, acknowledging the effectiveness of Pakistan's military offensive. \"That has very much disrupted their efforts in Afghanistan and has caused them to be less effective in terms of their ability to pull off an attack in Kabul,\" Anderson added. The operation is currently ongoing.<ref name=OperationZarb>{{cite news|title=Operation Zarb-i-Azb disrupted Haqqani network: US general|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1142664/|date=6 November 2014|work=Dawn|accessdate=7 November 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106124030/http://www.dawn.com/news/1142664|archivedate=6 November 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Sanctions===\nUntil 1 November 2011, six Haqqani network commanders were designated as terrorists under [[Executive Order 13224]] since 2008 and their assets were frozen while prohibiting others from engaging in financial transactions with them:<ref name=lwj20111101>{{cite web|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2011/11/us_adds_senior_haqqa.php|title=US adds senior Haqqani Network leader to terrorist list|work=The Long War Journal|accessdate=20 May 2015}}</ref>\n* In March 2008, the US State Department designated Sirajuddin Haqqani a terrorist and a year later issued a $5 million bounty for information leading to his capture.<ref name=lwj20111101 />\n* The State Department placed Nasiruddin Haqqani on its list of terrorists in July 2010.<ref name=lwj20111101 />\n* In February 2011, Khalil al Rahman Haqqani was designated a terrorist by the US State Department.<ref name=lwj20111101 />\n* In an effort to stop the flow of funds to the network, the US State Department announced on 16 August 2011 measures against [[Sangeen Zadran]] as \"Shadow Governor for [[Paktika Province]], [[Afghanistan]] and a commander of the Haqqani Network.\" The US designated Zadran under Executive Order 13224 while the United Nations listed him under [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1988|Security Council Resolution 1988]].<ref name='afp20110816'>{{cite news|title=US tries to stem funds to Haqqani network commander|date=16 August 2011|publisher=AFP|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/232918/us-tries-to-stem-funds-to-haqqani-network-commander/|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=17 August 2011}}</ref><ref name='state20110816'>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2011/08/170582.htm|title=Designation of Haqqani Network Commander Sangeen Zadran|accessdate=17 August 2011|date=16 August 2011|publisher=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n* The U.S. Department of Treasury added Abdul Aziz Abbasin, \"a key commander in the Haqqani Network\", to the list of individuals on the executive order in September 2011.<ref name='treasury20110929' /><ref name=lwj20111101 />\n* On 1 November 2011, Haji Mali Khan, who was already in ISAF custody, was added to the list.<ref name=lwj20111101 />\n\nIn September 2011, the US [[Senate Appropriations Committee]] voted to make a $1 billion counter-insurgency aid package to the Pakistani military conditional upon Pakistani action against militant groups, including the Haqqani network. The decision would still need to receive approval from the [[US House of Representatives]] and the [[US Senate]].<ref name='bbc20110922'>{{cite news|title=US senators link Pakistan aid to Haqqani crackdown|date=22 September 2011|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-15014800|work=BBC|accessdate=22 September 2011}}</ref> According to the press release, \"[t]he bill includes strengthened restrictions on assistance for Pakistan by conditioning all funds to the Government of Pakistan on cooperation against the Haqqani network, al Qaeda, and other terrorist organizations, with a waiver, and funding based on achieving benchmarks.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://appropriations.senate.gov/news.cfm?method=news.view&id=3105a024-f546-4e7a-9931-7b95ad620dba|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926051438/http://appropriations.senate.gov/news.cfm?method=news.view&id=3105a024-f546-4e7a-9931-7b95ad620dba|url-status=dead|archive-date=26 September 2011|title=Summary: FY12 State, Foreign Operations Appropriations Bill|accessdate=22 September 2011|date=21 September 2011|publisher=U.S. Senate Committee on Appropriations|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 September 2012, the Obama administration blacklisted the group as a [[foreign terrorist organization]]. The decision was mandated by Congress and was a source of debate within the administration.<ref name=nytimes20120907>{{cite news|last=Schmitt|first=Eric|title=U.S. Backs Blacklisting Militant Organization|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/07/world/asia/white-house-backs-blacklisting-militant-organization.html?_r=1&emc=na|work=The New York Times|accessdate=7 September 2012|date=6 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"aljazeera20120907\">{{cite news| url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia/2012/09/201297134941881703.html|title=US designates Haqqani group as 'terrorists'|agency=Al Jazeera|date=7 September 2012|accessdate=7 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"wapo20120907\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/haqqani-network-to-be-designated-a-terrorist-group/2012/09/07/e6576ac0-f8f6-11e1-a073-78d05495927c_story.html|title=Haqqani network to be designated a terrorist group|work=The Washington Post|date=7 September 2012|accessdate=7 September 2012|author=DeYoung, Karen}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 November 2012, the United Nations Security Council added the network to a [[blacklist]] of Taliban-related groups.<ref name=\"bbc20121105\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-20214211 |title=UN adds Haqqani network to Taliban sanctions list |publisher=BBC News |date=5 November 2012 |accessdate=6 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 May 2013 the government of Canada listed it as a terror group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.publicsafety.gc.ca/cnt/ntnl-scrt/cntr-trrrsm/lstd-ntts/crrnt-lstd-ntts-eng.aspx#2011|title=About the listing process|accessdate=20 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015 the UK proscribed the Haqqani network as a terror group.<ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/509003/20160318proscription.pdf PROSCRIBED TERRORIST ORGANISATIONS] UK Home Office.</ref>\n\n===Attempts to negotiate===\nUS officials confirmed that they held preliminary talks during the summer of 2011 with representatives of the militant network at the request of the ISI. Secretary of State Hillary Clinton said that the US had reached out to the Haqqanis to gauge their willingness to engage in a peace process and that \"Pakistani government officials helped to facilitate such a meeting.\"<ref name='bbc20111021'>{{cite news|title=Hillary Clinton: US held meeting with Haqqani network|date=21 October 2011|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-15399820|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=22 October 2011}}</ref> ''The New York Times'' reported that talks secretly began in late August 2011 in the [[United Arab Emirates]] between a midlevel American diplomat and Ibrahim Haqqani, Jalalludin's brother. Gen. [[Ahmed Shuja Pasha]], head of the ISI, brokered the discussion, but little resulted from the meeting.<ref name='nytimes20111030'>{{cite news|first=Eric|last=Schmitt|author2=David E. Sanger|title=U.S. Seeks Aid From Pakistan in Peace Effort|date=30 October 2011 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/31/world/asia/united-states-seeks-pakistan-spy-agencys-help-for-afghan-talks.html|work=The New York Times|accessdate=31 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Drone strikes in Pakistan]]\n* [[Hafiz Gul Bahadur]]\n* [[International Security Assistance Force]]\n* [[War in North-West Pakistan]]\n* [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n* [[Bowe Bergdahl]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite book| last=Vahid Brown |first=Don Rassler|title=Fountainhead of Jihad: The Haqqani Nexus, 1973\u20132012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |date=1 February 2013 |edition=1|page=320|isbn=978-0-19-932798-0}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/para/haqqani.htm Haqqani Network], GlobalSecurity.org\n* [http://www.understandingwar.org/themenode/haqqani-network Haqqani Network], [[Institute for the Study of War]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090330072513/http://www.rewardsforjustice.net/index.cfm?page=haqqani Sirajuddin Haqqani], [[Rewards for Justice Program]]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-14912957 Haqqanis: Growth of a militant network], ''[[BBC News]]'', 14 September 2011\n* [https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE60622S20100107 Q&A: Who are the Haqqanis?], ''[[Reuters]]''\n* {{NYTtopic|organizations/h/haqqani_network}}\n* [http://www.ctc.usma.edu/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/CTC_Haqqani_Network_Financing-Report__Final.pdf Haqqani Network Financing: The Evolution of an Industry] \u2013 The Combating Terrorism Center at West Point, July 2012\n* [http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/NSAEBB/NSAEBB389/ The Haqqani History: Bin Ladin's Advocate inside the Taliban] \u2013 National Security Archive Electronic Briefing Book, 11 September 2012\n{{Taliban}}\n{{Militant Islamism in South Asia}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n\n[[Category:Afghanistan\u2013Pakistan relations]]\n[[Category:Anti-Soviet factions in the Soviet\u2013Afghan War]]\n[[Category:Organizations designated as terrorist in Asia]]\n[[Category:Jihadist groups in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Jihadist groups in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Pakistan\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:Modern history of Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Organizations designated as terrorist by the United States]]\n[[Category:Taliban]]\n[[Category:War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:Waziristan]]\n[[Category:Organisations designated as terrorist by the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Organizations designated as terrorist by Canada]]\n", "name_user": "Coltsfan", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haqqani_network"}
